[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ Welcome to my course on the Von Hennig-Schara Gambit! I will immediately start by saying that I will call it  the Schara Gambit from now on, making it an easier task for you to study my course.My name is Max Warmerdam and I am a Dutch Grandmaster. 2021 was clearly the best year of my chess career so far, as I obtained the Grandmaster title at the start, and finished the year by crossing 2600 and winning the Dutch Championship. My seconding career started as well, as I started to work for Jorden van Foreest and Anish Giri for the first time. In between I even found time to create my first Chessable course!Back in December 2020 when I was asked by Jorden van Foreest to be his second for the 2021 Tata Steel Tournament, we were trying to create his repertoire for the tournament. Although all that I had read about the Schara Gambit was that it was a rather dubious gambit, a devil on my shoulder was telling me that it was more or less fine these days. It is up to this day not entirely clear why I was thinking that, but I proposed the gambit to Jorden.When we started to analyse it, it turned out that the Schara Gambit was actually in good shape due to improvements for Black in a few important positions. This development is partially due to the modern engines based on neural networks. If you have studied the AlphaZero games that were played in the matches against Stockfish, you may have noticed that it had a very good  understanding of long-term compensation. And that is what the Schara Gambit is all about: long-term compensation for the pawn that Black sacrifices early on.   When the 2021 Tata Steel Tournament started, Jorden had Black versus Fabiano Caruana in the first round. Fabiano started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  , and after  1...e6  2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  c5  , Fabiano thought for a bit and responded with  4.e3  ,  not allowing the Schara Gambit. Jorden did not get the  opportunity anymore to show the gambit in that tournament @@StartBracket@@which we did not  feel bad about, as he won the tournament!@@EndBracket@@, but eventually used it to beat David Anton Guijarro in the Carlsen Invitational of 2021. Soon the gambit was picked up by top player Alexander Grischuk, and more strong players followed suit.Eventually it led to Magnus Carlsen using it versus Sam Shankland in a  classical game of the Tata Steel Tournament of 2022. Although I do not know  the details, Jorden must have had some influence on this, as he was part of  Magnus Carlsens team for the 2021 World Championship match against Ian  Nepomniatchi @@StartBracket@@in which one game started with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  e6  ,  by the way!@@EndBracket@@. This was only the  second time the Schara Gambit was used by a World Champion in a classical game,  as Alexander Alekhine used it to beat Vasja Pirc back in 1931.Actually, not only the evaluation and status of the Schara Gambit has changed, but also Black's main setups. For example, in the main line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  , for a long time the main move was  7...Nc6  followed by Nf6-Bc5-Qe7 and castling long. These days however, we have discovered that  7...Nf6  is best, followed by Bc5 and castling kingside instead! The way to approach this gambit has completely changed, not only in this position but in several others as well.This is my second course for Chessable, and also my second Black repertoire  versus 1. d4. My first Chessable course was on the Janowski, which actually starts with the same two moves as the Schara Gambit. In this course we respond to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  , but after  3.Nc3  play  3...c5  instead of 3... a6. The gambit  starts after  4.cxd5  cxd4!?  .  We deviate from the more typical reply 4... exd5,  which leads to the Tarrasch Defense. White can, of course, respond to 3...c5  differently, but that is covered in the first chapter of this course. Thus, the starting position of this course is actually after 3... c5.The Schara Gambit is all about long-term compensation. We are usually not playing  for tricks early on, or even trying to win back the pawn as soon as possible.  Things could, of course, go badly wrong for White early on regardless. However, mainly we will play  with the extra space we have due to the pawn missing and lead in development in the Schara Gambit. Eventually we can turn this into a kingside attack or an initiative on the queenside.White usually either picks up the pawn with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  , after which we play  5...Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  , or with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  .  In both versions of the sacrifice, we get the same pawn structure. In a way it is difficult to call it a structure, as the pawns that are still left on the board are in their starting position. What I mean by structure is that we get the  two vs two situation on the queenside, and four vs three on the kingside.We have a slight lead in development, which gives us some compensation, but by itself not enough. Where the other part of our compensation comes from, is actually the extra e-pawn that White has. On e2 it is blocking White's light-squared bishop. On e3 it will be blocking White's dark-squared bishop, and on e4 it will be  weakening the dark-squares such as d4 too much. Also, White usually does not have enough time to develop the dark-squared bishop before playing e3, as this would weaken the b2-pawn which we can often make use of.The Schara Gambit itself is  already quite an exciting weapon, but one of the big advantages is that it can  easily be used versus  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  and to avoid the Nimzo Indian. If top level chess players have Black, they often want to reach the position after  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  . However, this move order allows White to go for a Nimzo-Indian after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  , while  3...d5  leads to a different type of position after  4.cxd5  . @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Nf6  is the same story, but via a different move order. Black players also have to deal with the move orders @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  e6  2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  Nf6  2.Nc3  e6  3.e4  .  As you can see, move orders can be a headache, especially via 1. c4, and that is why I think this opening is also quite interesting  for players who normally play  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  as Black.  They don't need to study all  the Nimzo Indians, and have an easy way to meet 1. c4. If you play in this way as Black, then after  3.Nf3  you are still able to switch back after  3...Nf6  .  3. Nf3 could  also be met in other ways, such as the Janowski with  3...a6  , but  3...c6  ,  3...c5  and  3...dxc4  are also popular options.The main difference between my two courses is actually that the Janowski course was a lifetime repertoire,  meaning that it covers everything after White has played 1. d4. What is different about this course, is that we only cover the position after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  . This course could have been made into an entire repertoire. However, I refrained from doing so because it is difficult to find a similar weapon as the Schara Gambit after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  .  In my Janowski course it was quite simple, as I  could recommend 3... a6 after both 3. Nc3 and 3. Nf3. Yes, after 3. Nf3 we can  still play  3...c5  , but after  4.cxd5  the move  4...cxd4  is this time actually quite bad in comparison to the line 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4. This means that I would have to recommend something else entirely, but that would not be in the same spirit as the  Schara Gambit. That is why we are only focussing on the Schara Gambit in this  course.To give some further background on the name of the Schara Gambit, we should  go into the past. As mentioned before, Alexander Alekhine played it in  1931, but the gambit was actually very fresh when he played it. Anton Schara introduced the gambit in Vienna 1918, while Heinz von Hennig played it for the  first time in 1929. They both won their games in quite a smooth way.  Eventually, the gambit was named after the both of them, thus the name Von  Hennig-Schara Gambit was created. They supposedly analysed the gambit  together, but I do not want to get too much into the details. They were decent  players for their time, but not among the best of the world. Especially as it  was a while back, not too many records of that time are still saved.As I am sure this will otherwise raise questions, I would like to mention it here  already. Yes, I am aware of the V for von Hennig-Schara: Black's Best Gambit  against 1.d4 course on Chessable by IndrekR & Chessforlife. It was released in  December 2020 @@StartBracket@@no, I was not aware of this course when I proposed this opening  to Jorden!@@EndBracket@@, and I think it is first of all missing all the recent updates  that started to happen in 2021 and 2022. Indrek and Chessforlife were already moving in the right  direction in a couple of places, but I do think that I bring important updates  in this course. Apart from that I hope that my expertise, explanations and the  video that is connected to this course will bring something valuable as well. }
*

