[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 4. e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3
{ The 4th move sidelines make up a bigger part of the Quickstarter Guide than they do of the theoretical chapters. My reasoning for this is that they are relatively popular, but not as critical as entering the Schara Gambit. Especially 4. Nf3 and 4. dxc5 should give us a very pleasant position early on.It is important to me that the Quickstarter Guide gives you a nice summary, but also shows you what you can expect to face in your own games. When selecting the lines of the Quickstarter Guide, I mostly had a look at the most popular reactions White has in the normal database and the Lichess database. }
4... Nf6 5. cxd5
{ This is an attempt to steer the game into a different direction. We intend to react to  5.Nf3  with  5...a6  , so this line has some independence as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  White intends to play  6.Bb5+  next. }
5... exd5
{ We typically recapture with the pawn, which could lead to isolated queen's pawn positions. They should be explained well enough in the 4th move sidelines chapter, but I hope to give a nice overview here as well. }
6. Bb5+ Nc6
{ 6...Bd7  and  6...Nbd7  are interesting alternatives, but this is the most active approach so I like it. These positions will revolve around the d4-square, so the knight is well placed on c6. }
7. Nf3 cxd4
{ We usually try to release the tension as early as possible in these lines. The problem is that we want to castle kingside as quickly as possible. However, if we play a move like  7...Bd6  , this will cost us time after  8.dxc5  as we now have to move the bishop twice. }
8. exd4
{ The positions here will remain quite symmetrical, but will not be dull due to the amount of pieces left. }
8... Bd6 { The best square for this bishop, controlling e5 and f4. } 9. O-O O-O
10. Bg5 Bg4
{ The most active way to meet Bg5. We are threatening to play Bxf3, when gxf3 is quite ugly but Qxf3 costs a pawn due to Nxd4. On the other hand White is not really threatening Nxd5 as we will see soon. In general we still have a lot of improving moves in such positions such as Re8 and Rc8. }
11. Nxd5
{ This together with  11.h3?  @@StartBracket@@we anyway were threatening to play Bxf3@@EndBracket@@ are the most popular responses on Lichess. Other alternatives are mentioned in the chapter, but should not cause any trouble either. }
11... Bxh2+
{ This is why 11.Nxd5 was not a problem. We win back the pawn while White is left with an isolated d-pawn, and the h-pawn is gone which was an important defender of White's king. }
12. Kxh2 Qd6+
{ 12...Qxd5  also gives us nice position, but this is even more clever. We intend to take back with the knight on d5, giving us a nice blockade and a great position. }
