1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3
{ The 4th move sidelines make up a bigger part of the Quickstarter Guide than they do of the theoretical chapters. My reasoning for this is that they are relatively popular, but not as critical as entering the Schara Gambit. Especially 4. Nf3 and 4. dxc5 should give us a very pleasant position early on.It is important to me that the Quickstarter Guide gives you a nice summary, but also shows you what you can expect to face in your own games. When selecting the lines of the Quickstarter Guide, I mostly had a look at the most popular reactions White has in the normal database and the Lichess database. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 a6
{ I have always quite liked this line, avoiding the copy-cat move  5...Nc6  .  5...Nc6  is more popular, but I think that  5...a6  leads to more original positions and may also catch your opponent off-guard. We prepare an eventual b5, but also stop Bb5+. }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. g3 c4
{ This structure is always quite ambitious, and we should go for it if possible. The point here is that the combination of g3 and e3 looks odd, as the bishop wants to go to g2 instead of pressuring c4. That is why c4 is possible here. Playing c4 is a lot easier with the pawn on a6, as we can quickly start solidifying the queenside with b5. }
8. Bg2 Bb4
{ The bishop is quite nice on b4, as it deals with the important knight on c3. The knight not only exerts pressure on the d5-pawn and the b5-square, but it also supports an eventual e4-break. Apart from that it blocks the c4-pawn, so a break with b3 is easier to get in. However, the pressure that our bishop is creating is annoying for White. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Bd2 Re8
{ The rook is always quite nice on e8 in these structures, stopping any e4-break but also pressuring the e5-square. }
11. Ne5 Nc6
{ This is an interesting move that has been played by a lot of strong players already. The knight on e5 is quite powerful and needs to be dealt with. We do not mind the structure after Nxc6 bxc6 at all. }
12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ With a pleasant position for Black, in which the engine already starts to prefer our side. We intend to play a5 soon to expand on the queenside and are able to meet  13.b3  a5  14.bxc4  with  14...Ba6  .  In the model games chapter a game of Magnus Carlsen has been included showing the right plans in such positions. }
