1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3
{ The 4th move sidelines make up a bigger part of the Quickstarter Guide than they do of the theoretical chapters. My reasoning for this is that they are relatively popular, but not as critical as entering the Schara Gambit. Especially 4. Nf3 and 4. dxc5 should give us a very pleasant position early on.It is important to me that the Quickstarter Guide gives you a nice summary, but also shows you what you can expect to face in your own games. When selecting the lines of the Quickstarter Guide, I mostly had a look at the most popular reactions White has in the normal database and the Lichess database. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 a6
{ I have always quite liked this line, avoiding the copy-cat move  5...Nc6  .  5...Nc6  is more popular, but I think that  5...a6  leads to more original positions and may also catch your opponent off-guard. We prepare an eventual b5, but also stop Bb5+. }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. Be2 cxd4
{ Again taking on d4 as soon as possible. We should not play  7...c4  this time as the pawn will not last very long on c4 after  8.O-O  followed by b3. }
8. Nxd4
{ 8.exd4  is of course possible, but not very threatening with a bishop on e2. We can just play  8...h6  followed by Bd6. }
8... Nc6 9. O-O Bd6
{ We again go for this setup, but things are slightly different this time than in the 5.cxd5 IQP positions that we have seen before. }
10. b3 Qc7
{ This is quite a clever move, making use of the vulnerable knight on c3 and h2-pawn.  11.Nf3  is more or less forced as  11.h3  loses to  11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Be5  . }
11. Nf3 Be6 { d5 was under attack, so it had to be protected. } 12. Bb2 O-O 13.
Rc1 Rfe8 { The rooks are best on e8 and d8 in these positions. } 14. h3 Rad8
15. Bd3 Qe7
{ Funnily enough, we suddenly transpose to a position that we have seen before in this chapter. All the plans are of course still the same. }
