[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. Nf3
{ Although this is still objectively ok for White, this move @@StartBracket@@and the same goes for  4.dxc5  @@EndBracket@@ can very easily lead to trouble early on for White. It does not make a lot of sense to allow us to get rid of White's central pawn so easily. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ We should make use of the fact that White has no pawn in the centre. This can easily go wrong for White with the vulnerable knights. }
6. Ndb5
{ This seems to make things even worse for White, as we can play a6 gaining another tempo. }
6... a6 7. Qa4
{ White needs to have seen this move beforehand, as  7.Na3  d4  is just really bad for White due to our huge space advantage. White is now threatening devastating discovered checks while also pinning our a-pawn. }
7... Bd7
{ Not only preventing discovered checks, but it also prevents  8.Nxd5  as we win a piece after  8...Bxb5  9.cxb5  Qxd5  . The move does come at the cost of a pawn, but we get great compensation for it. }
8. cxd5 Nf6
{ Just continuing our development. We can play Bc5 or Qb6 next, with at the very least a fine position if White does not respond quickly. }
9. d6
{ This move looks quite appealing for White as the pin on the a-file is still there and Nc7+ is a deadly threat. However, we have a powerful move here. }
9... axb5
{ Sacrificing the exchange, gaining time and also forcing the queen to go to a bad square on a8. }
10. Qxa8 b4
{ Black is already objectively better in this position, and I have to say it just looks great. We can play Bxd6 next, castle afterwards and enjoy a very nice initiative due to White's lack of development and bad placement of the queen. This has been worked out in more detail in the sidelines chapter @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@, but it is probably White who would need more assistance in this dangerous position. }
*

