[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 4. Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. Nf3
{ Although this is still objectively ok for White, this move @@StartBracket@@and the same goes for  4.dxc5  @@EndBracket@@ can very easily lead to trouble early on for White. It does not make a lot of sense to allow us to get rid of White's central pawn so easily. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ We should make use of the fact that White has no pawn in the centre. This can easily go wrong for White with the vulnerable knights. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.Ndb5  should be played, but the move  6.Nf3?!  is a lot more popular. both of our centre pawns are now under attack, but we can gain a tempo by playing d4. }
6... d4 7. Nd5
{ 7.Nxe5  f6!  does not look great for White either, but 7. Nd5 is also an admission that things have gone wrong for White. We have now obtained a powerful centre. }
7... Ne7
{ We try to deal with the knight as quickly as possible, while not allowing a pin with Bg5, which  7...Nf6  would have. }
8. e4
{ This is the standard reaction to Ne7 and also the best move for White, but White often falls for a trap here. }
8... dxe3 9. Bxe3 Nxd5 10. cxd5
{ This looks more logical than  10.Qxd5  , which leaves White in a slightly worse endgame. However, we have a strong idea here. }
10... Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Qxd5
{ Winning a pawn and giving us an almost winning position already due to  12.Bxb4  Qe4+  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 4. dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5 d4
{ A logical reply, gaining space with tempo. White also very often goes wrong here.  5.Na4  should be preferred to 5. Ne4, but then too we have a nice initiative after  5...Bd7  6.b4  Bxa4  7.Qxa4+  Nd7  followed by a5. }
5. Ne4
{ This is the most popular move by far, but can very easily lead to trouble for White. }
5... Nf6 { Just continuing with our development. } 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Followed by Bxc5, with an excellent position for Black. White is already in dangerous territory after 4. dxc5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 5. Qxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qa4
{ It is always a good sign for us when White does not accept the pawn sacrifice after we have played 4... cxd4. We will always get good versions of IQPs in such cases. Not only is the queen misplaced on a4, White also spent two moves to get it there. Still, this Qxd4-Qa4 maneuver is pretty popular when having a look at the Lichess database. }
6... exd5 7. e3
{ 7.Nf3  would be punished by  7...d4!  ,  so White should make the passive move 7. e3 instead. This means that the dark-squared bishop on c1 will remain passive. }
7... Nf6 8. Nf3 Bd6 { We can just go for a typical IQP setup with Black. } 9.
Be2 O-O 10. O-O a6
{ This is a clever move as it prevents Nb5. Now  11.Nb5  loses to  11...axb5  12.Qxa8  Qb6  followed by moving the light-squared bishop, trapping the queen. We can now continue our development with moves such as Bf5 and Re8, giving us a pleasant position. The d-pawn is isolated, but not weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 5. Qxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ The queen trade should now be avoided, and I have dedicated one chapter to  7...Bd6  and one chapter to  7...Qc7  here.  7...Bd6  is a bit more concrete, while  7...Qc7  probably leads to more typical Schara Gambit positions. }
7... Qc7
{ This move is slightly slower in comparison to 7... Bd6 as we develop the queen early on. However, at the same time it is less awkward as the bishop is quite unstable on d6. }
8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qb3
{ This is also a logical retreat square, as the queen is quite vulnerable on d1 instead. However, as the b7-pawn is already protected by our queen, we can immediately start chasing White's queen with Be6. }
9... Be6 { Why not develop with tempo when given the opportunity? } 10. Qa4 Bc5
{ This is the typical square for our dark-squared bishop in the Schara Gambit. }
11. e3 O-O
{ Although Schara gambit players very often castled queenside back in the days, these days it has become clear that Black's king generally belongs on g8 in this opening. }
12. Be2 Rad8
{ Very often we will put our rooks on c8 and d8 in the Schara Gambit. However, our queen is usually on e7. Here it is on c7 and thus our rooks are typically better on d8 and e8, so that we have one piece controlling the c, d and e-files each. }
13. O-O a6
{ Going for b5 is a typical plan in these positions, especially with a vulnerable queen on a4. We have quite a nice lead in development, and White is still struggling to find activity. }
*

