[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 5. Qxd4 #5 (Alternative 7...Bd6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ The queen trade should now be avoided, and I have dedicated one chapter to  7...Bd6  and one chapter to  7...Qc7  here.  7...Bd6  is a bit more concrete, while  7...Qc7  probably leads to more typical Schara Gambit positions. }
7... Bd6 8. Bg5
{ The most direct reply, as otherwise we can just continue with our development with Nf6 and O-O. }
8... Nge7
{ With a pin on the h4-d8 diagonal, the knight is very often just better placed on e7 than on f6. It is defended by more pieces, which gives us more freedom. }
9. Qd2 h6
{ This is an important move to remember. The bishop needs to be kicked away from the g5-square. White is about to play Rd1 or even castle queenside, causing trouble on the d-file. By including h6-Bh4, we can deal with it in a nice way, as the bishop is not protecting the c1-square anymore. }
10. Bh4 Qb6
{ We prepared this move by including h6-Bh4. The bishop is not protecting the c1-square anymore, which means that we can meet  11.Qxd6?  with  11...Qxb2  winning the game, as Rc1 is no longer possible. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 5. Qa4+ with 8. Qxb7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+ Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ Comparing this to the position arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  although Nc6 is a more useful move than Bd7, the good thing is that White is not threatening to trade queens now. }
7... Nf6
{ This is one of the big updates in comparison to how people used to play the Schara Gambit. In the past  7...Nc6  was played first and only afterwards Nf6-Bc5-Qe7-O-O-O. Black players were not bothered with the question of whether to start with  7...Nc6  or  7...Nf6  , and typically opted for  7...Nc6  as it would prevent Qxb7. However, It is quite clever to delay Nc6, as we can develop the knight to a6 instead if White's queen retreats to b3. }
8. Qxb7 { This move is quite greedy, and can lead to disaster very quickly. }
8... Nc6
{ A logical move, protecting the rook. We are now also threatening to win the game with  9.--  Rb8  10.Qa6  Nb4  with a deadly fork on c2. }
9. Qb3
{ This is the safest reply for White. The queen will now be able to protect the c2-square, and head back to d1 for safety. All these queen moves do cost White a lot of time, of course. }
9... Rb8 10. Qd1 Bb4
{ We now gain counterplay in a different way. The idea is to play Ne4 next and perhaps even follow up with Qf6 to put pressure on both c3 and f2. }
11. Nf3 Ne4 12. Bd2
{ We will have to release some tension now as the knight is unpinned. } 12...
Bxc3
{ Although it looks odd to give up the bishop first,  12...Nxc3  would have been met with  13.bxc3  gaining a tempo on our bishop. 12...Bxc3 also opens up the b-file for our rook. }
13. Bxc3 O-O
{ We keep the tension for one more move, finishing our development first. } 14.
e3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qf6
{ With obvious compensation due to White's lack of development and the weakness on c3. White will find it difficult to develop kingside, especially as we can play Qg6, Bg4 or even sometimes Bh3 once White has dealt with c3. }
*

