{ This move makes it clear why it is clever to start with Nf6. Qb3 is a problem in the 7...Nc6 lines, but here our queenside knight is going to c5 to gain more time. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2
{ 10.Qd1  is an alternative, but not too worrysome after  10...Nce4  followed by Bb4. The line after 10. Qc2 is quite critical, and I have dedicated an entire chapter to it. }
10... Rc8
{ Quite a logical move with the queen now on c2. Wherever the queen goes it will remain a target. }
11. e3
{ In this position in the chapter I have provided three alternatives. Of each line I have given the right setup here in the Quickstarter guide, and for further concrete lines I would advise you to have a look at the chapter. }
11... a6
{ The setup with g6 is not very common in the Schara Gambit, but it is the one we are trying to achieve here. We start by playing 11... a6, to be able to move our bishop to e6 if Ne5 comes. The pawn prevents Bb5+. After  11...g6  the sequence  12.Ne5  Be6  13.Bb5+  is quite annoying. }
12. Be2 g6 13. O-O Bg7 14. Rd1
{ Threatening to win the bishop pair with Ne5, so we prevent it with Qe7. }
14... Qe7 { Ne5 had to be prevented. } 15. Nd4
{ Normally the knight is better off on f3 protecting the king, but with our bishop on g7 we do not typically go for a kingside attack. Instead we are trying to put pressure on the queenside. That is why the knight is an excellent blockader on d4. Very often, we try to put pressure on it by playing Ne6. }
15... b5
{ First we play this move, with more or less the threat of b4. As we are fighting for counterplay on the queenside, b5 is quite a useful move. }
16. a3 O-O
{ With very decent compensation for the pawn due to White's cramped position on the queenside. One idea to play Ne6 to put the knight on d4 under pressure. Then we can decide whether we want to trade on d4 or not. The pressure is somewhat annoying for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide: 5. Qa4+ with 8. Qb3 #3 (Alternative 11...Nce4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+ Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ Comparing this to the position arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  although Nc6 is a more useful move than Bd7, the good thing is that White is not threatening to trade queens now. }
7... Nf6
{ This is one of the big updates in comparison to how people used to play the Schara Gambit. In the past  7...Nc6  was played first and only afterwards Nf6-Bc5-Qe7-O-O-O. Black players were not bothered with the question of whether to start with  7...Nc6  or  7...Nf6  , and typically opted for  7...Nc6  as it would prevent Qxb7. However, It is quite clever to delay Nc6, as we can develop the knight to a6 instead if White's queen retreats to b3. }
8. Qb3 Na6
{ This move makes it clear why it is clever to start with Nf6. Qb3 is a problem in the 7...Nc6 lines, but here our queenside knight is going to c5 to gain more time. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2
{ 10.Qd1  is an alternative, but not too worrysome after  10...Nce4  followed by Bb4. The line after 10. Qc2 is quite critical, and I have dedicated an entire chapter to it. }
10... Rc8
{ Quite a logical move with the queen now on c2. Wherever the queen goes it will remain a target. }
11. e3
{ In this position in the chapter I have provided three alternatives. Of each line I have given the right setup here in the Quickstarter guide, and for further concrete lines I would advise you to have a look at the chapter. }
11... Nce4
{ This is the more concrete approach, and most popular move. Magnus Carlsen also used it in 2022. }
12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd5
{ The plan is to either win back the pawn on c3 or win the bishop pair with Nb4. }
14. O-O Nxc3 15. Bb2 Bb4
{ This is where I will end the line in the Quickstarter Guide, while I continue further in the chapter itself. White has a couple of moves here that could be tried, all being somewhat concrete. In general, we would like to play Ba4 next if White gives us the time do so.   I would advise repeating the lines of @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2n5/8/2N1PN2/PPQ2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQk - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nce4  in that chapter a couple of times before playing it. The alternatives  11...a6  or  11...Bd6  are probably easier to play with less studying. If you have studied  11...Nce4  , you should be able to switch between the three options without any issues. }
