[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+ Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ Comparing this to the position arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  although Nc6 is a more useful move than Bd7, the good thing is that White is not threatening to trade queens now. }
7... Nf6
{ This is one of the big updates in comparison to how people used to play the Schara Gambit. In the past  7...Nc6  was played first and only afterwards Nf6-Bc5-Qe7-O-O-O. Black players were not bothered with the question of whether to start with  7...Nc6  or  7...Nf6  , and typically opted for  7...Nc6  as it would prevent Qxb7. However, It is quite clever to delay Nc6, as we can develop the knight to a6 instead if White's queen retreats to b3. }
8. Qd1 Bc5
{ The queen has already gone back to d1, so we may as well play Nc6. Keeping the knight on b8 is a bit more flexible however, and we want to play Bc5 and O-O anyway. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. a3
{ An entire chapter has been devoted to this move. The point is that it prepares Bf4 or Bg5 as Qb6 followed by Qxb2 is not as much of a threat anymore. That is because after Qxb2, White will be able to play Na4 trapping our queen as the b4-square has been protected by the a3-pawn. }
10... Nc6
{ If White continues with the plan of developing the dark-squared bishop we will still gain counterplay with Qb6. If White were to continue with 11. e3 we can just go for our Schara setup with Qe7 and Rfd8.Before playing this move, I would advise to have a deeper look at the corresponding chapter. Things can get very concrete, although the most important lines have been covered here. 10...Qc7 seems to require less study to me. }
11. Bg5 h6
{ We want to get rid of the pin by playing h6-g5, but this move does include a piece sacrifice after 12. Bxf6. }
12. Bh4
{ A more solid approach by White, and it makes sense because if they are just able to play e3-Be2-O-O then they are doing great. }
12... g5
{ The pin is very annoying and we would otherwise always have to deal with the option for White to play Bxf6. }
13. Bg3 Qb6
{ Qxb2 is not a threat yet, but  14.Na4  is not a problem either due to  14...Qa5+  15.b4  Nxb4  .  We intend to play Rad8 next and create counterplay in the centre. }
14. e3 Rad8
{ An improvement over Adrien Demuth's Chessable course. The idea is that we will need the other rook on e8 once we start sacrificing in the centre. The logical  15.Be2  is met with  15...Bf5  ,  followed by ideas connected to Na5. White will have to be careful of sacrifices on e3 as well. }
