{ Comparing this to the position arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  although Nc6 is a more useful move than Bd7, the good thing is that White is not threatening to trade queens now. }
7... Nf6
{ This is one of the big updates in comparison to how people used to play the Schara Gambit. In the past  7...Nc6  was played first and only afterwards Nf6-Bc5-Qe7-O-O-O. Black players were not bothered with the question of whether to start with  7...Nc6  or  7...Nf6  , and typically opted for  7...Nc6  as it would prevent Qxb7. However, It is quite clever to delay Nc6, as we can develop the knight to a6 instead if White's queen retreats to b3. }
8. Qd1 Bc5
{ The queen has already gone back to d1, so we may as well play Nc6. Keeping the knight on b8 is a bit more flexible however, and we want to play Bc5 and O-O anyway. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3 { We will now enter the main line of the Schara Gambit. }
10... Qe7
{ This followed by Rfd8 and Nc6 is the typical setup that we intend to go for. The lines here could be covered in greater length than I have done for the Quickstarter Guide. What I think is most important is the first 2-3 moves after you have played Nc6-Ne5 or Nc6-Rd8. As all the positions might seem similar, it is important to understand which setup you should adopt after White chooses theirs. }
11. Be2 Nc6
{ This is an interesting alternative to  11...Rd8  .  The idea is to play Ne5 as quickly as possible. }
12. O-O Ne5 13. Nxe5
{ This trade is never really a good idea for White, as it activates our queen. The f3-knight is also an important defender of White's kingside. However, in the three games on Lichess after 12... Ne5, all players went for this move. }
13... Qxe5 14. Bf3 Rad8 { Threatening Bb5. } 15. Qe2 h5
{ A typical move, preparing either h4 or Ng4. We have quite a nice version of the typical Schara Gambit positions as White has traded on e5 and is still lacking activity. }
*

