9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3 { We will now enter the main line of the Schara Gambit. }
10... Qe7
{ This followed by Rfd8 and Nc6 is the typical setup that we intend to go for. The lines here could be covered in greater length than I have done for the Quickstarter Guide. What I think is most important is the first 2-3 moves after you have played Nc6-Ne5 or Nc6-Rd8. As all the positions might seem similar, it is important to understand which setup you should adopt after White chooses theirs. }
11. Be2 Rd8
{ We could also have started with  11...Nc6  ,  but I always like to scare White on the d-file first. White can and should just castle, but it could be nice if we can already provoke a different move. }
12. O-O Nc6
{ As mentioned after 10... Qe7, I have not covered the lines here in great detail in the Quickstarter Guide. It is most important to remember the first 2-3 moves from here on, as they could be somewhat confusing as it all looks somewhat similar. }
13. Qb3
{ This move actually does threaten Qxb7, so that needs to be dealt with. }
13... a6 { Preventing  14.Qxb7  due to  14...Na5  ,  while also preparing b5. }
14. a3 Bf5
{ This move is not typical early on for the Schara Gambit, and mostly because White's queen is often on c2. With the queen on b3 instead we intend to play b5, followed by Na5-Be6 to go after White's queen. The bishop on f5 takes away the c2-square for White's queen currently. }
15. Bd2 b5
{ As mentioned before, we threaten Na5 followed by Be6 and Nb3 now. If White were to move away from this threat by playing  16.Qa2  , we can instead go for  16...Ne5  and Rac8 with counterplay. }
