13. Qc2 Nb4
{ Although the logical  13...Rac8  is a very decent alternative, we immediately start chasing the queen now. }
14. Qb1
{ 14.Qb3  is also possible, but then we continue our counterplay with  14...Bc6  .  Funnily enough, this can transpose to 13.a3 after  15.a3  Nd3  16.Qc2  Ne5  . }
14... Bc6
{ White is always quite passive with the queen on b1.  15.a3  can be met with  15...Nbd5  .  Rac8 is also quite a useful move that we can still make.   The bishop on c6 actually prevents White from developing the dark-squared bishop, as  15.Bd2?  is met with  15...Bxf3  16.Bxf3  Rxd2  winning the game. }
