{ As mentioned after 10... Qe7, I have not covered the lines here in great detail in the Quickstarter Guide. It is most important to remember the first 2-3 moves from here on, as they could be somewhat confusing as it all looks somewhat similar. }
13. a3 Ne5
{ a3 prevents any ideas of Nb4, so it make sense to play Ne5 instead. We can often follow this up with Bc6, to put pressure on the knight on f3. The idea of a3 is not only to create a safe square on c2 for the queen, but also that b5 will never immediately come with the threat of b4. }
14. Qc2 Bc6
{ With good counterplay due to the threat of Nxf3+ damaging White's kingside. If White were to play  15.Nd4  , we just take the pawn with  15...Bxd4  16.exd4  Rxd4  .  Hopefully you enjoyed the Quickstarter Guide. In some lines it is more important to go for deeper study than in others, but I have let you known in this chapter which lines those are. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5
{ One of the options that White has instead of the usual 4. cxd5. Although this move is not seen very often, it has a point. White simply threatens to capture on d5 now, with the opened up d-file allowing the queen to attack the pawn as well. Although  4...Bxc5  is playable and leads to a typical Schara Gambit position,  4...d4  seems even better to me.   After  4...Bxc5  , the following line is likely to happen:  5.cxd5  Nf6  6.dxe6  Qxd1+  7.Nxd1  Bxe6  with excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn. Black intends to play Nc6 and 0-0 next with a huge lead in development.White also gets to keep an extra pawn after 4... d4, but is forced to put the knight on a4 to keep it. The pawn on d4 will grab space in the centre and make life more difficult for White. }
4... d4 { With this move we are already grabbing the initiative. } 5. Ne4 Nf6
{ As the attempt to keep protecting the c5-pawn with  6.Nxf6+  Qxf6  7.b4  leads to even more trouble, it is probably best for White to play  6.Nd6+  here forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. However, after  6...Bxd6  7.cxd6  Qxd6  , Black is better due to the lead in development and space advantage.   6.Bg5  is also possible and keeps the tension. After  6...Na6  we will anyway pick up the pawn with  7.--  Nxc5  next, leading to a pleasant position due to our space advantage. }
6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. b4 a5
{ White's structure is falling apart, while Black still has a nice space advantage in the centre. The move  8.a3  fails, as after  8...axb4  the a3-pawn is pinned on the a-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5
{ One of the options that White has instead of the usual 4. cxd5. Although this move is not seen very often, it has a point. White simply threatens to capture on d5 now, with the opened up d-file allowing the queen to attack the pawn as well. Although  4...Bxc5  is playable and leads to a typical Schara Gambit position,  4...d4  seems even better to me.   After  4...Bxc5  , the following line is likely to happen:  5.cxd5  Nf6  6.dxe6  Qxd1+  7.Nxd1  Bxe6  with excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn. Black intends to play Nc6 and O-O next with a huge lead in development.White also gets to keep an extra pawn after 4... d4, but is forced to put the knight on a4 to keep it. The pawn on d4 will grab space in the centre and make life more difficult for White. }
4... d4 { With this move we are already grabbing the initiative. } 5. Na4
{ As it is difficult for White to keep the pawn after  5.Ne4?!  Nf6  ,  the knight really should go to a4. }
5... Bd7
{ Targetting the knight on a4. Black is not only trying to get rid of the defender of the c5-pawn, but also just threatening to win a piece with Qa5+. }
6. b4
{ Giving additional protection to the c5 pawn and also avoiding the deadly Qa5+. }
6... Bxa4
{ Forcing the queen out in the open, where it will soon get exposed once we start tearing apart the queenside with a5. }
7. Qxa4+ Nd7
{ The knight nicely blocks the check on d7 while it also has the potential to grab the pawn on c5. Black is now ready to play a5 next. }
8. e3
{ This allows Black to trade off the d4 pawn, while still being able to tear the queenside apart with a5. }
8... dxe3 9. Bxe3 a5
{ There is not a great way for White to deal with the pressure on the queenside. It is probably best to give up one of the pawns to get the king faster out of the centre. }
10. g3 axb4
{ There was not really a good reason for Black to wait with this move. } 11.
Qxb4 Ra5
{ A nice way to target the c5 pawn while getting the rook off the h1-a8 diagonal where White was about to put pressure on with Bg2. Black intends to finally finish development with Bxc5 followed by Ngf6. }
12. Bg2 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight has a great outpost on c5 now and black's strategy has worked to perfection. White's queenside pawns are both isolated, and Black is already putting pressure on a2. Apart from the strategical plans in this interesting position, Black simply has the killer threat of Nd3+ with a royal fork. }
14. Rd1 Qc7
{ As  14...Nd3+??  fails to  15.Rxd3  Qxd3  16.Qxa5  ,  Black simply has to move the queen out of the way. The queen is protecting the b7 pawn which was under some pressure. Black now wants to play Nf6 followed by O-O and go after White's queenside afterwards. }
*

