[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5
{ One of the options that White has instead of the usual 4. cxd5. Although this move is not seen very often, it has a point. White simply threatens to capture on d5 now, with the opened up d-file allowing the queen to attack the pawn as well. Although  4...Bxc5  is playable and leads to a typical Schara Gambit position,  4...d4  seems even better to me.   After  4...Bxc5  , the following line is likely to happen:  5.cxd5  Nf6  6.dxe6  Qxd1+  7.Nxd1  Bxe6  with excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn. Black intends to play Nc6 and O-O next with a huge lead in development.White also gets to keep an extra pawn after 4... d4, but is forced to put the knight on a4 to keep it. The pawn on d4 will grab space in the centre and make life more difficult for White. }
4... d4 { With this move we are already grabbing the initiative. } 5. Na4
{ As it is difficult for White to keep the pawn after  5.Ne4?!  Nf6  ,  the knight really should go to a4. }
5... Bd7
{ Targetting the knight on a4. Black is not only trying to get rid of the defender of the c5-pawn, but also just threatening to win a piece with Qa5+. }
6. b4
{ Giving additional protection to the c5 pawn and also avoiding the deadly Qa5+. }
6... Bxa4
{ Forcing the queen out in the open, where it will soon get exposed once we start tearing apart the queenside with a5. }
7. Qxa4+ Nd7
{ The knight nicely blocks the check on d7 while it also has the potential to grab the pawn on c5. Black is now ready to play a5 next. }
8. Nf3
{ Now White will at least manage to grab the d4 pawn instead of trade it. The downside is that it slows down White's development a little bit. }
8... a5
{ There was not really a nice way of protecting the d4 pawn anyway, so we should just continue with the plan we had all along. }
9. Nxd4 axb4 10. Qxb4 Bxc5 11. Qb2 Ngf6
{ Although we are still down a pawn, it is clear that we have tremendous compensation. First of all, we have a big development lead and are about to finish our development with O-O. Apart from our development lead, both of White's queenside pawns are isolated. As they are both on half open files, this will give us a good opportunity for our rooks to put pressure on them.   White does have the bishop pair, but we can easily get rid of it. We can for example meet  12.e3  with  12...Ba3  and trade on c1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. Nf3
{ Although 4.Nf3 develops another piece, it is an odd move. We are simply allowed to exchange our c pawn for the centre pawn, which is a good trade strategically speaking. White does get active knights back for it, but they can also become vulnerable. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Fighting for the initiative in the centre! Black would ideally like to expand even more in the centre with d4 next. Most people have gone astray here with the logical looking  6.Nf3  .  At an afterparty of the European Team Championships 2021 I managed to get the opportunity to play a blitz game with Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, also known as MVL. Although both of us were not aware of the theory of this line, I managed to find the moves that I am about to recommend. Although it was blitz, even MVL played 6. Nf3 here, and with a neat trick I managed to quickly win a pawn. }
6. Nf3 d4 7. Nxe5 f6
{ Not falling for  7...dxc3?!  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.Nxf7+  Ke8  10.Nxh8  Bb4  11.Kd1!  which should be better for White.   Instead, the simple move  7...f6  is just very strong. Black just has a double attack now and White should be worse. The best way for White to get some compensation is by playing  8.e3  threatening Qh5+. }
8. Qa4+
{ White wants to force a piece to d7 so that the e5-knight can be traded and then save the c3-knight. However, we can play Nd7 and take back with the bishop to gain a tempo on the queen. }
8... Nd7 9. Nxd7 Bxd7 10. Nb5 a6
{ White did not manage to save a piece and also did not get any compensation for it in return now. }
*

