{ Although 4.Nf3 develops another piece, it is an odd move. We are simply allowed to exchange our c pawn for the centre pawn, which is a good trade strategically speaking. White does get active knights back for it, but they can also become vulnerable. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Fighting for the initiative in the centre! Black would ideally like to expand even more in the centre with d4 next. Most people have gone astray here with the logical looking  6.Nf3  .  At an afterparty of the European Team Championships 2021 I managed to get the opportunity to play a blitz game with Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, also known as MVL. Although both of us were not aware of the theory of this line, I managed to find the moves that I am about to recommend. Although it was blitz, even MVL played 6. Nf3 here, and with a neat trick I managed to quickly win a pawn. }
6. Nf3 d4 7. Nxe5 f6
{ Not falling for  7...dxc3?!  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.Nxf7+  Ke8  10.Nxh8  Bb4  11.Kd1!  which should be better for White.   Instead, the simple move  7...f6  is just very strong. Black just has a double attack now and White should be worse. The best way for White to get some compensation is by playing  8.e3  threatening Qh5+. }
8. e3 Bf5
{ The most practical way of dealing with Qh5+. Black is again ready to take one of the two knights. }
9. Qa4+ Nd7 10. Nc6 bxc6 11. exd4
{ White at least has two pawns for the piece now, but that should not be enough. }
11... c5
{ Two pawns for a piece is in general just not enough. Black should be better here and can just continue with development. }
