1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. Nf3
{ Although 4.Nf3 develops another piece, it is an odd move. We are simply allowed to exchange our c pawn for the centre pawn, which is a good trade strategically speaking. White does get active knights back for it, but they can also become vulnerable. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Fighting for the initiative in the centre! Black would ideally like to expand even more in the centre with d4 next. Most people have gone astray here with the logical looking  6.Nf3  .  At an afterparty of the European Team Championships 2021 I managed to get the opportunity to play a blitz game with Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, also known as MVL. Although both of us were not aware of the theory of this line, I managed to find the moves that I am about to recommend. Although it was blitz, even MVL played 6. Nf3 here, and with a neat trick I managed to quickly win a pawn. }
6. Ndb5
{ The best way for White to continue. As  6...d4  would give White a nice position after  7.Nd5  with a deadly threat of Nc7+, it is better to avoid this. We should try to kick out the b5-knight first with a6. }
6... a6 7. Qa4
{ Pinning the a6-pawn and keeping the knight on b5. Qa4 comes with deadly discovered attacks, so we should be a bit careful. }
7... Bd7
{ Sacrificing the d5-pawn for now. As  8.Nxd5??  would now be met with  8...Bxb5  9.cxb5  Qxd5  ,  we have at least managed to stop a knight from coming to the d5-square. That is definitely something that we should avoid, as it would lead to a deadly check on c7. }
8. cxd5 Nf6
{ For now we should just focus on development. The situation of the pin is a bit nasty for White, but it is also difficult to make use of for Black. In some cases we might just play axb5 and give up the exchange to get a very nice initiative. }
9. d6
{ The most played move in my database. Except for three correspondence games in 2018-2019, there is also a game in which Frank Marshall had the White pieces in 1905! Known for his Marshall Gambit, it is somewhat odd to see him have the White pieces here as Black is about to sacrifice. Somehow this inferior move was played in most games, but I guess it is just the most logical one in this complicated position. }
9... axb5
{ As Nc7+ was about to be played, sacrificing the exchange in this way makes a lot of sense. White is forced to play Qxa8 when a8 is a very bad square for the queen. Apart from that Black already has a lead in development and a space advantage in the centre and on the queenside. }
10. Qxa8 b4
{ We have to keep on fighting for the initiative.  10...Bxd6?!  Would have allowed White to consolidate with  11.e4  . }
11. Nd1
{ A much more solid reply to b4. The knight is kind of in the way, but White was already in a difficult position. }
11... Bxd6
{ We are now down a full exchange, but have a huge lead in development. We intend to make the most out of it, with ideas such as O-O, Bc6 and Ne4 next. We should not play the position slowly as White might be able to untangle in a few moves. }
12. Qxb7 Bc6
{ Thing are not so clear after  12...O-O  13.Bg5  . This forcing way of playing makes life difficult for White. }
13. Qa7 Ne4
{ Now the threat of Bc5 is difficult to deal with, as even  14.Be3  does not stop it. After  14...Bc5  15.Bxc5  we suddenly have  15...Qd2#! }
14. Qe3
{ The only move for White to stay in the game, but a rather akward one. } 14...
O-O
{ Now things remains difficult for White, and we have ideas such as Nc5-Bb5-Nc6-Nd4 to keep the initiative going. Bc5 is still an idea as well. }
