{ We would like to develop the dark-squared bishop to get the king out of the centre, but doing so immediately will make us lose time after White has played dxc5. That is why we should release the tension immediately with 7... cxd4. }
8. exd4 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 Bg4
{ The most active way of playing, and we can comfortably make this move as  11.Nxd5  is not an issue due to  11...Bxh2+  . }
11. Be2
{ This seems a bit passive to me, but White intends to play h3 next. Once there is no pawn on h2 anymore White is ready to play Nxd5 as we can't respond to it anymore with Bxh2+. }
11... Re8
{ The most useful move in the position, and as we will see next h3 is not difficult to deal with. In general the rooks will be best placed on c8 and e8 as the c and e-files have opened up. }
12. h3 Bxf3
{ Giving up the bishop pair, as White can respond to  12...Bh5  with  13.Nxd5  since there is no pawn on h2 anymore. The loss of the bishop pair is only a temporary issue, as we will play h6 next and White should give up theirs as well. }
13. Bxf3 h6 14. Bxf6
{ Other options are not that attractive either for White. To  14.Bh4  we can respond with  14...g5  15.Bg3  Bxg3  after which the slightly weakened king is compensated by white's worsened structure. Our king should not have that many issues as the light-squared bishop will find it difficult to join the attack.   14.Be3  is just a bit passive, and after  14...Bc7  we create the threat of Qd6 followed by Rxe3. The bishop can also reroute to b6 to put pressure on d4. This leaves us with the most forcing reply of 14. Bxf6. }
14... Qxf6 15. Bxd5
{ As  15.Nxd5  is met with  15...Qxd4  that is not an issue either. The knight will not be that well placed on d5 as it is dominated by our dark squared bishop. }
15... Nxd4
{ This time we don't capture with the queen on d4 as that will give White some initiative after  15...Qxd4  16.Qh5  .   Although things are rather balanced in the current position, I would prefer to play with Black due to our slightly more active pieces. We intend to play Rad8 next and all of our pieces have joined the battle.  16.Bxb7  is not an issue either as this can be met with  16...Rab8  followed by  17...Rxb2  with an active rook on the second rank. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. e3 Nf6 5. cxd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+
{ As I am recommending 5.Nf3 a6, this is an interesting direction for White. By using this move order we are not in time to play a6 in order to prevent Bb5+.   Instead of  6.Bb5+  , White usually continues with  6.Nf3  which allows us to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  a6  6.cxd5  exd5  if we respond with 6... a6. Instead of just transposing, it is also interesting to make use of this move order by playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/5n2/2pp4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c4!?  instead. The structure that arises after  c4  is generally an ambitious one, and one we will see later on in the  a6  lines as well where I will be explaining how to play it. }
6... Nc6
{ 6...Nbd7  and  6...Bd7  are also interesting moves. In a way, I would consider Nbd7 as an interesting fighting option.  After 6...Nc6 we will play cxd4 soon and this does allow White to go for a symmetrical structure by recapturing with exd4. On the other hand, Nbd7 will likely lead to an IQP position after White has gone dxc5 at some moment in which the knight might be misplaced on d7/c5. Having the Black pieces makes it generally difficult to avoid giving White a solid position. Although the positions after 6...Nc6 can become symmetrical, there is still a lot of life in the position with all the pieces remaining on the board and this made me decide on recommending this move. }
7. Nf3 cxd4
{ We would like to develop the dark-squared bishop to get the king out of the centre, but doing so immediately will make us lose time after White has played dxc5. That is why we should release the tension immediately with 7... cxd4. }
8. exd4 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 Bg4
{ The most active way of playing, and we can comfortably make this move as  11.Nxd5  is not an issue due to  11...Bxh2+  . }
11. Bxc6
{ The other move White usually continues with in this line. It does not make too much sense to me to be honest. It does give us a backward pawn on c6, but we get the bishop pair back for it and the pressure on d5 is gone. In the meantime there is also no pressure on c6 for now. }
11... bxc6
{ The general plan for Black is to improve the rooks for now. Re8 and Rb8-Rb4 are the direct plans. }
12. Qd3 Re8 { Improving the rook and preventing Ne5. } 13. Rae1
{ 13...--  14.Ne5  is again a threat, while  14.Rxe8+  Qxe8  15.Bxf6  would also be slightly annoying. It is generally not so bad to get the f-pawns doubled there as our light squared bishop can start protecting our king nicely once it gets to g6. }
13... Qb6
{ The most active way of playing. This not only puts pressure on d4 and b2 but also connects our rooks and unpins our knight. It does allow Bxf6, but this should not be a problem. The loss of another bishop for White compensates for our structure. }
14. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Our position is not the prettiest, but we do have a couple of threats and an active bishop pair. First of all  15.--  Bxf3  is an idea as after  16.Qxf3  we win a pawn with  16...Qxd4  . This means that White will have to recapture with  16.gxf3  and that will lead to an equally bad structure for both sides. The b2-pawn is still under attack and apart from those ideas we can also reroute our bishop to g6 via h5 where it will be quite strong and protective of our king. The bishop on g6 will work nicely together with our kingside pawn structure. }
*

