6... Nc6
{ 6...Nbd7  and  6...Bd7  are also interesting moves. In a way, I would consider Nbd7 as an interesting fighting option.  After 6...Nc6 we will play cxd4 soon and this does allow White to go for a symmetrical structure by recapturing with exd4. On the other hand, Nbd7 will likely lead to an IQP position after White has gone dxc5 at some moment in which the knight might be misplaced on d7/c5. Having the Black pieces makes it generally difficult to avoid giving White a solid position. Although the positions after 6...Nc6 can become symmetrical, there is still a lot of life in the position with all the pieces remaining on the board and this made me decide on recommending this move. }
7. Nf3 cxd4
{ We would like to develop the dark-squared bishop to get the king out of the centre, but doing so immediately will make us lose time after White has played dxc5. That is why we should release the tension immediately with 7... cxd4. }
8. exd4 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. h3
{ Stopping Bg4, but this also gives us time to stop Bg5. } 10... h6 11. Re1
{ In this very symmetrical position, White has a very slight initiative due to the extra move White started with from the very beginning. On the other hand, we don't have that much to worry about as we don't really have weaknesses. White can in the future try to go after the d5 pawn, but this usually also means that White will have to lose a bit of protection of the d4-pawn. A good example of this is if White will play Qb3 in the future, this means that the d4-pawn is not defended anymore by the queen. }
11... Bf5
{ As the g4 square is not available anymore, this is the next best square. If White does not play actively we intend on playing Re8 and Rc8 next. }
12. Ne5 Qb6
{ With a roughly equal position. Black has some pressure on d4 that White will have to deal with. We intend to play Rfe8 and Rac8 next with a perfectly healthy position. Again I will say that although the structure is symmetrical this is not a boring position. Due to all the pieces still being left on the board a lot can still happen. }
