6... Nc6
{ 6...Nbd7  and  6...Bd7  are also interesting moves. In a way, I would consider Nbd7 as an interesting fighting option.  After 6...Nc6 we will play cxd4 soon and this does allow White to go for a symmetrical structure by recapturing with exd4. On the other hand, Nbd7 will likely lead to an IQP position after White has gone dxc5 at some moment in which the knight might be misplaced on d7/c5. Having the Black pieces makes it generally difficult to avoid giving White a solid position. Although the positions after 6...Nc6 can become symmetrical, there is still a lot of life in the position with all the pieces remaining on the board and this made me decide on recommending this move. }
