1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+
{ As I am recommending 5.Nf3 a6, this is an interesting direction for White. By using this move order we are not in time to play a6 in order to prevent Bb5+.   Instead of  6.Bb5+  , White usually continues with  6.Nf3  which allows us to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  a6  6.cxd5  exd5  if we respond with 6... a6. Instead of just transposing, it is also interesting to make use of this move order by playing  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/5n2/2pp4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c4!?  instead. The structure that arises after  c4  is generally an ambitious one, and one we will see later on in the  a6  lines as well where I will be explaining how to play it. }
6... Nc6
{ 6...Nbd7  and  6...Bd7  are also interesting moves. In a way, I would consider Nbd7 as an interesting fighting option.  After 6...Nc6 we will play cxd4 soon and this does allow White to go for a symmetrical structure by recapturing with exd4. On the other hand, Nbd7 will likely lead to an IQP position after White has gone dxc5 at some moment in which the knight might be misplaced on d7/c5. Having the Black pieces makes it generally difficult to avoid giving White a solid position. Although the positions after 6...Nc6 can become symmetrical, there is still a lot of life in the position with all the pieces remaining on the board and this made me decide on recommending this move. }
7. Nf3 cxd4
{ We would like to develop the dark-squared bishop to get the king out of the centre, but doing so immediately will make us lose time after White has played dxc5. That is why we should release the tension immediately with 7... cxd4. }
8. Nxd4
{ I would say that this is the most ambitious approach by White. Capturing with the knight on d4 leaves us with an isolated queen's pawn. Don't worry if you are not familiar with IQP positions, as we have a pretty decent version of them and I will do my best to explain the typical plans of such positions together with concrete lines. In a way, IQP positions are Schara Gambit positions with an extra pawn on d5, so if you enjoy playing the Schara Gambit positions you should probably also not mind IQP's so much. }
8... Bd7
{ Although not the most active square, the c6 knight had to be protected. We will continue with Bd6 and O-O next. }
9. O-O Bd6 10. Nf3 Be6
{ As I don't like  10...a6  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.e4!  or  11...Bxc6  very much, I think this is a better move, simply protecting the d5-pawn. As we have now protected the-d6 bishop as well with our queen, we don't have to worry for e4-breaks either. This means that we can now safely play a6 on the next move and can safely recapture with bxc6. }
11. b3 a6
{ Almost all players have played O-O first here, but it seems more accurate to me to start with a6 and ask the question immediately to White where they want to put there bishop. By delaying castling we can adjust our setup even more depending on where White has placed their bishop. }
12. Be2
{ The bishop on e2 does not block the queen's view on the d-file. This setup is not that impressive and I am more a fan of 12.Bd3 instead. White wants to play Bb2-Rc1 next and then see. }
12... O-O 13. Bb2 Qe7
{ A setup had to be chosen and I like this one the most. The idea is to play Rad8 next to support the d-pawn. By adding a layer of protection it frees up our other pieces to move as well. }
14. Rc1 Rad8
{ The position remains complex, but Black is by no means worse. The engine even already starts to slightly prefer Black here. We have several plans involving the activation of our pieces. One simple improvement of our position is to play Rfe8 as the rook will just be more active there. Apart from that, we can activate our light-squared bishop even more by playing Bf5 or Bg4 soon. Another active way of playing is with Ne4.A typical idea in these IQP positions is to go for the d4-break. This break can be used as an equaliser @@StartBracket@@as it often leads to a trade of centre pawns if it is well protected@@EndBracket@@, but can also be used as a way to attack. Sacrificing the d5-pawn will create even more open lines towards white's king @@StartBracket@@the d5-g2 diagonal for example@@EndBracket@@, but the d5-square can also be used for the knight to get into the attack. }
