[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ A choice had to be made here between recommending  5...a6  or  5...Nc6  . The thing is that  5...Nc6  would make more sense in a way, because after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  we transpose to the lines we have seen after 5.cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7.Nf3.   However, after  5...Nc6  White is not obliged to play  6.cxd5  ,  or follow that up with Bb5 either. For example, after 5...Nc6  6.a3  is the most popular move, leading to different positions. White also has the option of playing  5...Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Be2  .   In general, I quite like the move  5...a6  as it has a more forcing nature and seems to lead to more non-standard positions. This is why I will recommend this move, and I don't think it will even mean that we have to do work. White does seem to have quite a few options after 5... Nc6 apart from the ones that have been shown via the other move order.   The idea of the move  5...a6  is very simple. First of all, it avoids the slightly annoying check/pin on b5. Second of all, it also 'threatens' to take on c4 as we are ready to follow it up with b5 whether White has recaptured on c4 or not. }
6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. cxd5 exd5
{ Transposes to 6.cxd5 exd5 7.dxc5 Bxc5 - see the variation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ A choice had to be made here between recommending  5...a6  or  5...Nc6  . The thing is that  5...Nc6  would make more sense in a way, because after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  we transpose to the lines we have seen after 5.cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7.Nf3.   However, after  5...Nc6  White is not obliged to play  6.cxd5  ,  or follow that up with Bb5 either. For example, after 5...Nc6  6.a3  is the most popular move, leading to different positions. White also has the option of playing  5...Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Be2  .   In general, I quite like the move  5...a6  as it has a more forcing nature and seems to lead to more non-standard positions. This is why I will recommend this move, and I don't think it will even mean that we have to do work. White does seem to have quite a few options after 5... Nc6 apart from the ones that have been shown via the other move order.   The idea of the move  5...a6  is very simple. First of all, it avoids the slightly annoying check/pin on b5. Second of all, it also 'threatens' to take on c4 as we are ready to follow it up with b5 whether White has recaptured on c4 or not. }
6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. a3
{ White is following a similar strategy as the one we have. We cannot really stop b4 anymore, but it is not such a big deal. }
7... O-O 8. b4 Be7
{ Ba7 and Bd6 are also interesting options, but I like this one the most. Although it seems to be the most passive square at first, the bishop on e7 has the potential to go to f6. As White has just weakened the a1-f6 diagonal this is quite a good square for the bishop. On e7 it also does not stand in the way of the queen protecting the d5-pawn. In these positions we would like to play a5 as soon as possible to try to get White to play b5. White will lose control over the c5 square by pushing b5, and our knight also gets a nice square on b6. }
9. Bb2 dxc4
{ Allowing dxc4 followed by b5 is generally not what White should do in the positions after 5... a6. This is because in the following symmetrical structure the knight on c3 is misplaced, while our knight usually has the flexbility of going to d7. }
10. Bxc4 b5 11. Be2 Nbd7
{ Followed by Bb7 with quite a pleasant position for us. This might seem odd at first because White is still up a move in development, but the knight is just quite misplaced on c3. If the knight was on d2 instead White might be the one fighting for an advantage, but here it is Black who might already be better. The knight on c3 has nowhere to go and is blocking the diagonal of white's dark-squared bishop. We intend to play either Rc8-Nb6-Nc4 or Qb8-Rc8-Nb6-Nc4 after we have played Bb7. }
