{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ A choice had to be made here between recommending  5...a6  or  5...Nc6  . The thing is that  5...Nc6  would make more sense in a way, because after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  we transpose to the lines we have seen after 5.cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7.Nf3.   However, after  5...Nc6  White is not obliged to play  6.cxd5  ,  or follow that up with Bb5 either. For example, after 5...Nc6  6.a3  is the most popular move, leading to different positions. White also has the option of playing  5...Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Be2  .   In general, I quite like the move  5...a6  as it has a more forcing nature and seems to lead to more non-standard positions. This is why I will recommend this move, and I don't think it will even mean that we have to do work. White does seem to have quite a few options after 5... Nc6 apart from the ones that have been shown via the other move order.   The idea of the move  5...a6  is very simple. First of all, it avoids the slightly annoying check/pin on b5. Second of all, it also 'threatens' to take on c4 as we are ready to follow it up with b5 whether White has recaptured on c4 or not. }
6. cxd5 exd5
{ The standard reaction to cxd5 that we have already seen a couple of times. This structure will either lead to an Isolated Queen's Pawn position, or White allows us to advance with c5-c4 which leads to very unbalanced positions. White has a couple of different moves that they can play here. As a thumb of rule to remember my recommendation after each move is that the tension in the centre will be resolved on the next move in some way. }
7. Bd3 c4
{ We can go for this structure again as we gain the tempo on the bishop. This gives us enough time to get in Bb4 and get our king out of the centre. }
8. Bc2 Bb4
{ The typical setup for these structures. The c3-knight is quite important as it puts pressure on d5 and helps White to get in the e4-break. That is one big difference with the 7. g3 line. There White was not aiming for the e4-break, but with the bishop on c2 instead it makes more sense. Another big difference with the 7. g3 line is that white's play there was more queenside orientated, whereas white's play here will be more kingside orientated.   Instead of  7...Bb4  ,  7...Bd6  was also a decent alternative. The bishop is much better placed on d6 if White does not have a blockade with g3. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5
{ White should opt for a plan connected to the kingside with f4. Afterwards White can think of expanding even more with f5 or g4, and the rook can now join via the f3-square. }
10... Nc6
{ The natural square for the knight in these structures. It not only challenges the e5-knight but can also reroute via e7 to f5. }
11. f4 Ne8
{ Instead,  10...Ne7  with the idea of improving our control over the kingside, or  10...a5  with the idea to play Ra6 next were also interesting ideas.   With  10...Ne8  we simply intend to meet  11.f5  with  11...f6  to halt White's kingside attack. If White does not play 11. f5 we can continue with Ne7, trying to control the f5-square. }
12. f5 f6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. e4
{ White's attack has not led anywhere, but he did get in the e4-break under decent circumstances. White's structure after  14...dxe4  is definitely not worse than ours, so we should simply leave the tension as it is. }
14... Nd6
{ We did not put the knight on e8 for it to stay there. We intend to resolve the tension in the centre and occupy the e4-square. }
15. exd5 Bxc3
{ We have to get rid of the c3-knight to get rid of the pressure in the centre. This was one of the ideas we already had in mind when playing 8... Bb4. }
16. bxc3 cxd5
{ With an unbalanced position. We intend to play Re8 next to occupy the e4-square with the knight. The f5-pawn is in a way overextended, and White has lost control over the e4-square. On the other hand White does have the bishop pair to compensate for this. Our a8-rook can join the battle via b8, or another way that I quite like is via a7 to e7. }
*

