[Round "?"]
[White "1) 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines: 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ A choice had to be made here between recommending  5...a6  or  5...Nc6  . The thing is that  5...Nc6  would make more sense in a way, because after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  we transpose to the lines we have seen after 5.cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7.Nf3.   However, after  5...Nc6  White is not obliged to play  6.cxd5  ,  or follow that up with Bb5 either. For example, after 5...Nc6  6.a3  is the most popular move, leading to different positions. White also has the option of playing  5...Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Be2  .   In general, I quite like the move  5...a6  as it has a more forcing nature and seems to lead to more non-standard positions. This is why I will recommend this move, and I don't think it will even mean that we have to do work. White does seem to have quite a few options after 5... Nc6 apart from the ones that have been shown via the other move order.   The idea of the move  5...a6  is very simple. First of all, it avoids the slightly annoying check/pin on b5. Second of all, it also 'threatens' to take on c4 as we are ready to follow it up with b5 whether White has recaptured on c4 or not. }
6. cxd5 exd5
{ The standard reaction to cxd5 that we have already seen a couple of times. This structure will either lead to an Isolated Queen's Pawn position, or White allows us to advance with c5-c4 which leads to very unbalanced positions. White has a couple of different moves that they can play here. As a thumb of rule to remember my recommendation after each move is that the tension in the centre will be resolved on the next move in some way. }
7. g3 c4
{ The bishop is quite nice on the g2 square in IQP positions, so I recommend the move c4 here. This is a structure that we will also see after 7. Bd3. I usually see this as a very ambitious and unbalanced structure. In the long term we would like to expand on the queenside with b5 and use the 3 vs 2 situation we have to create a passed pawn. In the meantime, things are not as simple for White with the 5 vs 4 majority on the kingside, as the e4-break is not that easy to get through. Without including f3, White can be left with an isolated pawn after dxe4. White typically plans to go for piece play in the centre or slow down or play on the queenside with b3.One thing that we have to be careful of in such positions is that the d5-pawn becomes weak. This is why we will typically go for a setup with Bb4, to put the knight on c3 under pressure. This makes it more difficult for White to get both the b3 and the e4-break in, and also deals with the pressure on d5. }
8. Bg2 Bb4 9. O-O O-O 10. Bd2
{ Protecting the knight on c3 in order to play for the b3-break. } 10... Nc6
{ The move  10...b5  would have been a bit too early, as it is not easy to maintain the pawn phalanx after  11.a4  . }
11. b3
{ Another typical plan. We can either allow the structure with bxc4 dxc4 after a move such as  11...Re8  ,  or try to get in b5. }
11... Bxc3
{ Giving up the bishop is necessary to get in b5, as the immediate  11...b5  would be unpleasant after  12.Ne5  . }
12. Bxc3 Ne4
{ Gaining a tempo on the bishop and blocking the diagonal of White's light-squared bishop. After White has dealt with the threat we can play b5. Although recapturing with bxc4 is quite fine, it is ideal for Black to recapture with dxc4 if possible. The pawn phalanx on the queenside can become incredibly strong. }
