6. cxd5 exd5
{ The standard reaction to cxd5 that we have already seen a couple of times. This structure will either lead to an Isolated Queen's Pawn position, or White allows us to advance with c5-c4 which leads to very unbalanced positions. White has a couple of different moves that they can play here. As a thumb of rule to remember my recommendation after each move is that the tension in the centre will be resolved on the next move in some way. }
7. Be2 cxd4
{ We should clarify the situation in the centre here immediately. Although most people have played  7...Nc6  here, it is more accurate to start with  7...cxd4  .  This is because we remain more flexible after both Nxd4 and exd4.   For example after  7...Nc6  8.O-O  ,  8...cxd4  is not that nice anymore because White can now play  9.exd4  followed by either Bg5 or Re1. So Black usually continues with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n2n2/2pp4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd6  , but this loses time after  9.dxc5  .   It is also not good to start with  7...c4  , as Black is in trouble after  8.O-O  b5  9.a4!  b4  10.Nxd5!!  with a crushing initiative for White after he follows up with 11. e4. This is big difference with 7. Bd3. There I do recommend 7...c4 as in that case we have enough time for it by gaining a tempo on the bishop. }
8. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now that we have clarified the situation on d4 we can play Nc6 since we don't have to deal with exd4 anymore. }
9. O-O Bd6
{ The typical setup for these IQP positions. We intend to get the same setup as we have seen in the 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bb5+ Nc6 7. Nf3 cxd4 IQP positions, but the specifics might be a little bit different here. }
10. Nxc6
{ Is a way in which a lot of players have continued, but it is not very impressive. }
10... bxc6 11. b3 h5
{ Generally a useful move in IQP/hanging pawn structures. In this case, Black is even immediately threatening a Greek Sacrifice with  12.--  Bxh2+  followed by Ng4+ with a devastating attack. }
12. h3
{ Stopping the sacrifice, but this weakening of the kingside is not great either for White. After an eventual battery on the h2-b8 diagonal White can now only respond with f4 due to the pawn on h3 which is under pressure. }
12... O-O
{ 12...Qe7  is also interesting, but the setup with Bb8 Qd6 is even stronger. This had to be prepared with 12... O-O as the immediate  12...Bb8  would have allowed  13.Ba3  . }
13. Bb2 Bb8
{ White is in a lot of trouble as Qd6 is coming, and will have to respond to this with f4. After having weakened the kingside so much we can put the bishop on a7 to aim for the newly created target, which is the e3-pawn. }
