1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Just continuing with normal development before making an important decision in the centre. We will leave it up to White to start trading in the centre for now. In the following positions cxd5 will typically be met with exd5. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ A choice had to be made here between recommending  5...a6  or  5...Nc6  . The thing is that  5...Nc6  would make more sense in a way, because after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  we transpose to the lines we have seen after 5.cxd5 exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7.Nf3.   However, after  5...Nc6  White is not obliged to play  6.cxd5  ,  or follow that up with Bb5 either. For example, after 5...Nc6  6.a3  is the most popular move, leading to different positions. White also has the option of playing  5...Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Be2  .   In general, I quite like the move  5...a6  as it has a more forcing nature and seems to lead to more non-standard positions. This is why I will recommend this move, and I don't think it will even mean that we have to do work. White does seem to have quite a few options after 5... Nc6 apart from the ones that have been shown via the other move order.   The idea of the move  5...a6  is very simple. First of all, it avoids the slightly annoying check/pin on b5. Second of all, it also 'threatens' to take on c4 as we are ready to follow it up with b5 whether White has recaptured on c4 or not. }
6. cxd5 exd5
{ The standard reaction to cxd5 that we have already seen a couple of times. This structure will either lead to an Isolated Queen's Pawn position, or White allows us to advance with c5-c4 which leads to very unbalanced positions. White has a couple of different moves that they can play here. As a thumb of rule to remember my recommendation after each move is that the tension in the centre will be resolved on the next move in some way. }
7. Be2 cxd4
{ We should clarify the situation in the centre here immediately. Although most people have played  7...Nc6  here, it is more accurate to start with  7...cxd4  .  This is because we remain more flexible after both Nxd4 and exd4.   For example after  7...Nc6  8.O-O  ,  8...cxd4  is not that nice anymore because White can now play  9.exd4  followed by either Bg5 or Re1. So Black usually continues with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n2n2/2pp4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd6  , but this loses time after  9.dxc5  .   It is also not good to start with  7...c4  , as Black is in trouble after  8.O-O  b5  9.a4!  b4  10.Nxd5!!  with a crushing initiative for White after he follows up with 11. e4. This is big difference with 7. Bd3. There I do recommend 7...c4 as in that case we have enough time for it by gaining a tempo on the bishop. }
8. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Now that we have clarified the situation on d4 we can play Nc6 since we don't have to deal with exd4 anymore. }
9. O-O Bd6
{ The typical setup for these IQP positions. We intend to get the same setup as we have seen in the 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bb5+ Nc6 7. Nf3 cxd4 IQP positions, but the specifics might be a little bit different here. }
10. b3 Qc7
{ More or less forcing  11.Nf3  . Usually White would like to respond to this move with  11.h3  , but that loses on the spot due to  11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Be5  . }
11. Nf3 Be6
{ We had to protect the d5-pawn, and now get into similar territory as we had in the 5. cxd5 lines. The main difference is the queen on c7. The queen is not ideal on c7 but we can improve it by playing Qe7 or Qd7 which are better squares in these IQP positions. This is also because we would eventually like to drop back the dark-squared bishop to b8. }
12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rc1 Rfe8
{ We will follow similar plans as in the 5.cxd5 lines, which are putting the rooks on e8 and d8. Afterwards we will switch back the queen to e7 to get even the exact same position. }
14. h3 Rad8 15. Bd3
{ The bishop is misplaced on e2 in these positions as the knight would actually like to reroute via e2. }
15... Qe7
{ Transposes to a position we have seen before after 5. cxd5 @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. I would like to refer to my comments there to explain this position for you to get a better understanding of it. The queen had to be moved from c7 as it was in the way of the dark-squared bishop.For a sideline chapter, this one was quite large. This is simply because 4. e3 is quite popular in practice and White has a lot of options in certain places. The IQP positions might be new for you and I wanted to do my best to explain them as well as I could. I hope you enjoyed the first chapter of this course and let's move on to what we are all here for, the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit! }
