[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 5.Qxd4: 7...Bd6 and Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Bd6 and Sidelines: 5. dxe6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. dxe6
{ This move should be mentioned somewhere, as it sets a trap. It is a rather bad move, but not because we can take the knight. }
5... Bxe6
{ If we had played  5...dxc3?  we would instantly be lost after  6.exf7+  Ke7  7.fxg8=N+!  Rxg8  8.Bg5+  winning the queen.   After  5...Bxe6  we are now threatening to take the knight. We also have a huge initiative and have not even sacrificed a pawn this time. }
6. Ne4 Nc6
{ We are not only ahead in development, but White's king and knight are quite vulnerable as well. Apart from that, our d4-pawn gives us a nice space advantage. }
7. Nf3 Bd5
{ There are several ways of getting a very nice position, but this feels most natural to me. We kick away the knight with tempo and afterwards it will be even more difficult for White to develop. }
8. Ng3 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Qb6
{ Followed by O-O-O with a great position. It will remain difficult for White to develop the light-squared bishop. The engine already gives a winning advantage for Black. }
