[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 5.Qxd4: 7...Bd6 and Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Bd6 and Sidelines: 6. Qa4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qa4
{ White makes it clear with this move that they don't want to grab the pawn, and instead play against the IQP that we will get. White does, however, get a really bad version of these typical IQP postions due to the time spent on moving the queen. }
6... exd5 7. e3 Nf6 8. Nf3 Bd6
{ We will just follow the typical IQP setups that we have seen in the 4th move sidelines chapter. We intend to castle next, put our rook on e8 and develop the light-squared bishop to an active square. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O a6
{ A typical move in IQP positions, with the idea of preventing Nb5. In the only game left remaining in this position, the White player did try  11.Nb5  , but got punished for it after  11...axb5!  12.Qxa8  Qb6  after which the queen was trapped. Black will move the light-squared bishop on the next move and win the game.Now that we have stopped White from playing Nb5, we can continue with our typical plan of playing Re8 and Bg4/Bf5 with a nice position for Black. }
