[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 5.Qxd4: 7...Bd6 and Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Bd6 and Sidelines: 7. e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. e3
{ Again, White should just be taking the pawn. White has at this point moved the queen twice already, giving us a nice version of the IQP positions that we have seen in the 4th move sidelines chapter. }
7... Nf6 8. Nf3 Bd6
{ This setup is possible due to  9.Nxd5  losing in a typical manner after  9...Nxd5  10.Qxd5  Bb4+  winning the queen. Once White has castled, the d5 pawn still can't be taken due to Bxh2+ instead, winning material. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Re8
{ Again, the d5-pawn cannot be captured:  11.Nxd5??  Nxd5  12.Qxd5  Bxh2+  winning the queen. }
11. b3 Ne4
{ We can play the position slowly with typical moves such as  11...a6  , but the direct move  11...Ne4  leads to a position that is slightlly more pleasant for Black. }
12. Bb2
{ 12.Nxd5  would have given us a powerful initiative after  12...Be6  . Not only are we threatening  13.--  Bxd5  14.Qxd5  Bxh2+  winning the game, White is also still underdeveloped and weakened on the a1-f6 diagonal. }
12... Ba3
{ A powerful tactical shot. The idea is to destabilize white's position to get in the d5-d4 break after trading off a couple of minor pieces. }
13. Bxa3 Nxc3 14. Qd2 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2
{ It seems like we are going a bit deep here, but there are actually still two games left in this position. Both games continued with  15...Bg4  with a pleasant position for Black. Instead,  15...d4  is also quite an interesting alternative. }
15... Bg4
{ As mentioned,  15...d4  is also an interesting alternative. The idea is that after a move such as  16.Rad1  , we gain a tempo with  16...Qa5  ,  unpinning the d-pawn. We can play dxe3 afterwards, with a pleasant position as White will have to ruin their kingside pawn structure with fxe3. However, 15...Bg4 has worked well in practice for Black, and also leads to a pleasant position even after good defense by White. }
16. Bb2
{ 16.Rfd1!  was the only move to keep an okay position for White. After  16...Ne5  , Black still has a nice initiative as white's king is about to get vulnerable.   16.Bb2  looks natural, but it doesn't actually stop d4. It does stop Ne5, but  16...d4  will renew the threat of Ne5. }
16... d4 17. h3 d3
{ A nice inbetween move that makes it difficult for White to keep coordination. The passed pawn on d3 will make it difficult for White to get defenders to the kingside. }
18. Qd2 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qd7
{ Even stronger than the game move  19...Ne5  , which still gave Black a winning advantage in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Darga, K @@StartBracket@@2505@@EndBracket@@-Nunn, J @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ Elvetham Hall 1979. Up to this point, Black basically played perfectly, and White simply collapsed under the pressure. }
