{ An improvement over the games Mamedyarov-van Foreest and Rakhmanov-Grischuk which saw  10...Qb6  and  10...Ng4  respectively. Although both are inaccurate moves, van Foreest and Grischuk did manage to draw their games eventually.   After further inspection, it turns out that after  10...Qb6  11.Bg2  Rd8  12.Qa4  h6  13.O-O  Be6  it is not that easy for White to prove an advantage. I do not really see a reason to go there however, as it seems like White still has some options to put Black under pressure.  11.Qxd6  would have been a mistake as after  11...Rd8  followed by Nb4 would have been pretty good for Black. The deadly check on c2 will be difficult to stop.   The move  10...Qe7  prepares to put the rook on d8, while also keeping control of the e-file. }
11. Bg2 Rd8
{ The rook should in general go to this square, but in this case we are also threatening Bxg3 as a discovered attack. The other rook will eventually go to c8, but first we have to decide on a square for our light-squared bishop. The square we will choose depends on where White will try to hide their queen. }
12. Qc2 Nb4
{ A logical move after White's last move. Nb4 is a typical idea in these positions, not only activating the knight, but also trying to reroute to d5. From there it will take out the c3-knight, which is a very important defender of White's queenside and e-pawn.   The setup with  12...h6  13.O-O  Bc5  does not work as well as it did after 12. Qa4. This is because  14.Na4  causes some trouble, a square that was not available to the knight in the 12. Qa4 line. }
13. Qb1 Bc5
{ The immediate  13...Nbd5  is also an interesting alternative. The advantage is that after  14.O-O  we have the option to transpose back to 13...Bc5 with  14...Bc5  , but also have the extra option of playing  14...Nxc3  instead. 13...Nbd5 does also give White an extra option however, which is  14.Nxd5  . After  14...Nxd5  15.O-O  Qxe2  we have won the pawn back, but White now takes over the initiative with  16.Re1  Qa6  17.Bg5  . Black should be okay there after  17...Nf6  ,  but in general I am not a big fan of 13...Nbd5. Apart from the extra option of 14.Nxd5, it is not clear why we would like to play  13...Nbd5  14.O-O  Nxc3  either, as after  15.bxc3  Bc5  White can at the very least transpose back to 13...Bc5 14.0-0 Nbd5 15.Bg5 Nxc3 16. bxc3  with  16.Bg5  , but also has other options in that position. }
14. O-O Nbd5
{ The typical idea in these lines, trying to get rid of the defender of the e2-pawn. In general the c3-knight is defending important squares. }
15. Nxd5 Rxd5
{ As we are not only threatening to take the e2-pawn, but also Bf5 is now suddenly a deadly option, White has to find a good follow-up. }
16. Nh4
{ Attacking the rook and preventing Bf5. The knight is not ideal on h4 however, and we have a very strong and concrete way of playing here. }
16... Qxe2
{ A very tricky move, that can easily lead to a quick defeat for White. We simply are dominating the board if White does not do something quick. Instead,  16...Rd8  was also a very playable alternative, as we still have quite a lot of compensation. }
17. Bf3 { This seems to win on the spot, but we have a neat tactic. } 17...
Qxf3 { Momentarily giving up the queen, but we will win back one soon. } 18.
Nxf3 Bf5
{ As White's queen is trapped we will win back the lost material. Afterwards, what is left is a more active position for us. }
