[White "2) 5.Qxd4: 7...Bd6 and Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Bd6 and Sidelines: 8. Nf3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. This chapter will be devoted to  7...Bd6  and the sidelines before the position after 7. Qxd5 arises, while  7...Qc7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
7... Bd6
{ The point of this move is to stop the queens from being swapped off while still helping with development. The downside of this move is that the bishop is not really ideal on d6. We will see lines after  8.Bg5  in which it is quite vulnerable on d6, but sometimes it can be sacrificed for a counter attack.White can also go for setups with g3, in which the bishop is facing granite on the kingside. In the 5. Qa4+ chapters, we will go for a setup with Bc5 in a similar position. Due to the pressure on f2, White will respond to it using a setup with e3-Be2. This blocks the g1-a7 diagonal, but later on the bishop can switch back to d6 to attack on the h2-b8 diagonal instead.Playing g3 and e3 with the bishop on e2 will severly weaken the kingside. Here, however, White can omit e3 and just play g3 followed by Bg2 and castle kingside safely. This means that we will not be able to get a kingside attack going and instead just have to use general activity as compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
8. Nf3
{ The most solid setup for White, and probably the one that I would like to face the least. White intends to play g3-Bg2-O-O next and just stabilize the position. After the queen is attacked it will likely drop back to d1.   White can also choose to start with  8.g3  , but there is not really a big difference. Things will likely transpose after  8...Nf6  9.Qd1  O-O  10.Nf3  or  10.Bg2  Qe7  11.Nf3  . }
8... Nf6 9. Qd1 O-O
{ For now we are simply finishing our development. Afterwards we can see what setup White has chosen and respond to it. }
10. g3
{ Both Grischuk and van Foreest went astray here. A setup with  10.e3  does not make too much sense in this line, as it is just a bad version of 5. Qa4+ for White. This is because in the e3-setups, our bishop is ideal on d6 and on top of that we did not waste a move on playing 5...Bd7. Black can simply continue with  10...Qe7  11.Be2  Rd8  and enjoy great compensation for the pawn. }
10... Qe7
{ An improvement over the games Mamedyarov-van Foreest and Rakhmanov-Grischuk which saw  10...Qb6  and  10...Ng4  respectively. Although both are inaccurate moves, van Foreest and Grischuk did manage to draw their games eventually.   After further inspection, it turns out that after  10...Qb6  11.Bg2  Rd8  12.Qa4  h6  13.O-O  Be6  it is not that easy for White to prove an advantage. I do not really see a reason to go there however, as it seems like White still has some options to put Black under pressure.  11.Qxd6  would have been a mistake as after  11...Rd8  followed by Nb4 would have been pretty good for Black. The deadly check on c2 will be difficult to stop.   The move  10...Qe7  prepares to put the rook on d8, while also keeping control of the e-file. }
11. Bg2 Rd8
{ The rook should in general go to this square, but in this case we are also threatening Bxg3 as a discovered attack. The other rook will eventually go to c8, but first we have to decide on a square for our light-squared bishop. The square we will choose depends on where White will try to hide their queen. }
12. Qc2 Nb4
{ A logical move after White's last move. Nb4 is a typical idea in these positions, not only activating the knight, but also trying to reroute to d5. From there it will take out the c3-knight, which is a very important defender of White's queenside and e-pawn.   The setup with  12...h6  13.O-O  Bc5  does not work as well as it did after 12. Qa4. This is because  14.Na4  causes some trouble, a square that was not available to the knight in the 12. Qa4 line. }
13. Qb1 Bc5
{ The immediate  13...Nbd5  is also an interesting alternative. The advantage is that after  14.O-O  we have the option to transpose back to 13...Bc5 with  14...Bc5  , but also have the extra option of playing  14...Nxc3  instead. 13...Nbd5 does also give White an extra option however, which is  14.Nxd5  . After  14...Nxd5  15.O-O  Qxe2  we have won the pawn back, but White now takes over the initiative with  16.Re1  Qa6  17.Bg5  . Black should be okay there after  17...Nf6  ,  but in general I am not a big fan of 13...Nbd5. Apart from the extra option of 14.Nxd5, it is not clear why we would like to play  13...Nbd5  14.O-O  Nxc3  either, as after  15.bxc3  Bc5  White can at the very least transpose back to 13...Bc5 14.0-0 Nbd5 15.Bg5 Nxc3 16. bxc3  with  16.Bg5  , but also has other options in that position. }
14. O-O Nbd5
{ The typical idea in these lines, trying to get rid of the defender of the e2-pawn. In general the c3-knight is defending important squares. }
15. Bg5
{ Probably the easiest and most pleasant way of playing for White, as White finally gets to make an active move. It costs him the e2-pawn, however. }
15... Nxc3 16. bxc3 Qxe2 17. Nd4
{ A nice move, opening up the diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. We do not want to give up our bishop pair on d4, and should retreat the queen instead. }
17... Qa6
{ As b7 was under attack, this square makes the most sense. From here the queen is also defending the knight on f6, so that we can always recapture with the queen and don't have to damage our pawn structure.In general, we intend to deal with some of the pressure on our position by playing h6 next. Afterwards we can think of dealing with the pressure on b7. This can be done with moves such as Qb6, blocking the b-file and also putting more pressure on the knight. White should have a slightly more pleasant position here, due to the activity.   This position is probably the main reason why I personally prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  over  7...Bd6  . After  7...Qc7  it is not as easy for White to give the pawn back for activity. The reason why I have a preference for  7...Qc7  is not for objective reasons, as I will show in my analysis that  7...Bd6  is fine as well.  7...Qc7  just seems like a better fighting option, but your opinion can easily differ, especially if you see the lines that arise after  7...Bd6  8.Bg5  . }
