{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. This chapter will be devoted to  7...Bd6  and the sidelines before the position after 7. Qxd5 arises, while  7...Qc7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
7... Bd6
{ The point of this move is to stop the queens from being swapped off while still helping with development. The downside of this move is that the bishop is not really ideal on d6. We will see lines after  8.Bg5  in which it is quite vulnerable on d6, but sometimes it can be sacrificed for a counter attack.White can also go for setups with g3, in which the bishop is facing granite on the kingside. In the 5. Qa4+ chapters, we will go for a setup with Bc5 in a similar position. Due to the pressure on f2, White will respond to it using a setup with e3-Be2. This blocks the g1-a7 diagonal, but later on the bishop can switch back to d6 to attack on the h2-b8 diagonal instead.Playing g3 and e3 with the bishop on e2 will severly weaken the kingside. Here, however, White can omit e3 and just play g3 followed by Bg2 and castle kingside safely. This means that we will not be able to get a kingside attack going and instead just have to use general activity as compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
8. Bg5
{ The most common move, but I think it is a somewhat risky one, especially when White has this Nf3-g3-Bg2 setup at their disposal. }
8... Nge7
{ We normally develop the knight to f6 in the Schara Gambit, but in this case it was not good. That is because after  8...Nf6  9.Qd2  the pin is very annoying, and we cannot go for something like  9...h6  due to  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Ne4  forcing  11...Bb4  and all the trades that come with it. }
9. Qd2
{ The most logical square for the queen this time. Typically in Schara Gambit positions, it returns to d1. In this case however, the dark-squared bishop is already developed and we have put our knight on e7 instead. This means that in the future, the queen is not really a target on d2 as we do not have Ne4 as an idea at our disposal. Apart from that, White is simply preparing Rd1, making use of the vulnerable bishop on d6. }
9... h6
{ Rd1 was coming, and it is quite annoying to deal with. The idea that we will use is a counterattack on b2 by playing Qb2. After Qxd6 Qxb2 it is difficult for White to keep protecting the rook and knight, but in the version  9...Qb6??  10.Qxd6  Qxb2  the move  11.Rc1  is possible. That is why we play h6, to go for this idea once the bishop has retreated to h4. }
10. Bh4 Qb6 11. Rd1
{ 11.Qxd6?  would not only lose a pawn after  11...Qxb2  12.Rd1  Qxc3+  13.Qd2  Qa3  ,  but also leads to a bad position as O-O followed by Rd8 is coming with a strong attack. }
11... Bb4
{ Once we are forced to move the bishop, b4 is usually the go-to square in these lines. White is still very far away from getting the king castled kingside, and dealing with the pin will cost even more time. }
12. a3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Nf5
{ White was about to stabilize with f3-Bf2-e4, so that had to be prevented. With this move we gain a tempo on the bishop, prevent f3, and protect g7. }
14. Bg3 O-O
{ We will develop our bishop to e6 next and then get the rooks into the game. }
15. e3 Be6
{ Followed by Rac8 and Rfd8 we have quite a strong initiative on the queenside that will be difficult to deal with for White. Afterwards we can play moves such as Na5 or even Ncd4 in some cases to really get our queenside play started. }
*

