{ Rd1 was coming, and it is quite annoying to deal with. The idea that we will use is a counterattack on b2 by playing Qb2. After Qxd6 Qxb2 it is difficult for White to keep protecting the rook and knight, but in the version  9...Qb6??  10.Qxd6  Qxb2  the move  11.Rc1  is possible. That is why we play h6, to go for this idea once the bishop has retreated to h4. }
10. Bxe7
{ Is possible, but not a very impressive move. Giving up the bishop pair in such an open position is not a good idea. }
10... Qxe7
{ We intend to get in O-O followed by Rd8 quickly, which will be annoying to deal with for White. That is why White should take immediate action with 11. Rd1 here. }
11. Rd1 Bb4
{ The most logical square, as allowing the knight to jump to d5 would not be ideal. The knight would be quite dominant and protecting quite a few important squares. The pin is difficult to deal with, as  12.a3  Ba5  13.b4  is pretty bad. }
12. a3 Ba5
{ With O-O, Rd8, Bg4 and Rac8 coming, it is clear that we have quite a powerful initiative. b5-b4 might even be an idea.   Apart from that,  13.b4  is also not possible, as White is simply lost after  13...Nxb4!  14.axb4  Qxb4  15.Rc1  Be6  followed by Rac8. }
