8. Bg5
{ The most common move, but I think it is a somewhat risky one, especially when White has this Nf3-g3-Bg2 setup at their disposal. }
8... Nge7
{ We normally develop the knight to f6 in the Schara Gambit, but in this case it was not good. That is because after  8...Nf6  9.Qd2  the pin is very annoying, and we cannot go for something like  9...h6  due to  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Ne4  forcing  11...Bb4  and all the trades that come with it. }
9. Qd2
{ The most logical square for the queen this time. Typically in Schara Gambit positions, it returns to d1. In this case however, the dark-squared bishop is already developed and we have put our knight on e7 instead. This means that in the future, the queen is not really a target on d2 as we do not have Ne4 as an idea at our disposal. Apart from that, White is simply preparing Rd1, making use of the vulnerable bishop on d6. }
9... h6
{ Rd1 was coming, and it is quite annoying to deal with. The idea that we will use is a counterattack on b2 by playing Qb2. After Qxd6 Qxb2 it is difficult for White to keep protecting the rook and knight, but in the version  9...Qb6??  10.Qxd6  Qxb2  the move  11.Rc1  is possible. That is why we play h6, to go for this idea once the bishop has retreated to h4. }
10. Rd1
{ A direct counterattack. In general, trading pieces should favour White. Here, we do get a nice pawn on g5 back for it, and the queen will be exposed on d6. This move was used by Wesley So to defeat Grischuk in the Champions Chess Tour of last year. }
10... hxg5
{ Although we will not really be using the open h-file, having the pawn on g5 is quite nice. On g5 or g4 it will be able to gain space on the kingside and restricts white's pieces, especially white's kingside knight. }
11. Qxd6 Qb6
{ The typical square for our queen, attacking the weakness on b2. Instead, the alternative  11...Qa5  is also an interesting novelty. However, after  12.Qa3  Qxa3  13.bxa3  White is the one playing for an advantage with the extra pawn. Things are not that easy to prove for White after  13...O-O  14.e3  Be6  15.Nf3  f6  , but I do not really see a good reason to recommend this endgame. }
12. Qa3
{ Not only the most popular move, but also clearly the best one. b2 had to be defended, and this is the right way to do so. The queen could have also retreated back to d2 to defend b2, but it is much more vulnerable on d2 with a rook soon coming to d8. }
12... O-O
{ An improvement by Grischuk over the existing games. In all of them,  12...Be6  was played instead. This is also the only move that was discussed by David Martinez in his 1.d4 repertoire for Chessable. It is hard to blame David, as the opening theory has been very rapidly evolving since the year 2021. }
13. Nf3
{ The idea of this move in comparison to 13. e3 is to be able to meet  13...Nb4  14.Qa4  Bf5  with  15.Nd4  . Thus, we will have to adopt another way of playing. }
13... Be6
{ We intend to play Nb4 on the next move, and we could have also started with  13...Nb4  instead. However, after  14.Qa4  Be6  White has the extra option of  15.Nxg5  instead of  15.e3  @@StartBracket@@which would transpose back to our notes here of 13...Be6@@EndBracket@@.   Now after  13...Be6  14.Nxg5  , we can play  14...Nb4  but have the alternative  14...Nf5  as well. I will recommend  14...Nb4  ,  so starting with 13...Nb4 or 13...Be6 won't actually make a big difference. Starting with 13...Be6, is a bit more flexible, however. }
14. Nxg5 Nb4 15. Qa4
{ Forced, as Nc2+ simply can't be allowed.  15.Rd2  would lose to  15...Rad8  and  15.Rc1  would not lead to any good either after  15...Ned5  . }
15... Nxa2
{ A typical idea in these lines. White's king is quite a lot of moves away from castling and counting the defenders and attackers that are actually in play after our piece sacrifice will leave us with a rook up. }
16. Nxa2 Bxa2
{ 16...Bb3  is in similar situations an interesting move as well, but this time  17.Qh4  with a mate threat on h7 is quite annoying. Even there, after  17...Rfc8  things are unclear and probably pretty difficult for White in practice. }
17. Qxa2 Qb4+
{ This pin will remain very annoying for White. We force the rook to d2, leaving the back rank undefended. Apart from that, the rook will also become a nice target for our attack. }
18. Rd2 Rac8
{ Not targetting the rook on d2, but the back-rank instead.  19.Qb1  is forced, as  19.Kd1  would be punished with  19...Qc5  ,  threatening both Qc1# and Qxg5. After forcing the queen to protect the back-rank, our other rook can join in on the action on d8, as now f7 is not under attack anymore. }
19. Qb1
{ One thing that we have to be careful of, is that White is actually threatening checkmate with Qh7 here. We can deal with it in a useful way however. }
19... Rfd8
{ Both preventing  20.Qh7+  as after  20...Kf8  21.Qh8+  Ng8  our king is completely safe, and also brining in another attacker. }
20. Nf3
{ We could force a draw here with  20...Rxd2  21.Nxd2  Rd8  22.Qc2  Rc8  23.Qb1  Rd8  ,  but we also have the option of continuing the game with 20... Nd5. }
20... Nd5
{ Not forcing the draw, but i'm not sure exactly who is to be preferred after the following forcing sequence. With this move we are threatening to play Nc3-Ne4, so White has to play  21.Qd1  here. Afterwards we can get the knight to e4 anyway via f6. }
21. Qd1 Nf6 22. e3 Ne4 23. Nd4
{ Finally, White has been able to block the d-file, but this comes at the cost of an exchange. Our attack continues for a bit, and White will have to give up the b2-pawn as well to stop it. }
23... Nxd2 24. Qxd2 Rc1+ { Cleverly making use of the pin. } 25. Ke2 Qc4+ 26.
Qd3 Qa2
{ After this long forcing sequence, we will win the pawn on b2. Afterwards we are left with a position where White has two minor pieces for a rook. Usually this is quite nice for the player with the minor pieces, but due to White's inactive and uncoordinated pieces the position is rather unclear. I am not sure which side I would like to play with during a practical game here. It is not necessary to remember all of these moves, but I think it is a good example of how powerful our initiative on the queenside really is. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 5.Qxd4: 7...Bd6 and Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Bd6 and Sidelines: 8. Bg5 #5 (alternative 14... Nf5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. This chapter will be devoted to  7...Bd6  and the sidelines before the position after 7. Qxd5 arises, while  7...Qc7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
7... Bd6
{ The point of this move is to stop the queens from being swapped off while still helping with development. The downside of this move is that the bishop is not really ideal on d6. We will see lines after  8.Bg5  in which it is quite vulnerable on d6, but sometimes it can be sacrificed for a counter attack.White can also go for setups with g3, in which the bishop is facing granite on the kingside. In the 5. Qa4+ chapters, we will go for a setup with Bc5 in a similar position. Due to the pressure on f2, White will respond to it using a setup with e3-Be2. This blocks the g1-a7 diagonal, but later on the bishop can switch back to d6 to attack on the h2-b8 diagonal instead.Playing g3 and e3 with the bishop on e2 will severly weaken the kingside. Here, however, White can omit e3 and just play g3 followed by Bg2 and castle kingside safely. This means that we will not be able to get a kingside attack going and instead just have to use general activity as compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
8. Bg5
{ The most common move, but I think it is a somewhat risky one, especially when White has this Nf3-g3-Bg2 setup at their disposal. }
8... Nge7
{ We normally develop the knight to f6 in the Schara Gambit, but in this case it was not good. That is because after  8...Nf6  9.Qd2  the pin is very annoying, and we cannot go for something like  9...h6  due to  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Ne4  forcing  11...Bb4  and all the trades that come with it. }
9. Qd2
{ The most logical square for the queen this time. Typically in Schara Gambit positions, it returns to d1. In this case however, the dark-squared bishop is already developed and we have put our knight on e7 instead. This means that in the future, the queen is not really a target on d2 as we do not have Ne4 as an idea at our disposal. Apart from that, White is simply preparing Rd1, making use of the vulnerable bishop on d6. }
9... h6
{ Rd1 was coming, and it is quite annoying to deal with. The idea that we will use is a counterattack on b2 by playing Qb2. After Qxd6 Qxb2 it is difficult for White to keep protecting the rook and knight, but in the version  9...Qb6??  10.Qxd6  Qxb2  the move  11.Rc1  is possible. That is why we play h6, to go for this idea once the bishop has retreated to h4. }
10. Rd1
{ A direct counterattack. In general, trading pieces should favour White. Here, we do get a nice pawn on g5 back for it, and the queen will be exposed on d6. This move was used by Wesley So to defeat Grischuk in the Champions Chess Tour of last year. }
10... hxg5
{ Although we will not really be using the open h-file, having the pawn on g5 is quite nice. On g5 or g4 it will be able to gain space on the kingside and restricts white's pieces, especially white's kingside knight. }
11. Qxd6 Qb6
{ The typical square for our queen, attacking the weakness on b2. Instead, the alternative  11...Qa5  is also an interesting novelty. However, after  12.Qa3  Qxa3  13.bxa3  White is the one playing for an advantage with the extra pawn. Things are not that easy to prove for White after  13...O-O  14.e3  Be6  15.Nf3  f6  , but I do not really see a good reason to recommend this endgame. }
12. Qa3
{ Not only the most popular move, but also clearly the best one. b2 had to be defended, and this is the right way to do so. The queen could have also retreated back to d2 to defend b2, but it is much more vulnerable on d2 with a rook soon coming to d8. }
12... O-O
{ An improvement by Grischuk over the existing games. In all of them,  12...Be6  was played instead. This is also the only move that was discussed by David Martinez in his 1.d4 repertoire for Chessable. It is hard to blame David, as the opening theory has been very rapidly evolving since the year 2021. }
13. Nf3
{ The idea of this move in comparison to 13. e3 is to be able to meet  13...Nb4  14.Qa4  Bf5  with  15.Nd4  . Thus, we will have to adopt another way of playing. }
13... Be6
{ We intend to play Nb4 on the next move, and we could have also started with  13...Nb4  instead. However, after  14.Qa4  Be6  White has the extra option of  15.Nxg5  instead of  15.e3  @@StartBracket@@which would transpose back to our notes here of 13...Be6@@EndBracket@@.   Now after  13...Be6  14.Nxg5  , we can play  14...Nb4  but have the alternative  14...Nf5  as well. I will recommend  14...Nb4  ,  so starting with 13...Nb4 or 13...Be6 won't actually make a big difference. Starting with 13...Be6, is a bit more flexible, however. }
14. Nxg5 Nf5
{ An interesting alternative. The idea is to start sacrificing once White moves up the e-pawn. We keep the move Nb4 as an idea as well. By best play, this move should probably lead to a draw. }
15. Nxe6
{ Although this opens the f-file, it makes sense in a way. The knight on g5 was a target. For example, after  15.e3?  we can play  15...Nxe3!  16.fxe3  Qxe3+  17.Be2  Qxg5  . Having won back both sacrificed pawns gives us an excellent position as we still have the initiative and a safer king. }
15... fxe6
{ With Nb4 coming and the open f-file we have quite a strong attack. } 16. e3
Nb4 { Getting in an extra attacker before sacrificing on e3 makes sense. } 17.
Qa4 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Qxe3+ 19. Be2 Qf2+ 20. Kd2
{ The attack looks dangerous, but there is nothing better than a draw here. It can be made with the simple  20...Qf4+  21.Ke1  Qf2+  22.Kd2  , and another way of doing it is with  20...Rad8+  or  20...Rfd8+  . }
20... Qf4+ { A draw is the best both sides can get here. } *

