{ Not only the most popular move, but also clearly the best one. b2 had to be defended, and this is the right way to do so. The queen could have also retreated back to d2 to defend b2, but it is much more vulnerable on d2 with a rook soon coming to d8. }
12... O-O
{ An improvement by Grischuk over the existing games. In all of them,  12...Be6  was played instead. This is also the only move that was discussed by David Martinez in his 1.d4 repertoire for Chessable. It is hard to blame David, as the opening theory has been very rapidly evolving since the year 2021. }
13. Nf3
{ The idea of this move in comparison to 13. e3 is to be able to meet  13...Nb4  14.Qa4  Bf5  with  15.Nd4  . Thus, we will have to adopt another way of playing. }
13... Be6
{ We intend to play Nb4 on the next move, and we could have also started with  13...Nb4  instead. However, after  14.Qa4  Be6  White has the extra option of  15.Nxg5  instead of  15.e3  @@StartBracket@@which would transpose back to our notes here of 13...Be6@@EndBracket@@.   Now after  13...Be6  14.Nxg5  , we can play  14...Nb4  but have the alternative  14...Nf5  as well. I will recommend  14...Nb4  ,  so starting with 13...Nb4 or 13...Be6 won't actually make a big difference. Starting with 13...Be6, is a bit more flexible, however. }
14. e3
{ This transposes back to a couple of games that started with 12... Be6. }
14... Nb4 15. Qa4 Nxa2
{ A second novelty in the same line, that's something that does not happen too often! This is the same tactic as the one we saw in the 14.Nxg5 line, but with a different idea in mind. As White has not gone Nxg5, there is an extra defender and we intend to play Bb3 next this time instead of Bxa2. }
16. Nxa2 Bb3
{ 16...Bxa2  17.Qxa2  Qb4+  would not give a lot of play for the sacrificed piece. After  18.Nd2  White will soon be able to castle to safety. }
17. Qb5 Bxd1
{ Although taking the knight is possible now, taking the exchange seems even better as it stops White from exchanging the queens. White would still be down an exchange after  18.Qxb6  axb6  19.Kxd1  as we can play  19...Rxa2  . }
18. Kxd1 Rfd8+
{ The most logical move, getting in another attacker. After  19.Kc1  we continue with  19...Qc7+  , forcing  20.Nc3  . The blockader can be removed with  20...Nd5  after which the attack continues. We intend to get the other rook to c8 to join the attack as well.Analysis could be continued here, but it seems better to stop, not to get in too deep. Especially since the alternative 17...Bxa2 is probably also okay for us. 14... g4 was instead also an interesting alternative, and it is good sign for us. In many instances, even in the most critical lines of the Schara Gambit, we will see that we have alternatives on the road. }
*

