9... h6
{ Rd1 was coming, and it is quite annoying to deal with. The idea that we will use is a counterattack on b2 by playing Qb2. After Qxd6 Qxb2 it is difficult for White to keep protecting the rook and knight, but in the version  9...Qb6??  10.Qxd6  Qxb2  the move  11.Rc1  is possible. That is why we play h6, to go for this idea once the bishop has retreated to h4. }
10. Rd1
{ A direct counterattack. In general, trading pieces should favour White. Here, we do get a nice pawn on g5 back for it, and the queen will be exposed on d6. This move was used by Wesley So to defeat Grischuk in the Champions Chess Tour of last year. }
10... hxg5
{ Although we will not really be using the open h-file, having the pawn on g5 is quite nice. On g5 or g4 it will be able to gain space on the kingside and restricts white's pieces, especially white's kingside knight. }
11. Qxd6 Qb6
{ The typical square for our queen, attacking the weakness on b2. Instead, the alternative  11...Qa5  is also an interesting novelty. However, after  12.Qa3  Qxa3  13.bxa3  White is the one playing for an advantage with the extra pawn. Things are not that easy to prove for White after  13...O-O  14.e3  Be6  15.Nf3  f6  , but I do not really see a good reason to recommend this endgame. }
12. Qa3
{ Not only the most popular move, but also clearly the best one. b2 had to be defended, and this is the right way to do so. The queen could have also retreated back to d2 to defend b2, but it is much more vulnerable on d2 with a rook soon coming to d8. }
12... O-O
{ An improvement by Grischuk over the existing games. In all of them,  12...Be6  was played instead. This is also the only move that was discussed by David Martinez in his 1.d4 repertoire for Chessable. It is hard to blame David, as the opening theory has been very rapidly evolving since the year 2021. }
13. e3
{ Wesley So chose  13.e3  in his game against Grischuk, but to me  13.Nf3  also seems like an interesting alternative, and probably a better move. Having already spend 4 minutes on 10. Rd1, Wesley was clearly out of his notes here. }
13... Be6
{ Although  13...Nb4  seems best, this is perhaps the lazy way to go for us, intending to transpose back to our notes of 13.Nf3 as the lines transpose after  13...Be6  14.Nf3  now. The only critical alternative this gives to White is  14.Bb5  ,  after which we will continue in the same fashion as I have shown after 13...Bf5 14. Bb5. }
14. Bb5
{ Stopping Nb4, and getting ready to finish development with Nge2/Nf3. } 14...
Rad8
{ As White does not want to allow Rxd1+ which would be akward to recapture, this forces the trade on d8. This will give us full control over the open file. }
15. Rxd8 Rxd8 16. Nge2
{ The safer way of continuing for White, as the knight will be less exposed on e2. It also defends the other knight, so if we play Nd5-Nxc3 here, White can just recapture with Nxc3 and defend the bishop again. }
16... a6
{ The bishops are the best minor pieces in these open positions, so it is a good idea to target them. We don't have much better to do for now, and by playing a6 we will be able to put our bishop on c4 to claim this strong diagonal for ourselves. Once White has castled we can also enter with our rook on d2. }
17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. O-O Bc4
{ With a nice initiative on the queenside. With Rd2 incoming, we definitely have great compensation for the sacrificed pawn. The pawn on g5 also seems like a nice trump, as it restricts White's pieces and pawns on the kingside. }
