7... Qc7
{ 7...Bd6  looks more active, but the downside is that the bishop is not ideal on d6. c5 is usually the most active square, and by playing  7...Qc7  we intend to let the bishop reach that square.The downside of  7...Qc7  is that typically the e7-square is optimal for our queen. In practice, the move 7... Qc7 has been seen only very rarely. }
8. Qg5
{ This move is a typical computer move. So far it has not been played in over the board or online games, but it has been seen a couple of times in correspondence chess. The idea is to support the bishop to come to f4 and if the queen is kicked away, then White can bring it back to g3 to offer a queen exchange. }
8... Be6
{ So far players have continued with the normal  8...Nf6  . With  8...Be6  we have some deeper intentions. The idea is that later on in the lines when Qg3 happens, we want to be able to respond with Bd6. By playing Bd6 we sacrifice the g7-pawn, but we can respond to Qxg7 with Be5. However, if we have played Nf6, Qxg7 will come with a double attack. This means that the move Be6 serves as a useful waiting move. We are interested in seeing how White will develop and can now respond adequately to it. An advantage of having played Be6 is that we can castle queenside quickly in some cases.   Concretely speaking, what I did not like about  8...Nf6  was  9.e4  . After  9...h6  White has  10.Qg3  which cannot be met with  10...Bd6  , while White also seems to be better after  10...Qa5  11.Bb5  .   Instead of 9...h6 we can also play  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppq2ppp/2n2n2/6Q1/4P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be6  , but then after  10.Bf4  Qb6  11.Qb5  White seems to get an advantage in the endgame due to the extra pawn. }
9. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now we do develop the knight to f6. We will soon see the exact difference between 10. e4 here and 9. e4. }
10. Bf4 Qb6 11. Qb5
{ This line is similar to @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/ppq2ppp/2n1b3/6Q1/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bf4  Qb6  10.Qb5  .  However, the inclusion of Nf3 and Nf6 will change some details. }
11... Qxb5 12. Nxb5 Bb4+
{ We react here in the same way as in the 9.Bf4 line. The difference, though, is that White is now able to play Bd2 and recapture with the knight.   On the other hand,  13.Nc3  should not be advised as we get a lot of counterplay after  13...Ne4  . }
13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Nb4
{ A typical way of getting counterplay, although it seems to be an odd thing to do since White was threatening a fork on c7. Our counterfork on c2 is much more dangerous however, as we are much better developed. }
15. Nd4
{ White should really stop Nc2+. After  15.Nc7+  Ke7  16.Nxa8  Nc2+  17.Kd1  Nxa1  18.Nc7  Bxa2  White is just dead lost due to our initiative and attack against the king. }
15... Rc8
{ Followed by Ke7 with ideas such as Nc2+ or Rfd8 to bring in the forces. It is obvious we have plenty of compensation for the pawn. }
