{ So far players have continued with the normal  8...Nf6  . With  8...Be6  we have some deeper intentions. The idea is that later on in the lines when Qg3 happens, we want to be able to respond with Bd6. By playing Bd6 we sacrifice the g7-pawn, but we can respond to Qxg7 with Be5. However, if we have played Nf6, Qxg7 will come with a double attack. This means that the move Be6 serves as a useful waiting move. We are interested in seeing how White will develop and can now respond adequately to it. An advantage of having played Be6 is that we can castle queenside quickly in some cases.   Concretely speaking, what I did not like about  8...Nf6  was  9.e4  . After  9...h6  White has  10.Qg3  which cannot be met with  10...Bd6  , while White also seems to be better after  10...Qa5  11.Bb5  .   Instead of 9...h6 we can also play  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppq2ppp/2n2n2/6Q1/4P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be6  , but then after  10.Bf4  Qb6  11.Qb5  White seems to get an advantage in the endgame due to the extra pawn. }
9. Bf4 { The most logical follow up to white's previous move. } 9... Qb6
{ I was considering recommending  9...h6  here as an alternative to 9... Qb6. However, I eventually decided not to as I was not a big fan of the endgame after  10.Bxc7  hxg5  .   A reason why you might want to consider  9...h6  is because after  10.Qxh6!?  Qb6!  things are starting to get dangerous for White. White should grab the rook with  11.Qxh8  , but after  11...Qxb2  12.Rc1  Nf6  White has to defend very accurately in a position that is already objectively fine for Black. Probably only an engine will manage.   In practice, however, after  9...h6  I expect people to play  10.Bxc7  anyway, so I don't see that much of an upside. So the choice came down to the endgame after 9... Qb6 10.Qb5, or 9...h6 10. Bxc7, and I think 9...Qb6 should be preferred. }
10. Qb5
{ Forcing the queen trade, as our queen has no good escape square with the b7-pawn being a target. }
10... Qxb5
{ By exchanging queens ourselves we gain some initiative, as we can meet  11.Nxb5  with  11...Bb4+  , forcing  12.Nc3  . }
11. Nxb5 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 Nf6
{ Such an endgame as the one we are seeing here is one that can occur more often in the Schara. Typically, we don't want to exchange queens, but in some occasions we can if we have an even bigger lead in development than usual. Especially as the engine recommends  13.Bd2  as the best move for White, there should be enough of a development lead for us to get compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
13. e3
{ Also quite a logical move, with the intention to defend the knight on c3 with Ne2. However, the setup with Ne2 is not very harmonious, as it blocks white's own light-squared bishop. Apart from that, the dark-squared bishop is also quite exposed on f4. }
13... Nd5 { The logical continuation, attacking both c3 and f4. } 14. Ne2 Rc8
{ Adding even more pressure on the c-file. With Na5 coming soon we are likely going to get back our sacrificed pawn immediately. }
15. a3 Nxf4
{ Only now that we have to make a decision with our bishop do we capture on f4. This is because after Nxf4 we would like to capture on c3 and ruin White's queenside pawn structure, and having the inclusion of a3 and Rc8 should of course be quite nice. }
16. Nxf4 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Na5
{ And due to the weaknesses on the queenside we will get back our pawn with active play. If White defends with  18.Rc1  , we can slowly build up the pressure with  18...Rc5  followed by Ke7/O-O and bring the other rook to c8. }
*

