[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 5.Qxd4: 7...Qc7"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Qc7: 8. Qg5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. }
7... Qc7
{ 7...Bd6  looks more active, but the downside is that the bishop is not ideal on d6. c5 is usually the most active square, and by playing  7...Qc7  we intend to let the bishop reach that square.The downside of  7...Qc7  is that typically the e7-square is optimal for our queen. In practice, the move 7... Qc7 has been seen only very rarely. }
8. Qg5
{ This move is a typical computer move. So far it has not been played in over the board or online games, but it has been seen a couple of times in correspondence chess. The idea is to support the bishop to come to f4 and if the queen is kicked away, then White can bring it back to g3 to offer a queen exchange. }
8... Be6
{ So far players have continued with the normal  8...Nf6  . With  8...Be6  we have some deeper intentions. The idea is that later on in the lines when Qg3 happens, we want to be able to respond with Bd6. By playing Bd6 we sacrifice the g7-pawn, but we can respond to Qxg7 with Be5. However, if we have played Nf6, Qxg7 will come with a double attack. This means that the move Be6 serves as a useful waiting move. We are interested in seeing how White will develop and can now respond adequately to it. An advantage of having played Be6 is that we can castle queenside quickly in some cases.   Concretely speaking, what I did not like about  8...Nf6  was  9.e4  . After  9...h6  White has  10.Qg3  which cannot be met with  10...Bd6  , while White also seems to be better after  10...Qa5  11.Bb5  .   Instead of 9...h6 we can also play  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppq2ppp/2n2n2/6Q1/4P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be6  , but then after  10.Bf4  Qb6  11.Qb5  White seems to get an advantage in the endgame due to the extra pawn. }
9. Bf4 { The most logical follow up to white's previous move. } 9... Qb6
{ I was considering recommending  9...h6  here as an alternative to 9... Qb6. However, I eventually decided not to as I was not a big fan of the endgame after  10.Bxc7  hxg5  .   A reason why you might want to consider  9...h6  is because after  10.Qxh6!?  Qb6!  things are starting to get dangerous for White. White should grab the rook with  11.Qxh8  , but after  11...Qxb2  12.Rc1  Nf6  White has to defend very accurately in a position that is already objectively fine for Black. Probably only an engine will manage.   In practice, however, after  9...h6  I expect people to play  10.Bxc7  anyway, so I don't see that much of an upside. So the choice came down to the endgame after 9... Qb6 10.Qb5, or 9...h6 10. Bxc7, and I think 9...Qb6 should be preferred. }
10. Qb5
{ Forcing the queen trade, as our queen has no good escape square with the b7-pawn being a target. }
10... Qxb5
{ By exchanging queens ourselves we gain some initiative, as we can meet  11.Nxb5  with  11...Bb4+  , forcing  12.Nc3  . }
11. Nxb5 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 Nf6
{ Such an endgame as the one we are seeing here is one that can occur more often in the Schara. Typically, we don't want to exchange queens, but in some occasions we can if we have an even bigger lead in development than usual. Especially as the engine recommends  13.Bd2  as the best move for White, there should be enough of a development lead for us to get compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
13. Bd2
{ A slow move, but a slightly annoying one, not giving us as much threats as we had after  13.e3  .  White stops Ne4/Nd5 for now, and that was where most of our play was coming from. It is typical in the Schara Gambit that White does not really have the time to develop the dark-squared bishop early on as it leads to problems on the queenside. }
13... Bxc3
{ We will have to start creating weaknesses to attack before White manages to stabilize. Otherwise White will  just go Nf3-e3-Bb5 and castle kingside eventually. }
14. bxc3
{ It looks more logical for White to recapture with the bishop, but this should also be taken into consideration of course. }
14... Ne4 15. Nf3 O-O-O
{ Normally we will castle kingside, but now that a rook on the d-file is quite powerful with the bishop on d2 being quite vulnerable this makes quite a lot of sense. Castling queenside is always the quickest way to get your rooks to the d and e-files. }
16. e3 Rhe8
{ Followed by f5-f4 with a nice initiative in the centre. It is not easy for White to castle with the dark-squared bishop under a lot of pressure. The a2-pawn is still under attack as well. }
*

