{ If White is just allowed to play a3 or e3 without consequences then the knight on b4 looks a bit silly. By playing O-O-O instead of Rd8 we are getting our king out of the centre and make it more easy for our other rook to join. With the knight on b4, our king is also a target, as White would be able to develop quickly with e3 followed by Bb5+.Although people used to castle queenside all the time in the Schara Gambit, this is almost the only line where I will recommend you to do so. It has been shown that in normal circumstances, O-O-O is a bad plan. }
12. a3
{ The critcal move, asking us what O-O-O is all about.  12...Nbd5  would now simply be met with  13.Bd2  after which our king is quite misplaced on the queenside. By playing O-O-O we brought some cool sacrifices into the position, however! }
12... Rd1+
{ A very cool looking move.  12...Bb3  is an alternative, but I would prefer to play this one. White is now forced to give up the queen for a rook and a knight as by playing Rd1+ we will be forcing White to allow us to play Nc2+ in some way. White will then have to give up the queen for the knight to avoid getting checkmated. }
13. Kxd1
{ White will now be forced to give up the queen anyway, but our pieces will be coordinated better and White has given up the right to castle. }
13... Bb3+
{ If White moves the king to d2 now or on the next move, Qd8+ is quite tough to meet. }
14. Ke1 Nc2+ 15. Qxc2
{ Forced, as White is getting mated after  15.Kd2  Qd8+  . } 15... Bxc2 16. Be3
{ With Rc1 incoming White still has some play on the queenside, but we can just play Bf5 followed by Kb8 to keep everything safe. }
16... Bf5 17. Rc1 Kb8
{ With a nice initiative for us, since White's kingside is heavily underdeveloped. It is good to remember that White has also lost the right to castle. You might have spotted that White can play  18.Bxa7+  here, but we can simply meet it with  18...Ka8  .  Afterwards we just finish our development and have a nice position. }
*

