{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. }
7... Qc7
{ 7...Bd6  looks more active, but the downside is that the bishop is not ideal on d6. c5 is usually the most active square, and by playing  7...Qc7  we intend to let the bishop reach that square.The downside of  7...Qc7  is that typically the e7-square is optimal for our queen. In practice, the move 7... Qc7 has been seen only very rarely. }
8. Nf3
{ The most human looking response to 7... Qc7, and the one I would expect you to face most often in practice. White simply wants to retreat the queen to d1, and we will get an interesting version of the 5. Qa4+ lines, with our pieces coordinated slightly differently. }
8... Nf6 9. Qb3
{ This seems to lose a tempo in comparison to  9.Qd1  as we can target the queen immediately, but in general the queen is never staying on d1 either. The queen is usually quite safe on c2 or a4. }
9... Be6
{ We should get this tempo in before White is able to play e3 and respond to Be6 with Bc4. }
10. Qc2 Nb4
{ If we were to follow the normal plan of Bc5 followed by O-O, we wouldn't have an ideal setup. Normally we have our queen on e7 instead, so we need to play things differently. However, I don't think you will mind what different setup I will be recommending.The move Nb4 is very typical in the Schara to get counterplay if White has placed their queen on c2. Normally, the queen will go back to b1 after which we can try to trap it by getting our bishop to f5. Otherwise, we can think of exchanging the c3-knight, which is an important defender of White's queenside. However, in this case we have completely different things in mind. }
11. Qb1 O-O-O
{ If White is just allowed to play a3 or e3 without consequences then the knight on b4 looks a bit silly. By playing O-O-O instead of Rd8 we are getting our king out of the centre and make it more easy for our other rook to join. With the knight on b4, our king is also a target, as White would be able to develop quickly with e3 followed by Bb5+.Although people used to castle queenside all the time in the Schara Gambit, this is almost the only line where I will recommend you to do so. It has been shown that in normal circumstances, O-O-O is a bad plan. }
12. a3
{ The critcal move, asking us what O-O-O is all about.  12...Nbd5  would now simply be met with  13.Bd2  after which our king is quite misplaced on the queenside. By playing O-O-O we brought some cool sacrifices into the position, however! }
12... Rd1+
{ A very cool looking move.  12...Bb3  is an alternative, but I would prefer to play this one. White is now forced to give up the queen for a rook and a knight as by playing Rd1+ we will be forcing White to allow us to play Nc2+ in some way. White will then have to give up the queen for the knight to avoid getting checkmated. }
13. Nxd1 Nc2+ 14. Qxc2
{ Forced, as  14.Kd2  leads to mate after  14...Ne4+  15.Kd3  Qc4#  . } 14...
Qxc2 15. Bf4
{ Again, this is similar to 13.Kxd1 in that White gets some play against our king by bringing the rook to c1. As this time our king is cut off from getting to b8, we have to move it back to the centre. Apart from that, from d7 the king controls the d6-square and prepares Bd6. }
15... Kd7
{ This square also makes more sense than d8 as it gives our rook more freedom. }
16. Rc1 Qf5
{ By playing this move we gain a tempo on the bishop to be able to finish our development quicker.  16...Qa4  would also attack the bishop and is a fine alternative to  16...Qf5  .  We intend to play Bd6 next and finish our development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 5.Qxd4: 7...Qc7"]
[Black "5.Qxd4 7...Qc7: 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qb3 #4 (alternative 12... Bb3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qxd4
{ Although  5.Qxd4  is of course the most logical move at first sight,  5.Qa4+  has always been seen as the critical move. After  5...Bd7  6.Qxd4  White has lured the bishop to d7 in order for it to block our queen. As after  5.Qxd4  our queen is now pinning the d5-pawn, we can make use of this by playing  5...Nc6  and gain a tempo on the queen.   On the other hand, after  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  White is in this case attacking our queen and we don't want to trade queens being a pawn down.  7...Bd7  is not a move we want to play either, so I do think there is something to be said for 5. Qxd4 instead of 5. Qa4+ as well. Initially, the strong engines of current times do prefer 5. Qa4+ to 5. Qxd4. }
5... Nc6
{ Making use of the fact the d5-pawn is pinned for now. After the queen has moved we then take on d5. }
6. Qd1
{ White should really go for the position after  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  . This position can also be reached by playing  6.Qd2  exd5  7.Qxd5  or  6.Qc4  exd5  7.Qxd5  . Even  6.Qd3  exd5  7.Qxd5  can be played. Usually White just does this via 6. Qd1, though.   White can also capture on d5 with the knight after all the queen moves, but they always lead to White being trouble as the knight should stay on c3 to defend the queenside. For example  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nf6  gives Black a nice initiative and a good position.   The only two queen moves that make a difference are  6.Qe3  and  6.Qa4  , but they are not impressive either. }
6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. }
7... Qc7
{ 7...Bd6  looks more active, but the downside is that the bishop is not ideal on d6. c5 is usually the most active square, and by playing  7...Qc7  we intend to let the bishop reach that square.The downside of  7...Qc7  is that typically the e7-square is optimal for our queen. In practice, the move 7... Qc7 has been seen only very rarely. }
8. Nf3
{ The most human looking response to 7... Qc7, and the one I would expect you to face most often in practice. White simply wants to retreat the queen to d1, and we will get an interesting version of the 5. Qa4+ lines, with our pieces coordinated slightly differently. }
8... Nf6 9. Qb3
{ This seems to lose a tempo in comparison to  9.Qd1  as we can target the queen immediately, but in general the queen is never staying on d1 either. The queen is usually quite safe on c2 or a4. }
9... Be6
{ We should get this tempo in before White is able to play e3 and respond to Be6 with Bc4. }
10. Qc2 Nb4
{ If we were to follow the normal plan of Bc5 followed by O-O, we wouldn't have an ideal setup. Normally we have our queen on e7 instead, so we need to play things differently. However, I don't think you will mind what different setup I will be recommending.The move Nb4 is very typical in the Schara to get counterplay if White has placed their queen on c2. Normally, the queen will go back to b1 after which we can try to trap it by getting our bishop to f5. Otherwise, we can think of exchanging the c3-knight, which is an important defender of White's queenside. However, in this case we have completely different things in mind. }
11. Qb1 O-O-O
{ If White is just allowed to play a3 or e3 without consequences then the knight on b4 looks a bit silly. By playing O-O-O instead of Rd8 we are getting our king out of the centre and make it more easy for our other rook to join. With the knight on b4, our king is also a target, as White would be able to develop quickly with e3 followed by Bb5+.Although people used to castle queenside all the time in the Schara Gambit, this is almost the only line where I will recommend you to do so. It has been shown that in normal circumstances, O-O-O is a bad plan. }
12. a3
{ The critcal move, asking us what O-O-O is all about.  12...Nbd5  would now simply be met with  13.Bd2  after which our king is quite misplaced on the queenside. By playing O-O-O we brought some cool sacrifices into the position, however! }
12... Bb3
{ An interesting alternative to  12...Rd1+  . The move  12...Bb3  does give White the opportunity to go for a repetition with  13.Qf5+  Be6  14.Qb1  . If you are not satisfied with a draw, you could still play  14...Rd1+  afterwards. }
13. axb4 Qxc3+
{ This was the point of the move, getting rid of the defender of the d1-square. Now  14.bxc3  would obviously be met with  14...Rd1#  ,  so White should play 14.Bd2 instead. }
14. Bd2 Qc6
{ Funnily enough,  14...Qxb4  is also a move as White mates themselves after  15.Bxb4  Bxb4+  16.Nd2  Bxd2#  . However, the simple  15.g3  seems to lead to an advantage for White.   Right now after  14...Qc6  , we are intending to continue our attack with  15.--  Rxd2!  followed by Bxb4 with Ne4 and Rd8 to come. White should be quite careful here. }
15. Qf5+ Be6 16. Qa5
{ The queen is obviously much better on a5 than it was on b1. It is now protecting the b4-pawn, which stops our Rxd2 followed by Bxb4 ideas. White is now also threatening Rc1, so we should anyway play 16... Rxd2. }
16... Rxd2
{ We have to continue our initiative, as otherwise White will take over. } 17.
Nxd2 Qc2
{ The idea is to take on b2 and then play Bxb4. However, if we play Qxb2 on the next move, White will be able to play Rb1. Thus, we can start by sacrificing a knight with Ne4, and after Nxe4 play Qxb2 with the deadly threat of Bxb4+. Apart from that, we can also attack the b4-pawn with Nd5. }
18. e3 Ne4
{ Now, for example,  18...Nd5  would be too slow due to  19.Qxa7  Bxb4  20.Qd4  after which White has everything defended. }
19. Nxe4 Qxb2 20. Nc5
{ In a way, this makes more sense than  20.Ra4  as that allows a bunch of checks with  20...Qb1+  . After  21.Ke2  we can play  21...Qxe4  , while after @@StartFEN@@2k2b1r/pp3ppp/4b3/Q7/RP2N3/4P3/5PPP/1q2KB1R w K - 2 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Kd2  we can force a draw with  21...Qb2+  or continue the attack with  21...Be7  followed by Rd8. }
20... Qc3+ 21. Kd1
{ With this move White decides to play on. After  21.Ke2  Qc2+  White will have to go back to play for a win, because after  22.Kf3  Qf5+  forces  23.Ke2  Qc2+  .  This is one of the reasons why you might prefer 12...Rd1+ to 12...Bb3, as there are no forced draws in the lines there. Here, the position seems more dangerous for White, but we are the ones forcing the draw in the critical lines. }
21... Bb3+ { The only safe check left in the position so we had to go for it. }
22. Nxb3 Qxb3+
{ Funnily enough, the only way for White to continue the game this time, is actually by running to f3. The queen on a5 is not blocked anymore by the knight on c5, so we don't have a check anymore on f5. We simply get a really computerish line.I thought it would be nice to be providing 12...Bb3+ so that you know that it is perfectly possible, but I would probably prefer 12... Rd1+ myself. I am going to provide the rest of the line to where it is necessary, but I would not necessarily advise you to learn all this by heart. }
23. Ke2 Qc2+
{ We need to keep on giving checks on light-squares, to be able to give the checks on the dark-squares with our bishop. After  23...Qb2+  White is able to run away on the light-squares via f3-e4 because we don't control them:  24.Kf3  Qf6+  25.Ke4+-  . }
24. Kf3 Qc6+
{ Again, the only check left in the position. I would think that our moves are not too difficult, but it is White who is the one playing for a win here.  25.Kg3  is now met with  25...Qg6+  ,  so White should play 25.e4 instead. }
25. e4 Qc3+
{ Again not such a difficult move as it is our only check, because  25...Qf6+  loses to  26.Qf5+  forcing a queen exchange. }
26. Ke2 Bxb4
{ Finally our bishop has been able to join the attack, now that we have lured the pawn on e4. White is now actually the one who has to be careful, as we are simply going to play Rd8 next and will actually have dangerous mating threats. }
27. Qf5+ Kb8 28. Qf4+ Ka8 29. Rd1
{ The way to continue the game. White could have made an immediate draw with either  29.Rxa7+  Kxa7  30.Qe3+  forcing an opposite coloured bishop endgame, or with  29.Qc1  which forces a repetition with  29...Qd4  30.Kf3  Qf6+  31.Ke2  Qd4  .  White is giving back an exchange and a pawn with 29.Rd1 just to continue the game. }
29... Qc2+ 30. Rd2 Bxd2 31. Qxd2 Qxe4+ 32. Qe3 Qa4
{ By now we have two pawns for the bishop, and still quite a dangerous initiative. All the way from 12...Bb3 to here was forced from our side, while White had some alternatives along the way. In general I'm much more a fan of 12... Rd1+. It also looks like a cooler move to be honest. }
