6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. }
7... Qc7
{ 7...Bd6  looks more active, but the downside is that the bishop is not ideal on d6. c5 is usually the most active square, and by playing  7...Qc7  we intend to let the bishop reach that square.The downside of  7...Qc7  is that typically the e7-square is optimal for our queen. In practice, the move 7... Qc7 has been seen only very rarely. }
8. Nf3
{ The most human looking response to 7... Qc7, and the one I would expect you to face most often in practice. White simply wants to retreat the queen to d1, and we will get an interesting version of the 5. Qa4+ lines, with our pieces coordinated slightly differently. }
8... Nf6 9. Qb3
{ This seems to lose a tempo in comparison to  9.Qd1  as we can target the queen immediately, but in general the queen is never staying on d1 either. The queen is usually quite safe on c2 or a4. }
9... Be6
{ We should get this tempo in before White is able to play e3 and respond to Be6 with Bc4. }
10. Qa4
{ This move is much safer for White than 10. Qc2,  which we have just seen. The thing is that White is pinning our knight for now, but eventually the queen on a4 is not entirely safe either, with ideas such as a6-b5 in the future. For now we will finish our development in the normal Schara Gambit way with Bc5 and O-O. }
10... Bc5 11. e3 O-O 12. Be2
{ We are now having a typical Schara Gambit position, but our pieces have been placed slightly differently. The difference with the normal positions is mainly that our queen is on c7 instead of e7. Another difference is that our bishop is already on e6, but this often happens later on anyway.To get a better feel for these positions, I would generally recommend to not only study the 5. Qa4+ chapters but also the model games that I have provided. For me, it seems much more important to have a good feeling for these positions than to just know the concrete moves. }
12... Rad8
{ Normally we bring our rooks to c8 and d8, but this is when we have developed the queen to e7. Usually, the idea is that we want the heavy pieces to control the c,d and e-files. With the queen on c7, this means that our rooks should go to d8 and e8. Rad8 is also tactically a good idea, because we will soon see that it is important that White's Rd1-Rxd8 does not come with check. We intend to play a6-b5 next. }
13. O-O a6
{ Preparing a6-b5. This is a typical plan in these positions, and one that we will be going for here as well. Often we can play b5 without having to worry about Qxa6, as the queen often just gets trapped after Nb4. You will see the a6-b5 plan in the 5.Qa4+ chapters as well. White always has a couple of different moves that they can play in such positions, so I will provide the most logical and critical ones to show how to continue next. }
14. Bd2
{ A logical developing move as White does not want to push e4 in such positions. e4 would lose control over a lot of squares an also open up the f2-c5 diagonal for our bishop. However, the bishop on d2 is always quite vulnerable and will give us another weakness to attack. }
14... Ne5
{ A typical move for us in the Schara Gambit. With this move we are normally trying to get rid of White's main kingside defender, the f3-knight. However, this time we are also threatening  15.--  Nxf3+  followed by Rxd2. }
15. Rfd1 b5 16. Qf4
{ The queen would like to return to c2, as it is quite exposed on f4. However,  16.Qc2  would be met with  16...Nxf3+  17.Bxf3  Bd6  with the double threat of  18.--  Bxh2+  and  18...b4  . }
16... Bd6
{ The rerouting of the bishop to d6 is very standard in such positions. This time it is even more logical with the queen on h4. }
17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Qh4 h6
{ With plenty of compensation as we are putting not only a lot of pressure on both flanks but also on the d-file. We will likely play Qb8 soon as White is probably going to play Rac1 soon. We can always double up on the d-file or just generally improve our rooks. }
