14. Qc2 Nb4
{ Again the typical way of meeting Qc2 in these positions. This time we are not going to get in Bf5 next, but we are rerouting the knight to d5. }
15. Qb1 Rfe8
{ As we saw in the 14. Rd1 line we were getting in Bf5 in a nice way, but as a3 is coming on the next move that isn't really possible here due to e4. Rfe8 is simly the most useful move in this position while waiting for White to kick our knight away with a3. If White plays any other random move we might consider a move such as Qc8 as this time Bf5 would actually be a threat due to the inclusion of Rfe8. }
16. a3 Nbd5 17. Qc2
{ White should normally not play Nxd5 in such positions. After  17.Nxd5  Bxd5  we put pressure on White's main defender of their king. At any moment Ng4 could become lethal. On the other hand, allowing the structure after Nxc3 bxc3 is not at all ideal either. }
17... Nxc3
{ The logical continuation of our previous moves. Instead,  17...Bb6  is a good alternative. }
18. Qxc3 Bf5
{ Preparing Ne4, as the immediate  18...Ne4  19.Qc2  Bf5  would be met with either  20.Nd4  or  20.Nh4  . }
19. b4 Ne4 20. Qc2
{ 20.Qc4  would be met with  20...b5  , while this move is not ideal either. }
20... Ng3
{ An important discovered attack that we were setting up by playing 18... Bf5. }
21. Qxc5 Nxe2+ 22. Kh1 Qxc5 23. bxc5 Rd5
{ After we have taken the c5-pawn we will have a 2 vs 1 situation on the queenside that can easily lead to a passed pawn. }
