6... exd5
{ We only recapture the pawn now, after having gained a tempo on the queen. }
7. Qxd5
{ As mentioned after 6. Qd1,  7.Nxd5  does not make too much sense here. The knight on c3 does a good job of defending, and by playing  7.Qxd5  White kind of gains a tempo. Our queen is under attack, and we have to now make a slightly awkward move. This is because our ideal setup, which we will see in the main lines after 5. Qa4+, involves our bishop getting to c5 and the queen to e7.   7...Bd7  would make some sense, but actually transposes to a position that we don't want. In the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  we play  7...Nf6  , and not  7...Nc6  .  This is because after the queen retreats to b3  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.Qb3  @@EndBracket@@, it is important to have kept flexibility to be able to play  8...Na6  instead of  8...Nc6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be6  is also an option, but not a great one. We should not be exchanging pieces being down material, and after  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@9.e3 is also objectively better for White@@EndBracket@@  9...Nb4  10.Rc1  Nxa2  11.Nxa2  Bxa2  Black has won back the pawn, but the endgame is not pleasant at all. White should be better in various ways, but Black certainly has hopes to hold.   That more or less leaves us with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  as serious options. I have dedicated two chapters to them. Personally, I slightly prefer  7...Qc7  , but objectively both seem to be okay for Black and it is good to have options to be able to give our opponents more homework. }
7... Qc7
{ 7...Bd6  looks more active, but the downside is that the bishop is not ideal on d6. c5 is usually the most active square, and by playing  7...Qc7  we intend to let the bishop reach that square.The downside of  7...Qc7  is that typically the e7-square is optimal for our queen. In practice, the move 7... Qc7 has been seen only very rarely. }
8. Nf3
{ The most human looking response to 7... Qc7, and the one I would expect you to face most often in practice. White simply wants to retreat the queen to d1, and we will get an interesting version of the 5. Qa4+ lines, with our pieces coordinated slightly differently. }
8... Nf6 9. Qd1
{ Definitely the safest square for the queen, as we have seen what can happen after  9.Qb3  . }
9... Bc5
{ A typical move for the Schara Gambit, but normally our queen will go to e7. }
10. e3 O-O
{ We should compare this position to the one we usually get via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  Nf6  8.Qd1  Bc5  9.Nf3  O-O  10.e3  Nc6  .  We have the same position, but have played Qc7 instead of Bf5. The bishop is generally not ideal on d7, but on the other hand it is better than on c8. Our queen right now is on c7, instead of d8. Although the c7-square is an improvement, it typically goes to e7 instead. So our resulting setups from this position will differ from the main line. }
11. Be2
{ This is the typical setup that White adopts against the Schara Gambit. The bishop on e2 is quite useful as it defends the knight on f3, while other squares on the diagonal will leave it more vulnerable. }
11... Bf5
{ The ideal square for the bishop, where it is quite active and controls squares that White would have liked to have, such as c2 and e4.  11...Bg4  looks logical as well, but we might want to keep the g4-square empty so that one of our knights can use it in the future. }
12. O-O Rad8
{ We are choosing a similar setup as to what we have in the 9.Qb3 lines. With the queen on c7 it makes a lot of sense to put our rooks on the d and e-files. In the positions with our queen on e7 @@StartBracket@@arising from 5.Qa4+@@EndBracket@@, we put our rooks on the c and d-files instead. By doing this, we always manage to control the c,d and e-files. }
13. Qa4
{ This is the exact same position as we had in the 9. Qb3 line, but there our bishop is on e6 instead of f5. We will play the position in a very similar fashion. }
13... a6
{ Preparing b5, but apart from that this is a generally useful move in such positions. }
14. a3
{ a3 is also a useful move for White, but for different reasons. White generally does not want to expand with b4, as this often leaves the c3-knight vulnerable. Instead, a3 is just used as a move to grab space and take away the b4-square.   14...b5  could now be met with  15.Qxa6  . }
14... h6
{ A funny waiting game has begun. Normally  14...Rfe8  would be a useul move, but White answers with  15.Rd1  .  As the tension will result in one rook being exchanged, 14...Rfe8 isn't that useful as we need the rook on d8. }
15. Rd1 Ne5
{ With ideas such as Nfg4 with the idea to take on f3 and h2, or Rxd1+ followed by Rd8. We have nice compensation here. We have to use the weakened squares in White's position such as d3 for our pieces. }
*

