{ We are choosing a similar setup as to what we have in the 9.Qb3 lines. With the queen on c7 it makes a lot of sense to put our rooks on the d and e-files. In the positions with our queen on e7 @@StartBracket@@arising from 5.Qa4+@@EndBracket@@, we put our rooks on the c and d-files instead. By doing this, we always manage to control the c,d and e-files. }
13. Qb3 a6
{ It is good to remember this plan of a6-b5. Once we have developed all of our pieces, it is often quite a useful plan gaining space on the queenside. }
14. Bd2 Ne5
{ The typical way to react to Bd2. We now threaten to win material with  15.--  Nxf3+  16.Bxf3  Rxd2  . Apart from that, we might want to play  15.--  Nfg4  next with the idea to play  16.--  Nxf3+  17.Bxf3  Qxh2#  . }
15. Rad1
{ The rook is needed on f1 to defend the f2-pawn making it more difficult for us to start sacrificing on the kingside. }
15... b5
{ Continuing our plan that we started by playing a6.  15...Nfg4  would have been met with  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  17.g3  after which it is not that easy to continue the attack. }
16. h3
{ Preventing Nfg4 makes sense for White. Generally h3 is a useful move for White in these positions, but White does not always have the time to make the move. }
16... h6
{ A useful move that we have also seen in the 15.Qa4 line. We have ideas to improve our position with moves such as b4 or Rfe8. Apart from that, White's queen is also quite exposed and Be6 at any moment can be dangerous. Our bishop from c5 can be brought back to a7. Then it won't be blocking the c-file for our queen any longer and it might switch to b8 to create deadly threats on the kingside.   A concrete reason not to play the immediate  15...Rfe8  is that White can reply  16.Bc1  b4  17.Nd5  ,  which would not be working with the rook back on f8. Now after  17...Nxd5  White has  18.Rxd5  Be6  19.Rxd8! }
*

