{ At some depth both Leela and Stockfish think  14...b6  is the best move here, but that is too artificial for me.  14...Bg4  is much more concrete and fine as well for Black. The idea is just to take on f3 and ruin white's kingside pawn structure. The engines recommend  14...b6  so that  15.Na4  could be met with  15...Bd3!  16.Bxd3  Nxf3+  17.gxf3  Rxd3  with excellent compensation due to the damaged pawn structure and White's king safety. }
15. Nb5
{ White intends to bring the knight to d4 to have a better defense on the kingside. }
15... Qe7 16. Nbd4
{ With the knight on d4, it will be quite difficult for us to continue the attack. However, due to our activity, we can still improve our pieces and eventually go for it. }
16... Nxf3+
{ White was intending to exchange a couple of pieces with Nxe5 followed by Bxg4, so we should not allow that to happen. Instead, by taking on f3 we get rid of White's d4-knight and open up the d-file. }
17. Nxf3 Ne4
{ The knight is always a great piece on e4, restricting the e3-pawn and attacking a lot of important squares. First of all we are threatening  18.--  Nxd2  or  18...Bxf3  winning a piece. Apart from that, White will always have to be careful of sacrifices on f2. The knight may even go to g5 to put pressure on f3. We can also still improve our rooks. Rfe8 is generally a useful move, making sacrifices on f2 even more likely. The other rook might swing to the kingside via d6 or d5.This was the end of this chapter, and I hope you already have gotten a better feel of these typical Schara Gambit positions. Hopefully you liked the chapters on 5.Qxd4, now let's move on to 5. Qa4+. To me this chapter already gives a good indication of how the positions of 5.Qa4+ will be. }
*

