{ At least we will have damaged White's queenside structure by doing this. White's dark-squared bishop will also remain passive for now, as  12.bxc3  should be played.  12.Bxc3  is not good due to  12...Nxc3  13.bxc3  Ne5!  attacking both c3 and f3. }
12. bxc3 O-O
{ Now that we have lured the bishop to d2, we have a new target. We intend to play Rd8 next after which the c3-pawn is also weak. }
13. Bg2 Rd8 14. O-O
{ White should probably give up the pawn in such a way, to give us less counterplay. White after all will have the bishop pair in this open position after Nxc3. }
14... Nxc3
{ 14...Bg4  is an interesting alternative. It does not lead to material gains after  15.Qe1  Bxf3  due to  16.Bf4  . However, after  15.Qe1  Nxd2  16.Nxd2  Rac8  followed by h5 Black has plenty of counterplay for the pawn. Just winning back the pawn with 14...Nxc3 seems easier, though. }
15. Qe1 Ne4 16. Be3 Be6
{ White does have the bishop pair in an open position, but we have the more active pieces and a potential passed pawn on the queenside. We can play Rac8 next and see what White is up to. Often we can neutralize the light-squared bishop by playing Bd5. }
