6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Nf3
{ It is clear that this is not such a great move. White intends to play against the isolated pawn, but we actually get a great version of such positions due to the loss of time with Qa4-Qd4. }
7... Nf6
{ This is a well known position, but with the bishop back on c8. It arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  c5  5.cxd5  cxd4  6.Qxd4  exd5  . Usually White either plays  7.e4  leading to an endgame, or  7.Bg5  playing against the IQP.   However, the bishop being on d7 vastly improves things. First of all  8.e4  does not make a whole lot of sense since we can simply gain a tempo with  8...Nc6  , which usually would be met with  9.Bb5  ,  but that loses the queen now as our bishop is on d7. An added option that White has is  8.Nxd5  ,  but it is a move that we should welcome as we play the Schara Gambit to gambit! }
8. Bg5 Nc6 9. Qd2 Bb4
{ This direct approach makes life easy for us, but we can also play  9...Be6  to keep the game more tense. The idea of  9...Bb4  is to follow up with Ne4. }
10. a3 Ne4 { This forces a lot of exchanges. } 11. Bxd8 Bxc3
{ Slightly more accurate than  11...Nxd2  , although both moves are totally fine. }
12. Qxc3 Nxc3 13. Bh4
{ 13.bxc3  Rxd8  should be quite pleasant for us due to the isolated pawn on c3. }
