[Black "5.Qa4+ with 8. Qxb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ This will be the first chapter where we have a look at 5. Qa4+. Although the move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we will see in this chapter. }
8. Qxb7 Nc6
{ We just continue as if nothing happened. By developing the knight to  c6  we protect our rook on a8 and soon have plans of Nb4/Nd4. Right now we are even threatening to immediately win the game by playing  9.--  Rb8  10.Qa6  Nb4  followed by Nc2+. }
9. Bf4
{ Stopping Rb8, but also protecting the c7 square once more enabling Qc7. }
9... Bb4
{ A logical move that we will also see in the 9.Qb3 lines. We not only put pressure on the diagonal, but also take away the b3-square from White's queen. We are just trying to finish our development with O-O next, and afterwards intend to either put pressure on the diagonal with Ne4 or trap the queen. }
10. g3
{ Although this looks slightly strange with the bishop on f4, it actually makes quite a lot of sense to start putting pressure on either our c6 knight or try to get in Bh3. }
10... O-O 11. Bh3
{ We have to act quick after both Bg2 and Bh3 before White gets to trade a lot of pieces and castle kingside. }
11... Bxc3+
{ Followed by Qa5 already creates strong threats on the queenside. In general Bxc3 is an interesting idea as it creates weaknesses on the queenside. We don't start with  11...Qa5  because after  12.Bxd7  Bxc3+  13.Kf1!  we don't have a good move with both our knight and bishop hanging. }
12. bxc3 Qa5 13. Qb2 Bxh3
{ Forcing the knight to h3, where it will be awkwardly placed. } 14. Nxh3 Qh5
{ With very nice compensation. It is not a good look for White when the engine recommends Ng1 as the best move. We have moves such as Nd5 and Rae8 incoming. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qxb7 and Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qa4+ with 8. Qxb7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ This will be the first chapter where we have a look at 5. Qa4+. Although the move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we will see in this chapter. }
8. Qxb7 Nc6
{ We just continue as if nothing happened. By developing the knight to  c6  we protect our rook on a8 and soon have plans of Nb4/Nd4. Right now we are even threatening to immediately win the game by playing  9.--  Rb8  10.Qa6  Nb4  followed by Nc2+. }
9. Bf4
{ Stopping Rb8, but also protecting the c7 square once more enabling Qc7. }
9... Bb4
{ A logical move that we will also see in the 9.Qb3 lines. We not only put pressure on the diagonal, but also take away the b3-square from White's queen. We are just trying to finish our development with O-O next, and afterwards intend to either put pressure on the diagonal with Ne4 or trap the queen. }
10. g3
{ Although this looks slightly strange with the bishop on f4, it actually makes quite a lot of sense to start putting pressure on either our c6 knight or try to get in Bh3. }
10... O-O 11. Bg2 Qa5
{ In contrast to 11. Bh3, we are starting with Qa5 instead of Bxc3+ this time. The reason is that we don't have a good follow-up to  11...Bxc3+  12.bxc3  Qa5  13.Qb2  .  In the line with 11. Bh3 we could continue with 13... Bxh3, but the bishop is on g2 now. }
12. Bxc6 Bxc3+ 13. Kf1
{ 13.bxc3  would have obviously lost after  13...Qxc3+  with a triple attack. We are now able to win back our pawns, and White in return is finally able to finish development. }
13... Bxc6 14. Qxc6 Bxb2 15. Rd1 Qxa2
{ With still a lot of play left, I would prefer to have Black here. The engine indicates the typical 0.00, but our a-pawn will soon become annoying in a practical game. }
*

