{ We just continue as if nothing happened. By developing the knight to  c6  we protect our rook on a8 and soon have plans of Nb4/Nd4. Right now we are even threatening to immediately win the game by playing  9.--  Rb8  10.Qa6  Nb4  followed by Nc2+. }
9. Qb3 { This together with  9.Bf4  makes the most sense for White. } 9... Rb8
10. Qd1
{ The queen has finally returned back home, but we are already close to finishing development. Due to the solid nature of White's position it is not easy to get through. The main target in the position will be the knight on c3. }
10... Bb4
{ We have to put immediate pressure. Normally we have good compensation in the Schara Gambit, but only for one pawn. This time we cannot play the position for long term compensation. Two pawns is too much for that. We intend to play Ne4 next and in combination with the pressure on the b-file it might not be so easy for White to keep things together. After Ne4, Qf6 might be coming which will put pressure on both c3 and f2. }
11. e3
{ Although the move looks normal, it is too slow. White should play  11.Nf3  to have an extra defender of the e1-a5 diagonal. }
11... Ne4 12. Ne2
{ This defends c3, but the knight is very much in the way of White's development. }
12... Qh4 { Forcing g3, so that White cannot kick away the knight with f3. }
13. g3 Qf6 14. f4 Bg4
{ With having everything pinned and no development, White is just completely busted and will soon start to lose material. }
