11. Nf3 Ne4
{ 11...Ba5  is an interesting alternative as well. Although it feels rather slow, the idea is to play Ne4 next after which the pressure on b2 will be slightly annoying. }
12. Bd2 Bxc3
{ White was threatening to win material with  Nxe4  , so we had to deal with the pressure in some way.  12...Bxc3  is the way to go, momentarily giving up the bishop pair. It opens up the b-file and later on we will be able to take White's bishop pair as well anyway.  12...Nxc3  would be met with  13.bxc3  gaining a tempo on our bishop for White. }
13. Bxc3 O-O
{ We wait with the capture on c3 for one move.  14.g3?  can now be met with  14...Qb6!  with the threat of  15.--  Qxf2#  because we haven't swapped off our knight yet. }
14. e3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qf6
{ We are not only one, but two pawns down here. However, we do have excellent compensation. This is due to White's lack of development and the weaknesses in his position. We can activate our rooks with Rb2 and Rfd8. Apart from that g2/f3 are also weaknesses in White's camp.   For example  16.Qc1  could be met with  16...Qg6  or even  16...Bh3!?  . }
