{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we have seen. }
8. Qb3
{ In this chapter we will start looking at the move 8.Qb3. I have decided to dedicate two chapters to this move as it is quite a critical one. It was recently used by Samuel Shankland when Magnus Carlsen surprised him with the Schara Gambit. It was also the move I faced the first time I employed this gambit in an over the board game.The queen looks exposed on b3, but the question is, how do we actually attack it? Be6 at some point in time makes a lot of sense, but Qxb7 is a problem as long as we have not finished our development.Apart from that, we cannot use the typical setup of Bc5, O-O, Nc6 and Qe7 either. We do play like that after 8. Qd1, but the issue is that in the resulting positions the queen actually often goes to b3 anyway since it better over there. With a rook coming to d8 the queen is also exposed on d1, and it is stopping White's rooks from connecting.Taking everything into consideration, it is clear that we have to play differently. }
8... Na6
{ The knight is on the rim for now, but it is coming to c5 next, gaining a tempo on the queen. The idea is often to play Nce4 followed by moves such as Bb4 and Rc8 to put immediate pressure on the e1-a5 diagonal. White usually tries to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and castle kingside, but could as well try to bring out the dark-squared bishop first. This however, is usually not a great idea in these types of Schara Gambit positions as it will weaken the b2-pawn, but also simply costs White time. White should not wait too long with castling as White's king could prove to be vulnerable. }
9. e3
{ This keeps the option open of playing Nge2 instead of Nf3. This could easily transpose to  9.Nf3  , but as mentioned there are some differences. The downside is that White cannot develop the dark-squared bishop to an active square anymore, but White should refrain from doing so anyway. }
9... Nc5 10. Qc2 Rc8
{ Now  11.Nf3  transposes to the next chapter. This position is normally reached via  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/n4n2/8/8/1QN5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nf3  Nc5  10.Qc2  Rc8  11.e3  . }
11. Be2
{ An interesting try, with the idea to meet Nce4 with Bf3. Afterwards White can play Nf3. We actually have a couple of viable options here. I have analysed  11...b5  ,  11...Bd6  and  11...g6  .  11...g6 is a move that indicates we are playing for long term compensation. 11...b5 is a lot more concrete, trying to make use of the queen on c2. 11...Nce4 is more standard and perhaps the one that I like the most. }
11... Nce4 12. Bf3 Nxc3
{ This is the move that makes most sense, but it turns out going back with  12...Nc5  is an interesting alternative. It does allow a repetition with  13.Be2  . If White tries to continue with  13.Nge2  instead, we can play  13...Ba4  followed by Nd3+ with a strong initiative as well. }
13. bxc3 Bd6
{ Now that we have worsened the pawn structure on White's queenside, we can switch our focus back to finishing our development. We intend to castle next and then find a place for our queen. This is probably either a5 or c7. From both squares the queen pressures c3. From c7 it also targets h2, from a5 it can switch to e5 to attack as well and helps the bishop come to f5.If White takes on b7 in one of the next moves we would like to respond to it by playing Rc4. From c4 it is still targetting c3, but it can also very easily switch to the kingside to help with the attack. c5 is not a good square as that could be met with Ba3. I have added the first engine line of Stockfish to show how play could continue. }
14. Bxb7 Rc4 15. Ne2 O-O
{ White is not able to castle kingside yet, as  16.O-O  would lose to a typical greek gift:  16...Bxh2+  17.Kxh2  Ng4+  18.Kg1  Qh4-+  . }
16. Bf3 Qc7
{ This time we use the c7-square as  16...Qa5  would be met with  17.Qd3  with a double attack. }
17. h3 Be5
{ With the idea to play Qc8 next to be able to play Bxh3 once White has castled. If White were to accept the sacrifice, we can play Qxh3 with the double threat of Qh2# and Qxf3. The rook on c4 is also ready to join the attack on h4 or g4.We are still two pawns down, but both extra pawns are severly limiting White's play. Ba4 might sometimes be an interesting move as well, making it clear that the queen on c2 is rather vulnerable. }
*

