11... b5 12. Nf3 b4 13. Nb5 Qa5
{ This move threatens Bxb5, but also b3+ is an interesting idea now. } 14. Nbd4
b3+ 15. Qd2
{ Forced, as  15.Bd2  bxc2  16.Bxa5  c1=Q+  17.Rxc1  Nd3+  loses a lot of material, and  15.Qc3  Nd3+  loses the queen. }
15... Qxa2 { A tactic that is usually only seen in tactic books. } 16. Rxa2
bxa2 17. Qa5 Na4 { Blocking the queen. } 18. Nb3
{ This was the only way for White to stop the a-pawn from queening. } 18...
Rxc1+ { Trying to distract the knight. } 19. Bd1 { White is not giving in. }
19... Bd6
{ By now we have a rook and bishop for the queen, while the a2-pawn remains dangerous. We just intend to castle next. Once White gets the queen from the a-file, Nc5 becomes an idea to disrupt White'' s b3-knight from protecting the a1-square. }
