11... b5 12. a3 { This is a lot safer than  12.Nf3  for White. } 12... a5
{ 12...g6  could be considered as well. It is not very clear if the inclusion of b5 and a3 is favourable for White or for Black.  12...a5  feels like a more logical follow-up to 11... b5. }
13. Nf3 Qb6
{ 13...b4  would have been met with  14.axb4  axb4  15.Nb5  after which we don't really have a nice follow up. By playing 13...Qb6 first we take away the b5-square. }
14. O-O
{ 14.Nd4  was an alternative, to keep the option of meeting b4 with Nb5. Play would continue with  14...b4  15.axb4  axb4  16.Ncb5  , after which we can just continue our development with  16...Be7  17.O-O  O-O  with full compensation. We intend to play Rfd8 next, while  18.Bd2  can be met with  18...Nce4  winning the bishop pair. The knight on b5 looks quite vulnerable on b5 in general in these lines. }
14... b4 15. axb4 axb4 16. Nb1
{ A sad necessity, but at least White is not losing material on the spot. }
16... Be6 { Threatening Nb3, winning material. } 17. Qd1 Be7 18. Nd4 O-O
{ Followed by Rfd8 with very serious compensation. White is very passive, and the extra pawn on e3 only limits white's play even more.   19.Nxe6  can be met with  19...Qxe6  after which Nb3 becomes an issue again. }
