5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we have seen. }
8. Qb3
{ In this chapter we will start looking at the move 8.Qb3. I have decided to dedicate two chapters to this move as it is quite a critical one. It was recently used by Samuel Shankland when Magnus Carlsen surprised him with the Schara Gambit. It was also the move I faced the first time I employed this gambit in an over the board game.The queen looks exposed on b3, but the question is, how do we actually attack it? Be6 at some point in time makes a lot of sense, but Qxb7 is a problem as long as we have not finished our development.Apart from that, we cannot use the typical setup of Bc5, O-O, Nc6 and Qe7 either. We do play like that after 8. Qd1, but the issue is that in the resulting positions the queen actually often goes to b3 anyway since it better over there. With a rook coming to d8 the queen is also exposed on d1, and it is stopping White's rooks from connecting.Taking everything into consideration, it is clear that we have to play differently. }
8... Na6
{ The knight is on the rim for now, but it is coming to c5 next, gaining a tempo on the queen. The idea is often to play Nce4 followed by moves such as Bb4 and Rc8 to put immediate pressure on the e1-a5 diagonal. White usually tries to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and castle kingside, but could as well try to bring out the dark-squared bishop first. This however, is usually not a great idea in these types of Schara Gambit positions as it will weaken the b2-pawn, but also simply costs White time. White should not wait too long with castling as White's king could prove to be vulnerable. }
9. Bg5 Bb4
{ With the bishop out on g5 we should be acting fast. The normal plan of Nc5 followed by Rc8 and Nce4 is a bit slow here, as we want to punish White as quickly as possible for developing the dark-squared bishop.  9...Nc5  is actually very playable here as well, but my preference goes to  9...Bb4  when it became clear to me how quickly things can go wrong for White. }
10. e3
{ This normal move now also creates the threat of Bxa6. Although that would not win a piece due to Bxc3+, it would force a lot of exchanges. }
10... Rc8
{ Making our own threats bigger than our opponent's is usually the way to go when fighting for the initiative. We want to make our opponent respond to our move and not the other way around. We intend to play Qa5 next, which would not only increase the pressure on c3, but would attack the bishop on g5 as well. On top of that, we unpin our f6-knight which means that Ne4 starts to become an option. White should of course react to Qa5 with Bxf6, simultaneously defending the c3-knight. It is even better to actually start with 11. Bxf6. }
11. Bxa6 { This move looks logical, but is actually a mistake. } 11... Qa5
{ Giving up a knight for now, but there are a lot of things compensating for it. First of all, we have a double attack on the bishops. Secondly,  12.--  Bxc3+  threatens to win the game on the spot as White does not have a good reply to  13.bxc3  Rxc3  . Lastly,  12.--  Ba4  also threatens to win the queen. }
12. Bxf6 { All other moves also lead to issues that I have explained before. }
12... Ba4 13. Qxa4+ Qxa4
{ White had to sacrifice the queen in this way as otherwise things would get even worse. White is actually up a little bit material for now, as White has two knights, a bishop and a pawn for the queen. However, both bishops are still under attack, while there are still ideas such as Rxc3 or Bxc3. }
14. Bxg7 Rg8 15. Bxb7 Rc7
{ White now even has three pawns, but is about to lose one of the bishops. Three pawns and two knights are nine points, but they are not equal to a queen, especially since none of the pawns are passed pawns. White's king is also a liability for now as it still in the centre. It is really White who is fighting to survive here. }
