{ There are somewhat surprisingly still 3 games left in this position. One is even from the legend Garry Kasparov himself, when he faced Grischuk in the Zagreb blitz from 2021. We have probably seen one of the most solid lines that White can choose from when meeting the Schara Gambit up until this point. If we do win back the c-pawn, we can still start pushing in the endgame, however, with the two vs one situation on the queenside. By playing Qd4 White was not only intending to protect c3, but also to play Qb4 next and stop us from playing Ne4. }
15... Rc8 16. Qb4
{ Offering the exchange of queens, while also stopping our king from castling. }
16... Qc5
{ We want to exchange on our terms. Taking on b4 would improve white's structure and leave us without a target. By playing Qc5 it is pretty certain that a queen exchange will happen, but once we win the c3-pawn we can still very much play for a win. }
17. Qxc5
{ 17.Bd3  and  17.Rb1  were tried in the games that were still played in this position, but this move might actually be best. The idea is just to hang onto the pawn for now by playing c4 after the trade. }
17... Rxc5 18. c4 Ke7
{ We do not have an immediate way to win back the pawn, as White can still protect it with moves such as Rc1 and Nd2. We do have quite a lot of activity, and White's ruined pawn structure on the queenside as compensation. We often want our bishop to come to e6 to target c4, but we have to be a bit careful as Nd4 can be annoying. Our other rook will come to either d8 or c8. The knight on f6 is a big question. One idea is to reroute it via e4 to d6, and another plan is to get it via d7 to the queenside. I will give a sample line of how play could continue. }
19. Nd2
{ Protecting the c4-pawn and stopping Ne4. However, we do not have to worry about Nd4 anymore now. }
19... Rd8
{ The knight on d2 does a good job protecting the c4-pawn, but it also becomes a liability. We will play Be6 next, after which the pressure on both c4 and d2 will be quite annoying.  19.Rc1  was not the answer as that could have been met with  19...b5  making use of the pin. We could have started with  19...Be6  as well, but then White could answer with  20.Nb3  Rc7  21.Nd4  . }
20. Be2 Be6 21. f3 Rc7
{ Followed by either Nd7-Nb6/Nc5 or a well times Rcd7. Things are just not very easy for White to untangle, with the knight on d2 being so vulnerable. }
