{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we have seen. }
8. Qb3
{ In this chapter we will start looking at the move 8.Qb3. I have decided to dedicate two chapters to this move as it is quite a critical one. It was recently used by Samuel Shankland when Magnus Carlsen surprised him with the Schara Gambit. It was also the move I faced the first time I employed this gambit in an over the board game.The queen looks exposed on b3, but the question is, how do we actually attack it? Be6 at some point in time makes a lot of sense, but Qxb7 is a problem as long as we have not finished our development.Apart from that, we cannot use the typical setup of Bc5, O-O, Nc6 and Qe7 either. We do play like that after 8. Qd1, but the issue is that in the resulting positions the queen actually often goes to b3 anyway since it better over there. With a rook coming to d8 the queen is also exposed on d1, and it is stopping White's rooks from connecting.Taking everything into consideration, it is clear that we have to play differently. }
8... Na6
{ The knight is on the rim for now, but it is coming to c5 next, gaining a tempo on the queen. The idea is often to play Nce4 followed by moves such as Bb4 and Rc8 to put immediate pressure on the e1-a5 diagonal. White usually tries to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and castle kingside, but could as well try to bring out the dark-squared bishop first. This however, is usually not a great idea in these types of Schara Gambit positions as it will weaken the b2-pawn, but also simply costs White time. White should not wait too long with castling as White's king could prove to be vulnerable. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qd1
{ This is actually quite a solid option. White will often give back a pawn on the queenside to be to finish development or even trade queens. However, once we do win a pawn on the queenside we are able to create a passed pawn over there.  10.Qc2  instead is definitely the critical move and the main line, and I made the next chapter entirely about this move. It is not necessarily because it is the most critical line after, but mainly because I am providing analysis of  10...Rc8  11.e3  Bd6  ,  11...a6  and  11...Nce4  as well!  11...Nce4  seems to be the best option and the one Carlsen played, but lets have a look at it in the next chapter. }
10... Nce4
{ Continuing with our plan. As we don't need to start with Rc8 we can increase the pressure quicker with an immediate Nce4 and Bb4.  10...Nfe4  could have been considered as well. If White were to play  11.e3  ,  we would transpose to our notes from 9.e3 Nc5 10.Qd1 Nfe4 11. Nf3 - see the variation. However, White also has the option to play  11.g3  , which I don't like to that much for Black. }
11. e3 Bb4 12. Bd2
{ Both sides have so far made pretty standard looking moves, but we need to make an interesting decision here. }
12... Qa5
{ This move is an interesting alternative to  12...Bxc3  . The idea is that in the variation  12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Qa5  White responds with  15.Qd4  .  Whereas in the current position, due to the bishop still being on d2, White is not able to protect the c3-square by playing Qd4. The downside, however, is that White also gains some extra options such as meeting Bxc3 with bxc3. }
13. Bd3 Bxc3
{ This is an interesting alternative to a correspondence game from 2016. Stockfish and Lc0 had an interesting debate here, with Stock indicating that Black is completely fine while Lc0 kept on giving a plus for White. It actually turns out to be fully fine for Black. However, it seemed better to me not to recommend this in the course as the lines seem like rather complicated engine work to me while we have easy alternatives instead. I have kept it in the course so that you are still able to have a look at it. }
14. bxc3 O-O 15. c4 Qh5 16. Bxe4 Nxe4 17. Bb4 Rfd8 18. Be7 Bh3 19. Bxd8
{ 19...Bxg2  instead seems to lead to an slightly better endgame for White after  20.Qd7  Qc5  21.Qe8+  Qf8  22.Qxf8+  Kxf8  23.Nd4  Bxh1  24.Ba5  . }
19... Nc3 20. Qd2 Bxg2 21. Rg1 Qxf3 22. Qxc3 Rxd8
{ Black is still down a full exchange, but due to king safety, activity and White's damaged pawn structure Black actually has full compensation. It is difficult to say which side should be preferred here in a practical game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qb3 Sidelines"]
[Black "8. Qb3 with 9. Nf3 #6 (alternative 12...Qa5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we have seen. }
8. Qb3
{ In this chapter we will start looking at the move 8.Qb3. I have decided to dedicate two chapters to this move as it is quite a critical one. It was recently used by Samuel Shankland when Magnus Carlsen surprised him with the Schara Gambit. It was also the move I faced the first time I employed this gambit in an over the board game.The queen looks exposed on b3, but the question is, how do we actually attack it? Be6 at some point in time makes a lot of sense, but Qxb7 is a problem as long as we have not finished our development.Apart from that, we cannot use the typical setup of Bc5, O-O, Nc6 and Qe7 either. We do play like that after 8. Qd1, but the issue is that in the resulting positions the queen actually often goes to b3 anyway since it better over there. With a rook coming to d8 the queen is also exposed on d1, and it is stopping White's rooks from connecting.Taking everything into consideration, it is clear that we have to play differently. }
8... Na6
{ The knight is on the rim for now, but it is coming to c5 next, gaining a tempo on the queen. The idea is often to play Nce4 followed by moves such as Bb4 and Rc8 to put immediate pressure on the e1-a5 diagonal. White usually tries to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and castle kingside, but could as well try to bring out the dark-squared bishop first. This however, is usually not a great idea in these types of Schara Gambit positions as it will weaken the b2-pawn, but also simply costs White time. White should not wait too long with castling as White's king could prove to be vulnerable. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qd1
{ This is actually quite a solid option. White will often give back a pawn on the queenside to be to finish development or even trade queens. However, once we do win a pawn on the queenside we are able to create a passed pawn over there.  10.Qc2  instead is definitely the critical move and the main line, and I made the next chapter entirely about this move. It is not necessarily because it is the most critical line after, but mainly because I am providing analysis of  10...Rc8  11.e3  Bd6  ,  11...a6  and  11...Nce4  as well!  11...Nce4  seems to be the best option and the one Carlsen played, but lets have a look at it in the next chapter. }
10... Nce4
{ Continuing with our plan. As we don't need to start with Rc8 we can increase the pressure quicker with an immediate Nce4 and Bb4.  10...Nfe4  could have been considered as well. If White were to play  11.e3  ,  we would transpose to our notes from 9.e3 Nc5 10.Qd1 Nfe4 11. Nf3 - see the variation. However, White also has the option to play  11.g3  , which I don't like to that much for Black. }
11. e3 Bb4 12. Bd2
{ Both sides have so far made pretty standard looking moves, but we need to make an interesting decision here. }
12... Qa5
{ This move is an interesting alternative to  12...Bxc3  . The idea is that in the variation  12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Qa5  White responds with  15.Qd4  .  Whereas in the current position, due to the bishop still being on d2, White is not able to protect the c3-square by playing Qd4. The downside, however, is that White also gains some extra options such as meeting Bxc3 with bxc3. }
13. Bd3 Nxd2
{ We take the bishop in this line, removing one defender of White's knight. White would be a bit better after  13...Nxc3  14.bxc3  Bxc3  15.Rc1  .  Now after 13... Nxd2 14.Qxd2 we can amp up the pressure with Rc8 and Nd5 and only then intend to win back the pawn. }
14. Qxd2 Rc8 15. Rc1 Nd5
{ We are attacking the c3-knight with so many pieces that White cannot protect it anymore. White has to give up the pawn, but at least we will have to give up our bishop pair. }
16. O-O Bxc3
{ In a perfect world we would like to win back the pawn by playing Nxc3. However,  16...Nxc3  is met by  17.a3!  That is why we win back the pawn by playing Bxc3 instead. }
17. bxc3 Nxc3
{ There are pros and cons for both sides here. We have the better structure with two vs one on the queenside, which means that endgames could benefit us. On the other hand, White has a beautiful square on d4 for the knight. It is difficult to say whether our bishop will be dominating the knight or vice-versa. The knight on c3 could become vulnerable, but for now  18.Rc2  can be met with  18...Ba4  .  We intend to castle next and play moves such as Rc5/Rc7 and Rfc8 doubling on the c-file. Eventually we can start to push our a and b-pawns. }
