9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2
{ This is the starting point of this chapter. As explained before I have made this into a seperate chapter because I will be providing three different options, but also because this line is quite critical. The idea of playing Qc2 instead of Qd1 is that it not only prevents Nce4 for now, but also adds protection to the knight on c3. White usually wants to play e3-Be2-O-O next and hopes to be better due to the extra pawn. In any case, we will have to start with Rc8. }
10... Rc8
{ Preparing Nce4, but it also quite a useful move in general because White has put their queen on c2. For example,  11.e4  has now been prevented because we can play  11...Ncxe4  . }
11. g3
{ I have mainly included this option to show various ways that White can continue, but it is actually fairly simple for us to reach a fine position from here. }
11... Nce4 12. Bg2 Bb4
{ We just follow the typical plan that we started a few moves ago. } 13. Bd2
O-O { We can keep the tension due to the pin on the c-file. } 14. O-O Bf5 15.
Qd1
{ The only good square for the queen, but that is not a good sign for White.  15.Qc1  would have been met with  15...Nd5  , while  15.Qb3  would have just lost to  15...Nxd2  16.Nxd2  Bxc3!  17.bxc3  Qxd2  . }
15... Nxc3 { It is time to harvest. } 16. bxc3 Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Rxc3
{ With a pleasant position. Again the two vs one situation on the queenside is nice in any endgame. The bishop on g2 can be neutralized with Be4. }
