[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qb3 with 10.Qc2"]
[Black "5. Qa4+ with 10. Qc2: 11. e3 Nce4 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we will see in this chapter. }
8. Qb3
{ I have decided to dedicate two chapters to this move as it is quite a critical one. It was recently used by Samuel Shankland when Magnus Carlsen surprised him with the Schara Gambit. It was also the move I faced the first time I employed this gambit in an over the board game.The queen looks exposed on b3, but the question is, how do we actually attack it? Be6 at some point in time makes a lot of sense, but Qxb7 is a problem as long as we have not finished our development.Apart from that, we cannot use the typical setup of Bc5, O-O, Nc6 and Qe7 either. We do play like that after 8. Qd1, but the issue is that in the resulting positions the queen actually often goes to b3 anyway since it better over there. With a rook coming to d8 the queen is also exposed on d1, and it is stopping White's rooks from connecting.Taking everything into consideration, it is clear that we have to play differently. }
8... Na6
{ The knight is on the rim for now, but it is coming to c5 next, gaining a tempo on the queen. The idea is often to play Nce4 followed by moves such as Bb4 and Rc8 to put immediate pressure on the e1-a5 diagonal. White usually tries to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and castle kingside, but could as well try to bring out the dark-squared bishop first. This however, is usually not a great idea in these types of Schara Gambit positions as it will weaken the b2-pawn, but also simply costs White time. White should not wait too long with castling as White's king could prove to be vulnerable. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2
{ This is the starting point of this chapter. As explained before I have made this into a seperate chapter because I will be providing three different options, but also because this line is quite critical. The idea of playing Qc2 instead of Qd1 is that it not only prevents Nce4 for now, but also adds protection to the knight on c3. White usually wants to play e3-Be2-O-O next and hopes to be better due to the extra pawn. In any case, we will have to start with Rc8. }
10... Rc8
{ Preparing Nce4, but it also quite a useful move in general because White has put their queen on c2. For example,  11.e4  has now been prevented because we can play  11...Ncxe4  . }
11. e3
{ An important position, where I have provided three interesting options. First of all I would like to mention that this position could also be reached via @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/n4n2/8/8/1QN5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.e3  Nc5  10.Qc2  Rc8  11.Nf3  , which was also mentioned in the previous chapter. The main line,  11...Nce4  , is probably the most direct way to continue, and the one Magnus Carlsen picked versus Sam Shankland. The other two are  11...a6  and  11...Bd6  . }
11... Nce4
{ This move seems to be most in line with the previous moves that we made. We are just intending to play Nxc3 next to damage White's pawn structure and trying to win the pawn back.  11...Nce4  is a much more concrete approach than  11...a6  or  11...Bd6  .  You either may like that, or not at all. That is one of the reasons why it felt important to me to give multiple options here. We are usually playing for long-term compensation in the Schara Gambit, so in a way playing in this way feels a bit odd. On the other hand, getting a fine position in a very concrete way may be something that you like, as a solution to this line. }
12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3
{ We have now managed to damage White's structure, but if they are able to just play O-O, c4 and Bb2, they  definitely have a nice position. We thus need to act fast. }
13... Nd5
{ Not only intending to take back the pawn, but winning the bishop pair with Nb4 is an idea as well. This was a novelty when Magnus Carlsen played it in the 2022 Tata Steel Tournament. }
14. O-O Nxc3
{ 14...Nb4  is actually a decent alternative, but I did not like it very much. After  15.Qe2  Nxd3  16.Qxd3  we have won the bishop pair, but are about to lose it again with Ne5 incoming. After  16...Be7  17.Ne5  Rc7  18.Nxd7  Rxd7  the enines are only giving an 0.10 evaluation, but it feels like we are fighting for equality to me. }
15. Qb3
{ White can force a draw with this move in a slightly odd way, but at least it is good to see as it can improve our understanding of the position. The point behind playing 15. Qb3 is to prevent us from protecting the knight with Bb4. This means that White is preparing Bb2. Apart from that, Bc4 or Ne5 are also quite powerful moves. }
15... Be6
{ White has to drop back the queen. They can only be worse after  16.Bb5+  Nxb5  17.Qxb5+  Qd7  , and they also cannot grab the pawn with @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp3ppp/4b3/8/8/1QnBPN2/P4PPP/R1B2RK1 w k - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Qxb7  due to  16...Qxd3  . }
16. Qc2 Bd7
{ This is the downside of playing concrete lines such as 11...Nce4. With good play, they can sometimes lead to early draws. We do not really have any other options, as  16...Bb4  would be met with  17.a3  Ba5  18.a4  followed by Ba3.  16...Be7  would be bad as well due to  17.Bb2  . }
*

