15. Bb2 Bb4
{ White has a couple of options here, all of which seem interesting to me. The current position is a bit odd, all due to this knight on c3. On the one hand it is kind of dominating the queenside, but on the other hand it is quite unstable. }
16. Qb3 a5
{ As mentioned in my comments after 15. Nd4,  17.a3  now loses to  17...Ba4  trapping the queen. I would like to note as well that @@StartFEN@@2rqk2r/1p1b1ppp/8/p7/1b6/1QnBPN2/PB3PPP/R4RK1 w k - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Rfc1?  is bad, but not due to  17...Ba4  because of  18.Bb5+!  Instead, we have  17...Be6!  making White's queenside situation quite uncomfortable. }
17. Bxc3 Rxc3 18. Qd5
{ We have won the bishop pair, but our pieces are uncoordinated. After for example  18...O-O?  we are simply losing a pawn and the bishop pair due to  19.Rfd1  followed by Bxh7+. }
18... Qc7
{ 18...Qe7  was the move that I wanted to recommend at first, but I started to appreciate the simplicity of  18...Qc7  . The question is how do we respond to  19.Qe4+  comfortably, but it is fairly simple actually. }
19. Qe4+ Kf8
{ It was anyway not that easy to castle yet due to the pressure on h7, so we just put our king on f8.  19...Be6  20.Nd4  would lose, while @@StartFEN@@4k2r/1pqb1ppp/8/p7/1b2Q3/2rBPN2/P4PPP/R4RK1 b k - 3 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Be7  20.Ne5  would be somewhat uncomfortable as well. The question after 19... Kf8 is: how do we get the h8-rook into game? One idea is to play g6 next, but I actually like the plan of h5-Rh6 quite a lot. }
20. Nd4 h5
{ All of our problems seem to have been solved now that our king is safe and our rook is about to join the game.  20...g6  is also playable, but perhaps our rook still has some difficulties to get active after  21.Ne2  Rc5  22.Qd4  Rg8  . }
