{ 14...Nb4  is actually a decent alternative, but I did not like it very much. After  15.Qe2  Nxd3  16.Qxd3  we have won the bishop pair, but are about to lose it again with Ne5 incoming. After  16...Be7  17.Ne5  Rc7  18.Nxd7  Rxd7  the enines are only giving an 0.10 evaluation, but it feels like we are fighting for equality to me. }
15. Bb2 Bb4
{ White has a couple of options here, all of which seem interesting to me. The current position is a bit odd, all due to this knight on c3. On the one hand it is kind of dominating the queenside, but on the other hand it is quite unstable. }
16. Bxh7
{ Not the move I would be scared of, but it felt good to include this move into the course. After 16. Bxh7 we intend to leave our king in the centre and use the h-file for our rook. }
16... Rc5
{ Stopping Bf5 while also getting the rook to a better square. We want to play Qe7 next and perhaps Bc6, creating attacking possibilities. White can of course play a couple of different moves, but I have added the top engine line as it does not seem too important to spend a lot of time on this possibility. }
17. Rac1 Qe7 18. Bxc3
{ Only now does White take, as  18...Bxc3  is this time not a great move for us due to  19.Qb3  . However, we don't mind to allow White to trade queens after  18...Rxc3  19.Qe4  due to our bishop pair. }
18... Rxc3 19. Qe4 Bc6 { Forcing the trade and clearing up the position. } 20.
Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ An endgame ensues with chances for both sides. We have full compensation for the pawn due to the bishop pair and the two vs one situation on the queenside. }
