16. Rac1
{ Now that the queen is protected, the Nxd4 Qxe2 trick has been prevented.  16...Nxd4  17.exd4  Rxc3  does not work either, because after  18.Bxc3  the bishop on e2 is protected. }
16... h5
{ 17.Bf3  will now transpose to 16. Bf3 h5 17. Rac1 - see the variation. White has several logical moves at this point, so I will provide some examples to show how we should proceed in such positions. }
17. Nf3
{ This move makes sense in a way, as it prevents h4, but also because we are not able to play Bf5 anymore. }
17... Bc6
{ A typical idea, once the knight has left the d4-square, we can reposition our bishop on c6. }
18. Rfd1 b5
{ Another normal move, gaining space on the queenside. White cannot take on b5 with either the knight or the bishop due to our c8-rook. }
19. a3 a6
{ This move is slightly odd, as we often play a5 in such positions. The point of a6 is to solidify the situation on the queenside in order to be able to focus our attention to the kingside instead. There is not such a big difference between starting with Rfe8 or a6. We have a lot of improving moves here, such as Rfe8, Bb8 and can maybe even reroute the knight via g7 to f5. If White is not able to play Qf5 anymore @@StartBracket@@for example after playing b4-Qb2@@EndBracket@@, we can even think of pushing g5-g4 if White is. The bishop might be slightly better on b7 instead of c6.The main thing in this position is perhaps that it is rather unclear what White is supposed to be doing. Probably it is b4 followed by a4 in the long term, but with our bishops targetting the queenside for now and the pin on the c-file that is not so easy to achieve. }
