13. O-O Bg7 14. Rd1
{ In the online game that I managed to find, play continued with  14.e4?  which was met by  14...Ncxe4!  giving Black a nice position. 14.Rd1 or 14.Bd2 seems a lot more natural. }
14... Qe7
{ We should prevent Ne5, now that our bishop is pinned. The bishop pair is always quite powerful in such open positions, and allowing Ne5 would lose ours. The e7-square is typical for our queen in these Schara Gambit type of positions. }
15. Bd2
{ This is not a great move this time. The rook on d1 actually takes away a square from the queen and it is not easy to meet b5 here. }
15... b5
{ White would normally like to react with either a3 or b4.  16.a3  is actually already a blunder, as there is no good way to react to  16...Bf5  .  17.Qc1  is an only move but after  17...Nb3  Black wins the game. }
16. b4 Na4
{ 16...Nce4  is possible as well, but we actually want to keep the square for the other knight. }
17. Rac1 Ne4 { This is possible due to our superior activity. } 18. Qxe4 Nxc3
19. Qxe7+ Kxe7 20. Bxc3 Rxc3 21. Rxc3 Bxc3
{ Followed by Rc8 with a nice endgame for Black. The bishop pair is quite powerful and White's queenside is about to become vulnerable. }
