15... b5 16. a3 { With Bf5 stopped, this move is now a possible reply to b5. }
16... O-O 17. Bd2
{ White is aiming to play Be1 and Rac1. Once White has managed to stabilize like this, our compensation is probably evaporating a bit. We need to start putting immediate pressure now. }
17... Ne6
{ This is the right move, and an idea that we have seen in the 11...Bd6 line as well. Currently we are threatening a trick:  18.--  Nxd4  19.exd4  Qxe2!  20.Nxe2  Rxc2  .  That exact trick was present as well in the 11...Bd6 variation, so it's definitely one to remember. }
18. Nxe6 Bxe6
{ In the 11...Bd6 line we take back with our queen to create a battery by playing Qe5 next. However, this time we take with our bishop as a lot of our play is focused on the queenside instead. }
19. Rac1 Nd7
{ Rerouting the knight in a nice way. From here it can go to b6 and afterwards to c4 or a4. We have no pawn that is limiting the scope of our bishops and White is quite cramped on the queenside. }
