{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we will see in this chapter. }
8. Qb3
{ I have decided to dedicate two chapters to this move as it is quite a critical one. It was recently used by Samuel Shankland when Magnus Carlsen surprised him with the Schara Gambit. It was also the move I faced the first time I employed this gambit in an over the board game.The queen looks exposed on b3, but the question is, how do we actually attack it? Be6 at some point in time makes a lot of sense, but Qxb7 is a problem as long as we have not finished our development.Apart from that, we cannot use the typical setup of Bc5, O-O, Nc6 and Qe7 either. We do play like that after 8. Qd1, but the issue is that in the resulting positions the queen actually often goes to b3 anyway since it better over there. With a rook coming to d8 the queen is also exposed on d1, and it is stopping White's rooks from connecting.Taking everything into consideration, it is clear that we have to play differently. }
8... Na6
{ The knight is on the rim for now, but it is coming to c5 next, gaining a tempo on the queen. The idea is often to play Nce4 followed by moves such as Bb4 and Rc8 to put immediate pressure on the e1-a5 diagonal. White usually tries to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and castle kingside, but could as well try to bring out the dark-squared bishop first. This however, is usually not a great idea in these types of Schara Gambit positions as it will weaken the b2-pawn, but also simply costs White time. White should not wait too long with castling as White's king could prove to be vulnerable. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2
{ This is the starting point of this chapter. As explained before I have made this into a seperate chapter because I will be providing three different options, but also because this line is quite critical. The idea of playing Qc2 instead of Qd1 is that it not only prevents Nce4 for now, but also adds protection to the knight on c3. White usually wants to play e3-Be2-O-O next and hopes to be better due to the extra pawn. In any case, we will have to start with Rc8. }
10... Rc8
{ Preparing Nce4, but it also quite a useful move in general because White has put their queen on c2. For example,  11.e4  has now been prevented because we can play  11...Ncxe4  . }
11. e3
{ An important position, where I have provided three interesting options. First of all I would like to mention that this position could also be reached via @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/n4n2/8/8/1QN5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.e3  Nc5  10.Qc2  Rc8  11.Nf3  , which was also mentioned in the previous chapter. The main line,  11...Nce4  , is probably the most direct way to continue, and the one Magnus Carlsen picked versus Sam Shankland. The other two are  11...a6  and  11...Bd6  . }
11... a6
{ A novelty in over the board chess, but it was recently played online by someone who seemed to know what they were doing. The point of a6 is actually to prepare g6, and choose a setup with the fianchettoed bishop. Then why not  11...g6?  Well it turns out that we have problems on the a4-e8 diagonal after  12.Ne5!  We could of course play something like  11...g6  12.Ne5  Bg7  13.Nxd7  Ncxd7  , but giving up the bishop pair and having to recapture in such a passive way is a bad sign.   After  11...a6  we are intending to meet  12.Ne5?!  with  12...Be6  , as  13.Bb5+  is not an option anymore. }
12. Be2 g6
{ As far as I can recall this is the only time I will be recommending a setup with the fianchettoed bishop in this course. The bishop on g7 will provide long-lasting pressure on the queen side. Apart from that, the g6-pawn also provides support to be able to play Bf5 at the right moment. We first need to get our king out of the centre as we could be hit by e4. Because Bf5 is always quite annoying for White to deal with, it makes a lot of sense for White to play Nd4 at some point to stop it. In general the knight is quite nice on d4 as it is an outpost and blocks the diagonal of our fianchettoed bishop as well. }
13. O-O Bg7 14. Rd1
{ In the online game that I managed to find, play continued with  14.e4?  which was met by  14...Ncxe4!  giving Black a nice position. 14.Rd1 or 14.Bd2 seems a lot more natural. }
14... Qe7
{ We should prevent Ne5, now that our bishop is pinned. The bishop pair is always quite powerful in such open positions, and allowing Ne5 would lose ours. The e7-square is typical for our queen in these Schara Gambit type of positions. }
15. Nd4
{ This seems like the most natural move to me, stopping Bf5 for some time to come. }
15... b5 16. a3 { With Bf5 stopped, this move is now a possible reply to b5. }
16... O-O 17. Bd2
{ White is aiming to play Be1 and Rac1. Once White has managed to stabilize like this, our compensation is probably evaporating a bit. We need to start putting immediate pressure now. }
17... Ne6
{ This is the right move, and an idea that we have seen in the 11...Bd6 line as well. Currently we are threatening a trick:  18.--  Nxd4  19.exd4  Qxe2!  20.Nxe2  Rxc2  .  That exact trick was present as well in the 11...Bd6 variation, so it's definitely one to remember. }
18. Be1 Nxd4
{ The blockading knight has finally been removed, and now our bishops will enter the fray. }
19. Rxd4
{ 19.exd4  is possible as well, but after  19...Rfe8  with the threat of  20.--  Rxc3  the position is quite akward for White. The queen does not have too many squares and the bishop is quite bad on e1. }
19... Bf5
{ Preparing to play Ne4 soon. This move is finally possible now that the knight is gone. }
20. Qd1 h5
{ It turns out that the immediate  20...Ne4  is met with  21.Nd5  Qa7  22.g4  .  To be honest, that is probably fine as well for us in the end. By playing  @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/4qpbp/p4np1/1p3b2/3R4/P1N1P3/1P2BPPP/R2QB1K1 b - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20...h5  we intend to play Ne4 on the next move. If White tries to stop it with  21.Bf3  we can play  21...Rfd8  with Ng4-Ne5 coming.By now we have finished the lines of 11... a6. This option is a lot slower paced than 11... Bd6 or 11... Nce4. I am not entirely sure what to think of it, as it is very different from the usual Schara Gambit type of position. It does seem to be objectively okay so I made sure to include it in the course to give you more freedom to choose. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qd1 with 10.a3"]
[Black "8. Qd1 with 10.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5 Nf6 8.
Qd1
{ This is the safest retreating square for the queen, and the move seen the most in practice. White generally just wants to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and O-O. However, in this chapter we will see an interesting concrete attempt by White to refute the Schara Gambit. }
8... Bc5
{ This is one of the places where the Schara Gambit has really evolved. Back in the days they played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/8/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@ 9. Qb3!@@EndBracket@@  9...Bc5  ,  followed by Qe7 and O-O-O. These days however, it is clear that the right plan is connected to castling kingside and playing things a lot slower. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bg5
{ This move should be shown somewhere, and it made sense to include in this chapter as it is connected to 10. a3. It is usually not a good idea for White to develop the dark-squared bishop early on in the Schara Gambit, and we will try to punish White for it here as well. }
10... Qb6
{ The most logical move, threatening to win the game with  11.--  Bxf2+  . Apart from that,  11.--  Qxb2  is another big threat. }
11. e3 Qxb2 12. Bxf6 Bb4
{ The engines like this move the most and it seems to be the easiest way to play to me.  12...gxf6  is possible, but it was not clear to me why I would prefer it to 12...Bb4 if White plays  13.Nd5  .  It is not easy to see the move 12... Bb4 in advance, but once you spot it it is actually easy to work out. Both f6 and c3 are hanging, and we leave White with only one move not to end up in a bad position. }
13. Rb1 Bxc3+ 14. Bxc3 Qxc3+ 15. Qd2 Qxd2+
{ 15...Qc7  is also playable, but the endgame seems quite comfortable to me. }
16. Kxd2 Bc6
{ Protecting the pawn, opening up the d-file for our rook and we are intending to play Nd7 next. White has a nice square on d4 for the knight, but we have a potentially passed pawn on the queenside which is quite nice. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qd1 with 10.a3"]
[Black "8. Qd1 with 10. a3 & 11. Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5 Nf6 8.
Qd1
{ This is the safest retreating square for the queen, and the move seen the most in practice. White generally just wants to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and O-O. However, in this chapter we will see an interesting concrete attempt by White to refute the Schara Gambit. }
8... Bc5
{ This is one of the places where the Schara Gambit has really evolved. Back in the days they played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/8/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@ 9. Qb3!@@EndBracket@@  9...Bc5  ,  followed by Qe7 and O-O-O. These days however, it is clear that the right plan is connected to castling kingside and playing things a lot slower. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. a3
{ Let me try to explain this move to you before I go into the story behind it. It seems more logical to just play e3 and castle kingside as most players have done so before. The point of the move a3 is actually to develop the dark-squared bishop to either f4 or g5. White plays the move a3 first, because  10.Bg5  is met by  10...Qb6  ,  targetting f2 and b2. After  11.e3  we play  11...Qxb2  ,  which would not be possible with a pawn on a3 due to  12.Na4  . Now however we can play a move such as  12...Bb4+  with a great position.It was an open question to me whether 10. a3 deserved an entire chapter of its own. It is clearly one of the most critical directions, and some books recommended this as their weapon against the Schara Gambit. However, things are different in practice. In the current position, only one game has been played so far in over the board play. This was a recent Grandmaster game between Ferenc Berkes and Amin Tabatabaei from the 2021 World Cup.   It is important to note however, that in the position after @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9....Nc6  @@StartBracket@@usually reached via the 7...Nc6 move order@@EndBracket@@ there are 41 games with  10.a3  .  It is almost the same story if I have a look at the Lichess database. That makes this line actually a bit more interesting as I will be recommending two options in this position. The first one is  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/P1N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nc6  , transposing to the mentioned move order, and the second is  10...Qc7  .   There is an interesting story behind both moves. Firstly, the position after  10...Nc6  was seen as the 'refutation' of the Schara Gambit after either  11.Bf4  or  11.Bg5  . Then the engines started to say that @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/P1N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  is an interesting alternative that seems to be okay for Black, and thus it was also recommended in the V for von Hennig-Schara course on Chessable. However, it turns out, that the modern engines are now saying that 10...Nc6 is fine again! 10...Nc6 is the concrete approach here, while 10...Qc7 will probably lead to  more typical Schara Gambit positions. }
10... Nc6
{ Amin Tabatabaei recently played this as a 'novelty'. It was the first time this position was reached in over the board chess via this move order. However, we do transpose to a bunch of games via Nc6 on any of the previous moves.This position had a reputation of being bad for Black, but I am going to prove otherwise. It is difficult for me to say whether Amin Tabatabaei knew the details here, as he played it in a rapid play-off, using a minute for Nc6 and two and a half minutes for 11. Bf4 Qb6. }
11. Bf4
{ Once White develops the dark-squared bishop, we cannot play for long term compensation anymore. If White were able to play e3, Be2 and O-O here then it will be difficult to find any compensation. With the bishop on c1 it is a different story. So we need to act fast here. }
11... Qb6
{ The move that makes the most sense, just attacking b2 and f2 although Qxb2 is not a threat yet. }
12. e3 Nh5
{ 12...Rfd8  was played by Amin Tabatabaei in his game instead, but  12...Nh5  seems to be much stronger. The bishop on d7 is invulnerable due to Qxb2 anyway, and Nxf4 is a rather big threat.  12...Rfd8  is actually not so bad, but after  13.Be2  Bf5  14.Qc1  it is not that easy to prove full equality. }
13. Bg3 { Giving up the dark-squared bishop so easily is not a great idea. }
13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 Qxb2
{ This move was made possible by removing our knight from f6. } 15. Na4 Qf6
{ Due to  16.Qxd7  Qxa1+  and  16.Nxc5  Qc3+  we are not losing a piece. } 16.
Nxc5 Qc3+ 17. Nd2 Qxc5
{ With a position that is at the very least fine for us, since we won back the pawn and will keep a slightly more active position. We intend to play Rfd8 and Rac8 next. }
*

