{ Let me try to explain this move to you before I go into the story behind it. It seems more logical to just play e3 and castle kingside as most players have done so before. The point of the move a3 is actually to develop the dark-squared bishop to either f4 or g5. White plays the move a3 first, because  10.Bg5  is met by  10...Qb6  ,  targetting f2 and b2. After  11.e3  we play  11...Qxb2  ,  which would not be possible with a pawn on a3 due to  12.Na4  . Now however we can play a move such as  12...Bb4+  with a great position.It was an open question to me whether 10. a3 deserved an entire chapter of its own. It is clearly one of the most critical directions, and some books recommended this as their weapon against the Schara Gambit. However, things are different in practice. In the current position, only one game has been played so far in over the board play. This was a recent Grandmaster game between Ferenc Berkes and Amin Tabatabaei from the 2021 World Cup.   It is important to note however, that in the position after @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9....Nc6  @@StartBracket@@usually reached via the 7...Nc6 move order@@EndBracket@@ there are 41 games with  10.a3  .  It is almost the same story if I have a look at the Lichess database. That makes this line actually a bit more interesting as I will be recommending two options in this position. The first one is  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/P1N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nc6  , transposing to the mentioned move order, and the second is  10...Qc7  .   There is an interesting story behind both moves. Firstly, the position after  10...Nc6  was seen as the 'refutation' of the Schara Gambit after either  11.Bf4  or  11.Bg5  . Then the engines started to say that @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/P1N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  is an interesting alternative that seems to be okay for Black, and thus it was also recommended in the V for von Hennig-Schara course on Chessable. However, it turns out, that the modern engines are now saying that 10...Nc6 is fine again! 10...Nc6 is the concrete approach here, while 10...Qc7 will probably lead to  more typical Schara Gambit positions. }
10... Nc6
{ Amin Tabatabaei recently played this as a 'novelty'. It was the first time this position was reached in over the board chess via this move order. However, we do transpose to a bunch of games via Nc6 on any of the previous moves.This position had a reputation of being bad for Black, but I am going to prove otherwise. It is difficult for me to say whether Amin Tabatabaei knew the details here, as he played it in a rapid play-off, using a minute for Nc6 and two and a half minutes for 11. Bf4 Qb6. }
11. Bg5
{ Developing the bishop here was the goal of 10. a3. White can now safely meet  11...Qb6  with  12.e3  when  12...Qxb2  loses to  13.Na4  due to the pawn on a3. }
11... h6
{ Introducing a piece sacrifice, as we intend to take back on f6 with the queen. The pin is generally quite annoying, so we intend to follow up with g5 if White plays Bh4. }
12. Bxf6
{ The greedy approach, and this can get quite dangerous for White. We will just follow some correspondence games here that have already shown that Black is fully okay in these lines. }
12... Qxf6
{ Giving up the bishop on d7. We are able to do this due to our huge lead in development. }
13. Qxd7 Rfd8
{ We gain the tempo with the f8-rook so that we can meet Qxb7 with Rab8. The question is how we are actually intending to turn this initiative into something substantial, and the answer is connected to White's queenside. The situation over there is rather unstable, and Bxa3 will be a common theme. }
14. Qg4 Ne5
{ White clearly cannot play  15.Nxe5  due to  15...Qxf2#  .  That means that White will have to move the queen another time, and afterwards we will be able to play Qb6. }
15. Qg3 { The queen is at least protecting f2 on this square. } 15... Qb6
{ Qxb2 would just be a devastating blow now. } 16. Rb1 Rac8
{ Bringing the final piece into the attack, ignoring that our knight on e5 is hanging. We intend to play  17.--  Bxa3  next and meet  18.bxa3  with  18...Qxb1+!  19.Nxb1  Rc1#  . }
17. e3 Bxa3 18. Bb5 Bxb2 19. O-O
{ This is the safer option as it forces 19... Nxf3+.  19.Rxb2  is also possible, but at the very least we can play  19...Nxf3+  20.Qxf3  Rxc3  when  21.O-O  transposes back to 19. O-O. We can also play  19...Nd3+  instead, when after  20.Bxd3  Qxb2  21.Nd1  Qb4+  22.Ke2  Rxd3!  the madness continues, but it should eventually result in a perpetual. }
19... Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Rxc3 21. Rxb2 a6
{ This wins back the piece due to the pin. } 22. Qxf7+
{ This seems like a decent try for White to still play for a win in a practical game. In both correspondence games  22.Qe2  was played and a draw followed. }
22... Kxf7 23. Bc4+ Rxc4 24. Rxb6 Rc7
{ During the Prague Challengers tournament of 2022, my opponent Hans Niemann managed to find his way to this rook endgame. This was quite unexpected as he was more or less out of book after 11...h6.   There are two ways to play this rook endgame. The first one is to give up the pawn on b7 with  24...Rc7  25.Rfb1  Ra8  26.Rxb7  Rxb7  27.Rxb7+  Ke6  @@StartBracket@@27...Kf6 is also possible@@EndBracket@@. The point is to start running with the a-pawn, which will give plenty of counterplay to make a draw without trouble. If White plays  28.Rxg7  , then we can play  28...a5  29.Rb7  a4  30.Rb1  a3  31.Ra1  Kd5  and are incredibly active with at least a draw. If White does not take on g7 we start to run as well, of course.   Instead, I went for the more three-result way of playing with  24...Rd7  25.Rfb1  Rcc7  @@StartBracket@@ 24...Rc7 25.Rfb1 Rdd7 is also possible@@EndBracket@@. The plan is to go Ke8-Kd8-Kc8 to free up a rook and start running with the a-pawn. After  26.g4  Ke8  27.Kg2  Kd8  28.h4  Kc8  the problem was that I did not know the right setup and just played it pretty miserably. The rooks should become more active and a good setup is with Re7/Rc4. So for example, after he played  29.R1b3  ,  29...Rc4  is a good move, with the intention to go  30.Kg3  Re7  .  The rooks are now making it difficult for him to keep advancing, and now a5-a4 starts to become realistic.   Instead, he went for @@StartFEN@@2k5/1p1r2p1/pR5p/8/2r3PP/1R2P3/5PK1/8 w - - 3 30@@EndFEN@@  30.f4  , and now I immediately pushed with  30...a5  @@StartBracket@@30...Re7 being a fine alternative again@@EndBracket@@. After  31.R6b5  a4  32.Ra3  I now made a big inaccuracy already with  32...Rd6  .   Instead  32...Kc7  preparing b6 was better, with the idea to meet  33.Ra5  with  33...Re7!  34.Kf3  Ree4  and now I can play Kb6-Kb5 to support the a-pawn.  After  32...Rd6  33.Kf3  I made a losing mistake with  33...Kc7  still going for the idea of meeting  34.Ra5  with  34...Ra6  . After  35.Rxa6  bxa6  this rook endgame is now just lost, however. Not only do I have doubled pawns, but this is also a much worse version of the first plan to give up on b7 immediately. I could have saved the game at one moment later on, but from here on it was already practically impossible to hold. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qd1 with 10.a3"]
[Black "8. Qd1 with 10. a3 & 11. Bg5 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5 Nf6 8.
Qd1
{ This is the safest retreating square for the queen, and the move seen the most in practice. White generally just wants to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and O-O. However, in this chapter we will see an interesting concrete attempt by White to refute the Schara Gambit. }
8... Bc5
{ This is one of the places where the Schara Gambit has really evolved. Back in the days they played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/8/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@ 9. Qb3!@@EndBracket@@  9...Bc5  ,  followed by Qe7 and O-O-O. These days however, it is clear that the right plan is connected to castling kingside and playing things a lot slower. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. a3
{ Let me try to explain this move to you before I go into the story behind it. It seems more logical to just play e3 and castle kingside as most players have done so before. The point of the move a3 is actually to develop the dark-squared bishop to either f4 or g5. White plays the move a3 first, because  10.Bg5  is met by  10...Qb6  ,  targetting f2 and b2. After  11.e3  we play  11...Qxb2  ,  which would not be possible with a pawn on a3 due to  12.Na4  . Now however we can play a move such as  12...Bb4+  with a great position.It was an open question to me whether 10. a3 deserved an entire chapter of its own. It is clearly one of the most critical directions, and some books recommended this as their weapon against the Schara Gambit. However, things are different in practice. In the current position, only one game has been played so far in over the board play. This was a recent Grandmaster game between Ferenc Berkes and Amin Tabatabaei from the 2021 World Cup.   It is important to note however, that in the position after @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9....Nc6  @@StartBracket@@usually reached via the 7...Nc6 move order@@EndBracket@@ there are 41 games with  10.a3  .  It is almost the same story if I have a look at the Lichess database. That makes this line actually a bit more interesting as I will be recommending two options in this position. The first one is  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/P1N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nc6  , transposing to the mentioned move order, and the second is  10...Qc7  .   There is an interesting story behind both moves. Firstly, the position after  10...Nc6  was seen as the 'refutation' of the Schara Gambit after either  11.Bf4  or  11.Bg5  . Then the engines started to say that @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1b1ppp/5n2/2b5/8/P1N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  is an interesting alternative that seems to be okay for Black, and thus it was also recommended in the V for von Hennig-Schara course on Chessable. However, it turns out, that the modern engines are now saying that 10...Nc6 is fine again! 10...Nc6 is the concrete approach here, while 10...Qc7 will probably lead to  more typical Schara Gambit positions. }
10... Nc6
{ Amin Tabatabaei recently played this as a 'novelty'. It was the first time this position was reached in over the board chess via this move order. However, we do transpose to a bunch of games via Nc6 on any of the previous moves.This position had a reputation of being bad for Black, but I am going to prove otherwise. It is difficult for me to say whether Amin Tabatabaei knew the details here, as he played it in a rapid play-off, using a minute for Nc6 and two and a half minutes for 11. Bf4 Qb6. }
11. Bg5
{ Developing the bishop here was the goal of 10. a3. White can now safely meet  11...Qb6  with  12.e3  when  12...Qxb2  loses to  13.Na4  due to the pawn on a3. }
11... h6
{ Introducing a piece sacrifice, as we intend to take back on f6 with the queen. The pin is generally quite annoying, so we intend to follow up with g5 if White plays Bh4. }
12. Bh4 g5
{ This does weaken our king in the long term, but chess is a concrete game. }
13. Bg3 Qb6
{ This is a very important update on the V for von Hennig-Schara course as they only considered  13...Qe7  , and concluded that it was not great for Black. The move  13...Qb6  does not appear to do that much, as f2 is protected in this case, while after  14.e3  the move  14...Qxb2  is not a threat anymore due to  15.Na4  .  However, the constant pressure on b2 will be annoying for White and we are intending to get our rooks in by playing Rad8 next. }
14. e3 Rad8
{ Up until here we were still fighting Adrien Demuth's recent Chessable course. He fails to mention  14...Rad8  and only mentions  14...Rfd8  instead. The reason might be due to the engines becoming stronger and stronger, and showing new ways for Black in the Schara Gambit. This is a clear example of how this Gambit is revolutionizing.The reason why we play Rad8 is quite deep and very concrete, but it comes down to that we will need the rooks on d8 and e8 once we start sacrificing in the centre. This is the case in the  15.Qb1  line. In the line with  15.Qc1  it is a major difference that the rook on f8 is always protecting the f7-pawn. }
15. Qb1 Bf5
{ We will see this tactic in the 15. Qc1 line as well. There is a huge difference between the two, as there we will have a knight on a5. As this knight is currently protecting the e5-square, the idea  16.Qxf5  Qxb2  17.Be5  does not work this time due to  17...Nxe5  . White actually only has one surprising move to stay in the game. }
16. Bc7 { The only move. } 16... Qb3
{ We want to keep the pressure, as after  16...Qxc7  17.Qxf5  most of our initiative is gone.   After  16...Qb3  ,  17.Qxf5  loses again due to  17...Qxb2  . }
17. Qa2
{ In a way this is quite solid for White, as it forces the exchange of queens. However, after the exchange White will be extremely uncoordinated with the bishop on c7 and rook on a2.  17...Qc2  18.Bxd8  leaves us with too little initiative. }
17... Qxa2 18. Rxa2 Rc8 19. Bg3 Rfd8
{ We have now activated every piece, and have an enjoyable position. The only piece that could be better placed is the bishop on c5. We can bring it via f8 to g7 to put pressure on the long diagonal. Apart from that, we can also try to win the bishop pair with Nh5, or play Ne4 to get rid of the c3-knight. }
*

