{ Introducing a piece sacrifice, as we intend to take back on f6 with the queen. The pin is generally quite annoying, so we intend to follow up with g5 if White plays Bh4. }
12. Bh4 g5
{ This does weaken our king in the long term, but chess is a concrete game. }
13. Bg3 Qb6
{ This is a very important update on the V for von Hennig-Schara course as they only considered  13...Qe7  , and concluded that it was not great for Black. The move  13...Qb6  does not appear to do that much, as f2 is protected in this case, while after  14.e3  the move  14...Qxb2  is not a threat anymore due to  15.Na4  .  However, the constant pressure on b2 will be annoying for White and we are intending to get our rooks in by playing Rad8 next. }
14. e3 Rad8
{ Up until here we were still fighting Adrien Demuth's recent Chessable course. He fails to mention  14...Rad8  and only mentions  14...Rfd8  instead. The reason might be due to the engines becoming stronger and stronger, and showing new ways for Black in the Schara Gambit. This is a clear example of how this Gambit is revolutionizing.The reason why we play Rad8 is quite deep and very concrete, but it comes down to that we will need the rooks on d8 and e8 once we start sacrificing in the centre. This is the case in the  15.Qb1  line. In the line with  15.Qc1  it is a major difference that the rook on f8 is always protecting the f7-pawn. }
15. Qc1
{ This is the most critical way of playing, but it is hard to fathom that White will ever find what we are about to see. }
15... Na5
{ A logical follow-up, as the fork on b3 is really tempting to go for. } 16.
Qc2 Bf5
{ We have not achieved a lot after  16...Nb3  17.Rd1  ,  but this blow is quite nice. Qxb2 comes with a typical double attack. }
17. Qxf5 Qxb2 18. Be5
{ It is hard to imagine that White will find this move before playing 15. Qc1 or even 16. Qc2, but of course the engines find it immediately. It turns out that  18...Qxa1+?  19.Nb1  traps the queen and wins the game. }
18... Ng4
{ A crazy move is met with a crazy move. After  19.Qxg4?  we can now safely play  19...Qxa1+  winning the game. Apart from that, 18...Ng4 threatens checkmate with Qxf2. }
19. Ra2
{ Allowing the check on c1 seems like a dangerous idea to me, but we are not able to deliver the final blow yet. }
19... Qc1+ 20. Ke2 Nc4
{ All of our minor pieces are eyeing the e3-pawn, and we will soon start to sacrifice if White gives us the time to do so. }
21. Rc2 Ncxe3
{ We have no choice, but it is still nice. We will trade into an endgame where we only have one pawn for the piece, but White's king is still in danger and we can easily win back the material. }
22. Qxf7+
{ There is not really any good reason for White not to take this pawn. } 22...
Rxf7 23. Rxc1 Nf5
{ With Re7 coming there is no good way for White to save his extra material.  24.Ne4  can be played, but both  24...Bb6  and  24...Bxa3  are fine for Black. }
*

