19... Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Bd4 { Interfering with the defense of White's rook. } 21.
Nxd4
{ The difference between  21.Nf6+  and  21.Nxd4  is that the knight is currently still defending the d2-square, so we cannot play  21...Nc6  here due to  22.Nxc6  . }
21... Qxa1+ 22. Ke2 Nb3
{ 22...Nc6  23.Nf6+  Kh8  24.Qf5  is a little bit annoying. The difference with 21. Nxf6+ has been that White could play Ke2 instead of Kd2. The knight is immune now on b3 as White's queen is unprotected. We just intend to play Nxd4+ exd4 Qxd4 to trade queens or even Rxd4. }
23. Nf6+ Kh8 24. Qf5 Kg7
{ It is better to keep the tension as  25.Nxb3  is anyway not possible due to  25...Qd1#  . }
25. Nh5+ Kg8 26. Kf3
{ 26.Nf6+  forces a draw, but  26.Kf3  is an attempt to play on for White. }
26... Qd1+ 27. Be2 Qxd4
{ As we are about to get mated with Qf6, we need this resource.  28.exd4  can be played, but the endgame after  28...Nxd4+  29.Kg4  Nxf5  30.Kxf5  Rd2  is at least fine for us. }
28. Nf6+ Kg7 29. Qh7+
{ White can win the queen in this way, but their king is still in danger. }
29... Kxf6 30. exd4 Rh8 31. Qd3 Nxd4+ 32. Kg4 h5+ 33. Kh3 g4+ 34. Bxg4 hxg4+
35. Kxg4 Rhg8+
{ With a forced draw. This variation is pretty long, and you should probably not try to learn this by heart. However, I found it difficult to stop the line earlier. The problem is that we do not really have any options to deviate in the whole line. Then why do I recommend this? First of all I think that it is good to show that 10... Nc6 is fully playable. Apart from that, I think that it is a good idea to make this repertoire playable for the very best players. I do not aim to make this repertoire for top players, but I would like it to be playable for them as well. }
*

