{ This is one of the places where the Schara Gambit has really evolved. Back in the days they played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/8/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@ 9. Qb3!@@EndBracket@@  9...Bc5  ,  followed by Qe7 and O-O-O. These days however, it is clear that the right plan is connected to castling kingside and playing things a lot slower. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3
{ Generally speaking I would consider this to be the main line. It is one of the most solid lines that White can play and they can also hope to get an advantage with accurate play. In this chapter we will have no choice but to play for long-term compensation. In other chapters the lines would often get more forcing, but that is not really the case here. Normally we now play the moves Qe7, Rd8 and Nc6, after which White will have to make a choice. }
10... Qe7 11. Bc4
{ Or  11.Bd3  Nc6  12.O-O  Rfd8  when due to threats such as Bf5 or Nb4, the engine recommends  13.Be2  .  That means that 11.Bd3 was just a really bad move. }
11... Nc6 12. O-O Rfd8
{ We just go for the typical setup, and can follow up with Ne5 targetting White's light-squared bishop. It is just not well placed on c4. }
