{ We have finished our development, and the way we continue next in this middlegame depends on what setup White chooses. We have a lot of useful moves here, like Ne5-Bc6, Rac8, a6-b5. If White moves the queen to c2 we can often attack it with Nb4 if White has not played a3 yet. Most of our play will be aimed at either the kingside or the queenside. Due to White's setup and extra pawn on e3 they do not actually have so much freedom for their pieces. This is also where most of our compensation comes from - the extra activity.We will take a look at all the different moves White can make here and see how we should react. What is most important in these positions is to get a feel for them instead of only just trying to remember the exact lines after each move. White's most popular move by far here is the move 13. a3. }
13. Qc2
{ This is the move that is recommended in Kamil Plichta's Chessable course Go for The Throat: Play 1. d4. He, however, failed to mention our reply. }
13... Nb4
{ This is a logical response. We are trying to punish White for not spending time on playing a3. After White has moved the queen we can continue with Bc6. Depending on where White has moved the queen, we can then also continue with either Nbd5 or Nd3.   13...Rac8  was discussed in Kamil Plichta's course, which is also an interesting move. White does play  14.a3  there, which can also be reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp1bqppp/2n2n2/2b5/8/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.a3  Rac8  14.Qc2  . However, after  13.a3  I will be recommending  13...Ne5  instead. }
14. Qb1 Bc6 15. a3 Nbd5
{ The only square for our knight. We have not entered on the light squares, but this reroute to d5 is often what we intend. }
16. Nxd5
{ 16.Bd2  also seems logical, but after  16...Ng4  things are pretty difficult for White with sacrifices incoming on f2 or e3. }
16... Bxd5 17. b4 Bb6
{ We have an active position with good compensation for the pawn.  18.Bb2  is, for example, met by  18...Ng4  with a sacrifice on f2 incoming.   The engine suggests some slightly weird looking  18.Qf5  , but after  18...Be6  we start chasing the queen. }
