13. Qc2
{ This is the move that is recommended in Kamil Plichta's Chessable course Go for The Throat: Play 1. d4. He, however, failed to mention our reply. }
13... Nb4
{ This is a logical response. We are trying to punish White for not spending time on playing a3. After White has moved the queen we can continue with Bc6. Depending on where White has moved the queen, we can then also continue with either Nbd5 or Nd3.   13...Rac8  was discussed in Kamil Plichta's course, which is also an interesting move. White does play  14.a3  there, which can also be reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp1bqppp/2n2n2/2b5/8/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.a3  Rac8  14.Qc2  . However, after  13.a3  I will be recommending  13...Ne5  instead. }
14. Qb1 Bc6 15. Qf5
{ This was already played in a correspondence game back in 2001! This queen sortie is often suggested by the engine, but it is hard to see a human make such a move. Very often the queen is quite safe on c2, while it just protects important squares. }
15... Bd7
{ We should try to keep chasing the queen, as it is quite annoying on f5. It for example stops us from playing Ng4 which would be a nice option to have in certain positions. }
16. Qe5
{ White tries to trade queens, and as we are a pawn down we should prevent this with  16...Be6  . }
16... Be6
{ We intend to play Bd6 next, when White's queen will start to feel uncomfortable. }
17. Bd2 Bd6 18. Qa5
{ A typical engine line, which I do not think is likely to happen in practice. However, it does seem to me like I should cover the line a bit as it is one of the critical lines the engine suggests. }
18... a6
{ Preparing to play b5. By doing this we can afterwards try to trap the queen, as b5 takes away the a4-square. }
19. a3
{ This seems the most logical to me, just trying to kick away the knight. }
19... b5
{ 19...Nc6  is also possible, but this move is simply strong. We will win back the piece anyway after 20.axb4 as White's queen is about to get trapped. }
20. axb4 Bxb4 21. Nd5
{ 21.Qb6  is also possible, but after either  21...Bc5  or  21...Rd6  White's queen is in danger. The move 21. Nd5 ensures that White does not risk anything in the position. }
21... Nxd5
{ Capturing the knight, but protecting the dark-squared bishop at the same time. }
22. Bxb4 Qxb4 23. Nd4
{ Bf3 is now a pretty big threat, after which it will be difficult for us to move. }
23... Qxa5 24. Rxa5 Nb4
{ With a fairly equal position. White has a nice square on d4 for the knight, but we have a potential passed pawn on the queenside in return for it. This is a scenario we have seen more often in the Schara Gambit. As long as there is a pawn on e3, White will usually have an outpost on d4. However, our knight is well placed on b4 as well as it is difficult to attack. It protects the a6-pawn, which means that we can just play Rac8 next with a fine position. }
*

