{ This was played in the mentioned correspondence game, but trying to trade queens with  16.Qe5  also makes sense. After  16.Qf4  the correspondence game continued with  16...Bg4  , but I find  16...Rac8  to also be quite a good move and more logical. }
16... Rac8
{ White was intending to meet  16...Bd6  with  17.Qh4  .  By starting with Rac8 we can play Bd6-Qh4 and follow it up with Nc2-Rc5-Rh5. }
17. a3 Nc2 18. Rb1 Bd6 19. Qh4 Rc5 { Followed by Rh5 with a dangerous attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qd1 with 10.e3"]
[Black "10. e3 with 11. Be2 and 13. Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we have seen. }
8. Qd1
{ This is the safest retreating square for the queen, and the move seen the most in practice. White generally just wants to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and O-O. }
8... Bc5
{ This is one of the places where the Schara Gambit has really evolved. Back in the days they played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/8/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@ 9. Qb3!@@EndBracket@@  9...Bc5  ,  followed by Qe7 and O-O-O. These days however, it is clear that the right plan is connected to castling kingside and playing things a lot slower. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3
{ Generally speaking I would consider this to be the main line. It is one of the most solid lines that White can play and they can also hope to get an advantage with accurate play. In this chapter we will have no choice but to play for long-term compensation. In other chapters the lines would often get more forcing, but that is not really the case here. Normally we now play the moves Qe7, Rd8 and Nc6, after which White will have to make a choice. }
10... Qe7 11. Be2
{ The bishop is best on e2. We have seen that it can become vulnerable on d3 or c4. }
11... Rd8
{ Starting with  11...Nc6  is possible, and also even gives an extra possibility instead of playing Rfd8, namely  12.O-O  Ne5  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@, which I've given as an alternative option.   However, most players go for the move order  11...Rd8  . In a way we hope that White will get scared for what is about to happen on the d-file and already make a choice with their queen. However, White can just safely play  12.O-O  after which we do not really have a choice and should just play  12...Nc6  . }
12. O-O Nc6
{ We have finished our development, and the way we continue next in this middlegame depends on what setup White chooses. We have a lot of useful moves here, like Ne5-Bc6, Rac8, a6-b5. If White moves the queen to c2 we can often attack it with Nb4 if White has not played a3 yet. Most of our play will be aimed at either the kingside or the queenside. Due to White's setup and extra pawn on e3 they do not actually have so much freedom for their pieces. This is also where most of our compensation comes from - the extra activity.We will take a look at all the different moves White can make here and see how we should react. What is most important in these positions is to get a feel for them instead of only just trying to remember the exact lines after each move. White's most popular move by far here is the move 13. a3. }
13. Qb3
{ This move seems somewhat illogical at first, as the point is to meet  13...Be6  with  14.Qc2  . After @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp1bqppp/2n2n2/2b5/8/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  , my recommendation is  13...Nb4  14.Qb1  Bc6  .  With the bishop on e6 we can't play this way. }
13... a6
{ This is generally a useful move as it prepares b5, but in this case it also prevents  14.Qxb7  due to  14...Rdb8  and the a6-square has now been taken away. }
14. a3
{ Against both  14.Rd1  and  14.Bd2  we are getting counterplay with Be6 with sometimes even Nb4, so preventing Nb4 makes quite a lot of sense. As we often play b5 as well, b4 will not be as much of a threat anymore with a pawn on a3. }
14... Bf5
{ This is simply the most active square for the bishop, and taking away c2 from the queen. As we intend to follow up with b5, we could have also started with  14...b5  .  After we have played b5, the queen on b3 will start to feel the heat, as the only available square will be a2. That makes Na5-Qa2-Be6-Qb1-Nb3 a pretty big threat. }
15. Rd1 b5 { Na5 is now a threat, so Qa2 makes sense. } 16. Qa2
{ However, it does feel like playing a3 and moving the queen to a2 is in the wrong direction. }
16... Rxd1+
{ This trade makes more sense now that White cannot take back with the queen. One of White's minor pieces will now have to go passive. }
17. Nxd1 Rd8
{ Taking control over the d-file. White has played very passively so far. We can improve our position with Ne4, and can maybe even throw in g5-g4 to disrupt White's coordination. White will have to be careful of sacrifices on f2 the whole time as well. }
*

