{ This is simply the most active square for the bishop, and taking away c2 from the queen. As we intend to follow up with b5, we could have also started with  14...b5  .  After we have played b5, the queen on b3 will start to feel the heat, as the only available square will be a2. That makes Na5-Qa2-Be6-Qb1-Nb3 a pretty big threat. }
15. Bd2 b5 16. Qa2
{ The queen is again quite passive, so let's start the counterplay. } 16... Ne5
{ The bishop on d2 is always quite vulnerable, and we should try to make use of that. We are not directly threatening to a win a piece, as after  17.--  Nxf3+  18.Bxf3  our rook on a8 is also under attack. However we can play Rac8 on the next move which would threaten Nxf3+. Anyway, White will likely play b4 here, gaining a tempo on our bishop and protecting their dark-squared bishop with the queen as well. }
17. b4 Ba7
{ Dropping back the bishop to b6 is possible too, but the a7-square looks even better. We often want the bishop to get to the h2-b8 diagonal, and the b8-square seems better than c7, as the bishop won't block the c-file from there. We can even consider playing Bb8 with the rook on a8, as the rook on a8 can also be activated by pushing a5. Another idea is to play Qc7 next to create attacking ideas with Nfg4, which would threaten Nxf3+ Qxh2#. }
