{ This is generally a useful move as it prepares b5, but in this case it also prevents  14.Qxb7  due to  14...Rdb8  and the a6-square has now been taken away. }
14. Rd1
{ This is one of the generally useful moves that White can play in the Schara gambit, but it does not seem that great here without the rooks being connected. }
14... Be6
{ Now we do play Be6, trying to make use of the fact that the tension between the rooks should benefit us as we have ours connected while White doesn't. }
15. Qa4 Nb4
{ Preparing b5 and taking away the c2-square. We are preparing b5 as the knight is now protecting the a6-pawn. The immediate  15...b5  is met by  16.Rxd8+  and we cannot meet it with  16...Rxd8  due to  17.Qxa6  . }
16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Bd2
{ White has freed the d1-square for the queen, but giving up the d-file is a concession. }
17... b5 18. Qd1 Bf5
{ With an active position for Black. It is not easy for White to make moves here. If we play Nd3 at any moment White should probably give up the bishop pair with Bxd3. We also have plans of Ng4 with the intention to sacrifice on f2 or e3 or reroute it to e5. }
