{ We have finished our development, and the way we continue next in this middlegame depends on what setup White chooses. We have a lot of useful moves here, like Ne5-Bc6, Rac8, a6-b5. If White moves the queen to c2 we can often attack it with Nb4 if White has not played a3 yet. Most of our play will be aimed at either the kingside or the queenside. Due to White's setup and extra pawn on e3 they do not actually have so much freedom for their pieces. This is also where most of our compensation comes from - the extra activity.We will take a look at all the different moves White can make here and see how we should react. What is most important in these positions is to get a feel for them instead of only just trying to remember the exact lines after each move. White's most popular move by far here is the move 13. a3. }
13. Qb3
{ This move seems somewhat illogical at first, as the point is to meet  13...Be6  with  14.Qc2  . After @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp1bqppp/2n2n2/2b5/8/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  , my recommendation is  13...Nb4  14.Qb1  Bc6  .  With the bishop on e6 we can't play this way. }
13... a6
{ This is generally a useful move as it prepares b5, but in this case it also prevents  14.Qxb7  due to  14...Rdb8  and the a6-square has now been taken away. }
14. Bd2
{ This is quite a good attempt for White if they are well prepared against the Schara Gambit. }
14... Be6
{ Now with a target on d2 we can go for counterplay like this. We cannot allow White to just play Rfd1 and Rac1.  14...Bf5  seems like an interesting alternative, but after  15.Rfd1!  b5  16.Nh4!  it is not easy to prove equality. After  16...Be6  17.Qc2  Bb6  things still remain messy, but in terms of objective evaluation White should be somewhat better. }
15. Qc2 Nb4
{ Usually if we can get in Nb4 and Bf5 we are quite happy as we can then try to win the bishop pair with Nd3. }
16. Qb1
{ Trying to prevent Bf5, and now if White is just able to play Ne4 or a3 they can be pretty happy. }
16... Bg4
{ We have to keep the initiative going, before White is able to consolidate. By playing Bg4 we threaten to win a piece with  17.--  Bxf3  followed by  18.--  Rxd2  . Ideally we would immediately play @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/1p2qppp/p3bn2/2b5/1n6/2N1PN2/PP1BBPPP/RQ3RK1 b - - 5 16@@EndFEN@@  16...g6  followed by 17...Bf5, but  17.e4  is rather annoying. By including the moves Bg4 and Rfd1 the rook is not defending f2 anymore. f2 is typically the weak point in White's position if they push e4. }
17. Rd1 g6 { Preparing Bf5, which can be pretty nasty if allowed. } 18. e4 Bxf3
{ With the newly created weakness on f2, we should go after it quickly before White stabilizes. White should take back with the bishop, as gxf3 weakens the king too much. This will open up the d3-square for our knight. }
19. Bxf3 Nd3 20. Be3 { Not intending to take back on e3, but on d3 instead. }
20... Bxe3 21. Rxd3 Ba7
{ There are other alternatives to consider here, such as  21...Bf4  ,  rerouting the bishop to e5.  21...Ba7  is my preference as the pressure on f2 will be practically more difficult for White to deal with. We will be a pawn down for some time to come, but we have quite a lot of positional compensation. First of all, the difference between the bishops is huge. Our bishop is quite active and has targets in this position, while White's bishop is mainly stuck protecting the e4-pawn. We have to be careful of e4-e5, but that should not be too difficult. We have quite a lot of improving moves here, such as Qc5, b5@@StartBracket@@watch out for e5!@@EndBracket@@, h5 and Kg7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5.Qa4+: 8.Qd1 with 10.e3"]
[Black "10. e3 with 11. Be2 and 13. Qb3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4
{ The start of the Von-Hennig Schara Gambit. From this point onwards, White should accept the gambit in some way, as Black is at least comfortable otherwise.   Instead of  4...cxd4  the much more common way to play for Black is  4...exd5  ,  which is called the Tarrasch Defense. Isolated queen's pawn positions usually arise in the Tarrasch Defense. In the Schara Gambit, Black sacrifices the d5-pawn instead to speed up development and gain the initiative. }
5. Qa4+
{ Although this move looks strange at first, it is quite clever in a way. After  5.Qxd4  we gain a tempo by playing  5...Nc6  before capturing on d5. Now after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  the light-squared bishop is blocking the d-file, which stops us from playing Nc6.You can also see from for example the Lichess database that 5. Qxd4 is played around five times as much as 5. Qa4+, as it is the most straightforward move. On the other hand, it is interesting to see that the average rating of players playing 5. Qa4+ is about 200 points higher!Interestingly, 5. Qa4+ is slightly more popular in my database of over the board games. The big difference is very likely due to the difference in time controls used. }
5... Bd7
{ The most logical move. The dubious gambit of  5...b5  is sometimes tried, but it should of course be rather bad. White seems to have more or less a winning advantage after  6.Nxb5  Bd7  7.e4! }
6. Qxd4 exd5 { As we can't play Nc6 we should just take back. } 7. Qxd5
{ If we compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3P4/3p4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  ,  it seems as if Nc6 has been more useful than Bd7. However, this is not fully the case. The point is actually that in the 5. Qxd4 variation, White is threatening to exchange queens. Due to this, we have to compromise a bit to avoid the queen exchange. Here, we can just continue our development and get the ideal setup with Bc5 and Qe7. }
7... Nf6
{ The most logical continuation. We do not start with Nc6 as we want to keep flexibility. For example, in the 8. Qb3  line we will put the knight on a6 instead. We are also not afraid of Qxb7 as we have seen. }
8. Qd1
{ This is the safest retreating square for the queen, and the move seen the most in practice. White generally just wants to play Nf3, e3, Be2 and O-O. }
8... Bc5
{ This is one of the places where the Schara Gambit has really evolved. Back in the days they played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/8/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@ 9. Qb3!@@EndBracket@@  9...Bc5  ,  followed by Qe7 and O-O-O. These days however, it is clear that the right plan is connected to castling kingside and playing things a lot slower. }
9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3
{ Generally speaking I would consider this to be the main line. It is one of the most solid lines that White can play and they can also hope to get an advantage with accurate play. In this chapter we will have no choice but to play for long-term compensation. In other chapters the lines would often get more forcing, but that is not really the case here. Normally we now play the moves Qe7, Rd8 and Nc6, after which White will have to make a choice. }
10... Qe7 11. Be2
{ The bishop is best on e2. We have seen that it can become vulnerable on d3 or c4. }
11... Rd8
{ Starting with  11...Nc6  is possible, and also even gives an extra possibility instead of playing Rfd8, namely  12.O-O  Ne5  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@, which I've given as an alternative option.   However, most players go for the move order  11...Rd8  . In a way we hope that White will get scared for what is about to happen on the d-file and already make a choice with their queen. However, White can just safely play  12.O-O  after which we do not really have a choice and should just play  12...Nc6  . }
12. O-O Nc6
{ We have finished our development, and the way we continue next in this middlegame depends on what setup White chooses. We have a lot of useful moves here, like Ne5-Bc6, Rac8, a6-b5. If White moves the queen to c2 we can often attack it with Nb4 if White has not played a3 yet. Most of our play will be aimed at either the kingside or the queenside. Due to White's setup and extra pawn on e3 they do not actually have so much freedom for their pieces. This is also where most of our compensation comes from - the extra activity.We will take a look at all the different moves White can make here and see how we should react. What is most important in these positions is to get a feel for them instead of only just trying to remember the exact lines after each move. White's most popular move by far here is the move 13. a3. }
13. Qb3
{ This move seems somewhat illogical at first, as the point is to meet  13...Be6  with  14.Qc2  . After @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp1bqppp/2n2n2/2b5/8/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  , my recommendation is  13...Nb4  14.Qb1  Bc6  .  With the bishop on e6 we can't play this way. }
13... a6
{ This is generally a useful move as it prepares b5, but in this case it also prevents  14.Qxb7  due to  14...Rdb8  and the a6-square has now been taken away. }
14. Bd2
{ This is quite a good attempt for White if they are well prepared against the Schara Gambit. }
14... Be6
{ Now with a target on d2 we can go for counterplay like this. We cannot allow White to just play Rfd1 and Rac1.  14...Bf5  seems like an interesting alternative, but after  15.Rfd1!  b5  16.Nh4!  it is not easy to prove equality. After  16...Be6  17.Qc2  Bb6  things still remain messy, but in terms of objective evaluation White should be somewhat better. }
15. Qc2 Nb4
{ Usually if we can get in Nb4 and Bf5 we are quite happy as we can then try to win the bishop pair with Nd3. }
16. Qb1
{ Trying to prevent Bf5, and now if White is just able to play Ne4 or a3 they can be pretty happy. }
16... Bg4
{ We have to keep the initiative going, before White is able to consolidate. By playing Bg4 we threaten to win a piece with  17.--  Bxf3  followed by  18.--  Rxd2  . Ideally we would immediately play @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/1p2qppp/p3bn2/2b5/1n6/2N1PN2/PP1BBPPP/RQ3RK1 b - - 5 16@@EndFEN@@  16...g6  followed by 17...Bf5, but  17.e4  is rather annoying. By including the moves Bg4 and Rfd1 the rook is not defending f2 anymore. f2 is typically the weak point in White's position if they push e4. }
17. Rd1 g6 { Preparing Bf5, which can be pretty nasty if allowed. } 18. a3
{ When talking about the Schara Gambit with Anish Giri, this was one of the critical lines that we discussed. This move pretty much forces an endgame where it was a bit unclear to us how easy it is for Black. }
18... Bf5 19. Qc1
{ 19.e4  is not advisable as we seem to be in the driver seat after  19...Nxe4  . }
19... Nc2
{ We have to go for this. After  19...Nd3  we do win the bishop pair as White should play  20.Bxd3  . But after  20...Bxd3  21.Be1  followed by Nd4 we simply do not have enough compensation for the pawn as White has gotten the position under control and will be able to finish their development harmoniously. }
20. Ra2
{ This feels a lot more natural than  20.Rb1  .  As b4 is incoming the rook will eventually target our knight. 20.Rb1 is also just bad for concrete reasons, as after  20...Ng4  followed by a sacrifice on e3 things will soon collapse. }
20... Rac8
{ We could not stop b4, so it is best to prepare for it in the best way possible. Due to White's passive position we are able to sacrifice the knight. }
21. b4 Nxb4
{ Giving up the knight, but due to our activity we will win back the invested material. }
22. axb4 Bxb4
{ We only have one pawn for the knight, but as we are about to play Ne4 we will win back the sacrificed material. We are also just threatening Rxd2, followed by taking the knight on c3. We will have a pawn and a bishop for the exchange, but have also gotten rid of White's bishop pair. Eventually our two connected passed pawns will also become quite strong. }
23. Nd4 Rxd4
{ Sacrificing another exchange, but we are about to win back at least a piece.  23...Ne4  was also just pretty bad due to  24.Nxf5  gxf5  25.Nd5!  winning material. By sacrificing on d4 first, we don't allow Nxf5. }
24. exd4 Bxc3 25. Bxc3 Nd5
{ This will make sure that we win back a bishop, after which we have a pawn and a knight for the rook. Due to our connected passed pawns and blockade on d5, we will have at least a fine position. However, White has a concrete attempt at an advantage here. }
26. Re1 Nxc3
{ We have to take with the knight, because White is coordinated quite nicely after  26...Rxc3  27.Qa1  followed by Bf3 and Ra5. The blockade will be difficult to maintain in that case. Nxc3 also just makes sense as a lot of pieces are vulnerable in White's position. }
27. Bd3
{ We cannot allow White to play Rc2 here. The pin would be overwhelming. }
27... Qb4
{ A sharp answer to a sharp move. We can now play Ne2+ on the next move @@StartBracket@@the immediate  27...Ne2+  28.Raxe2  Rxc1  29.Rxe7  loses material@@EndBracket@@. }
28. Bxf5 Ne2+ 29. Raxe2 Rxc1 30. Rxc1 gxf5
{ After a lot of exchanges an interesting position has appeared. White should be in the driver seat, and this is the position that I was discussing with Anish Giri. He was not sure how easy it is to hold for Black, but it seems to me that it also requires quite a lot of techique from White to get something here. I could easily imagine that we will see a high level game fight out in this position in the future. On the other hand, it might not be easy for both players to recall all the way up to this point.In this position we have two connected passed pawns, but as they are quite far back, they are not really as threatening as passed pawns usually are. The two rooks are quite strong.   What we first need to do is block the d-pawn, as it is the biggest threat for now. We can do this, for example, by meeting  31.Rd1  with  31...Qb3  32.Ree1  Qd5  .  Afterwards we intend to start running on the queenside, but we have to be careful. One of the two pawns will likely end up being backwards, and if White manages to double up the rooks on the backward pawn we will lose it. However, if White is not careful and the pawns get too far, they could also become problematic for him. Another issue that White has is that they will probably have to waste an important tempo somewhere on creating luft for their king with a move such as h3. }
*

