16. Rfd1 Neg4
{ Whenever the f1-rook leaves its post, the f2-square is always weak. We are now ready to play Nxf2 followed by Ng4+ with a crushing attack, so the only move after which White is still okay is h3. }
17. h3 Nxf2
{ In fact, even the sacrifice  17...Nxe3  is alright here. Even though we do not have the g4-square for our knight anymore, White's king will still be quite vulnerable. }
18. Kxf2 Bxf3
{ Getting rid of more defensive troops.  19.Bxf3  is now met by  19...Rxd2+!  with a great position for Black. }
19. gxf3 Qe5
{ 19...Rxd2  would this time leave us with too little after  20.Rxd2  Qxe3+  21.Ke1  .  By playing Qe5 we are threatening Qh2+ which will lead to checkmate. }
20. Kg2 { White's only move that doesn't lose. } 20... Qg5+ 21. Kh2 Rxd2
{ Removing White's defenses on the dark squares. } 22. Rxd2 Bxe3 23. Rc2
{ The only move for White again, but it does force a draw. If White manages to play Ne4 they will have their defenses in order, which forces us to make a draw in some way @@StartBracket@@there are multiple ways to do so@@EndBracket@@. }
23... Qe5+
{ This seems like the easiest way to make a draw with  24.Kg2  Qg5+  . If  25.Kh1  is played then  25...Qg3  just wins due to the mate threat on h3. It should be clear that White had a really tough defensive task up until this point. }
*

