9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3
{ Generally speaking I would consider this to be the main line. It is one of the most solid lines that White can play and they can also hope to get an advantage with accurate play. In this chapter we will have no choice but to play for long-term compensation. In other chapters the lines would often get more forcing, but that is not really the case here. Normally we now play the moves Qe7, Rd8 and Nc6, after which White will have to make a choice. }
10... Qe7 11. Be2
{ The bishop is best on e2. We have seen that it can become vulnerable on d3 or c4. }
11... Rd8
{ Starting with  11...Nc6  is possible, and also even gives an extra possibility instead of playing Rfd8, namely  12.O-O  Ne5  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@, which I've given as an alternative option.   However, most players go for the move order  11...Rd8  . In a way we hope that White will get scared for what is about to happen on the d-file and already make a choice with their queen. However, White can just safely play  12.O-O  after which we do not really have a choice and should just play  12...Nc6  . }
12. O-O Nc6
{ We have finished our development, and the way we continue next in this middlegame depends on what setup White chooses. We have a lot of useful moves here, like Ne5-Bc6, Rac8, a6-b5. If White moves the queen to c2 we can often attack it with Nb4 if White has not played a3 yet. Most of our play will be aimed at either the kingside or the queenside. Due to White's setup and extra pawn on e3 they do not actually have so much freedom for their pieces. This is also where most of our compensation comes from - the extra activity.We will take a look at all the different moves White can make here and see how we should react. What is most important in these positions is to get a feel for them instead of only just trying to remember the exact lines after each move. White's most popular move by far here is the move 13. a3. }
13. Nd4
{ Although this blocks the d-file, it is quite a strange move. What usually happens in these kinds of positions is that we play Ne5 to try to trade off the knights. White's best reply is often to play Nd4, after which we should maybe even retreat with Nc6. White will now have to constantly deal with the pressure on d4 in the long term, while they should not like to trade on either. }
13... Rac8 14. Bf3 Bb6
{ Just making a small improving move, as it clears the c-file. We still have improving moves such as Qe5 and h5, while White will find it difficult to make moves due to the pressure on d4. }
