14. Qc2 Bc6
{ Due to the tension on f3, other moves than 15. Nd4 do not seem to make that much sense. Although it seems odd, it actually is never that bad to allow the gxf3 structure for White. }
15. Nd4 { This gives back the pawn, but White gets the bishop pair in return. }
15... Bxd4 16. exd4 Rxd4 17. Be3
{ White should be slightly more comfortable due to the bishop pair. On the other hand, our pieces are more active, and we have some potential play against White's king. }
17... Rh4
{ Threatening  18.--  Bxg2  19.Kxg2  Qe6  ,  but it is quite easy for White to just kick out our rook with 18. Bg5. The point is actually that  @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp2qppp/2b2n2/4n3/3r4/P1N1B3/1PQ1BPPP/R4RK1 b - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Rh4  18.Bg5  Rd4  19.Rad1  Rxd1  20.Rxd1  h6  21.Be3  wins Black a full tempo in comparison to, for example,  17...Rdd8  18.Rad1  Rxd1  19.Rxd1  h6  , where the same position has White to move instead of Black. }
18. Bg5 Rd4
{ It is a pity that we cannot go for  18...Rxh2  here. There is a long line that leads to an endgame with good defense after  19.Kxh2  Nfg4+  20.Kg3  Qxg5  21.f4  Qh6  22.Rh1  Ne3  23.Qb1  Qg6+  24.Qxg6  Nxg6  25.Bf3  Nf5+  26.Kf2  Nxf4  wins a second pawn for the exchange, but after  27.Rhd1  Black's position is just pretty bad. The two extra pawns on the kingside are really far away from becoming passed pawns, while White's extra rook is going to become quite strong. This means that after 18. Bg5 we are forced to return to d4. }
19. Rad1 Rxd1
{ We exchange rooks, as  19...Rad8  loses a pawn to  20.Rxd4  Rxd4  21.Be3  . }
20. Rxd1 h6
{ White's position could be considered more pleasant due to the bishop pair, but our pieces are better coordinated and allow us to go for a kingside attack. For example,  21.Be3  can be met with  21...Nfg4  22.Bd4  Qg5  23.Ne4  Qg6  24.f3  Re8  with Nxf3+ incoming.Apart from such possibilities, we can just play normal improving moves as well such as ...a6, ...Re8 and ...Ng6. }
