[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Grünfeld, Ernst vs. Schara, Anton, Vienna 1918"]
[Result "*"]

{ The first three games of this chapter have mainly been added to show some history of the Schara Gambit. They, however, are also just very nice games to show to you. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Heinrich von Hennig would go on to play  7...Be6  years later, which is also a possibility. It is not fully correct, and my recommendations in this position are  7...Bd6  and  7...Qc7  . }
8. Bg5 Nge7 9. Qd2 f6
{ A mistake, although I do understand that the move seems logical. In a way, my recommendation of  9...h6  seems slightly odd, as after  10.Bh4  White is still pinning the knight. The idea, however, is that after  10...Qb6  11.Qxd6  Qxb2  White is not able to play  12.Rc1  with the bishop on h4.   Another benefit of playing h6 instead of f6, is that after  10.Rd1  hxg5  the h-file has been opened, while @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2nppp/2nb4/6B1/8/2N5/PP1QPPPP/R3KBNR b KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...f6  10.Rd1  fxg5  only weakens our king. }
10. Bh4 Qb6
{ Anton Schara clearly did understand that the bishop had to be driven away from g5 to make this move possible. }
11. Nf3 Bb4
{ 11...Be6  would have been more in the spirit of the position, as the dark-squared bishop has already been developed.  12.Qxd6  was anyway not possible due to  12...Qxb2  .  After 11...Be6 Black can follow up with 12...O-O-O with a nice initiative. }
12. e3 Bf5 { Preparing Rd8. } 13. Bc4
{ As is often the case in the Schara Gambit, the bishop should be on e2. On c4 it is only exposed to attacks. }
13... Na5
{ 13...Qc5  should have been preferred, as the knight is not great on a5. The queen also adds more pressure on c3. For example  14.Be2  Rd8  15.Qc1  Nd5  would give Black a nice position. }
14. Bd3
{ White seems to have failed to understand that the bishop should not be exposed so much, first putting it on c4 and now on d3. }
14... Rd8 15. Nd4 Nac6
{ Now White was starting to feel the heat, perhaps missing this move in advance when playing 14. Bd3. }
16. Nxf5
{ This move loses the game, but it was already a difficult position as  16.Rd1  was the only move that could save it. The point is that after  16...Nxd4  17.exd4  Rxd4?  White is actually doing great after  18.Bb5+!  Instead,  17...Bxd3  18.Qxd3  Qe6+  should give Black a nice initiative. }
16... Nxf5 17. Bg3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Ne5 19. Bb5+ Qxb5
{ This was probably missed when White played 16. Nxf5, and it is easy to understand why.  20.Nxb5  loses to  20...Rxd2  or  20...Bxd2+  , while  20.Qxd8+  Kxd8  leaves the knight on c3 pinned and White down a queen. The first game with the Schara Gambit was rather succesful! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Benzinger, Josef vs. von Hennig, Heinrich, Bled 1929"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 Be6
{ Although this move immediately heads for the endgame, it does set up some traps for White as a quick Nb4 or Nd4 is coming with a deadly fork on c2. }
8. Qxd8+ Rxd8 9. e3
{ 9.Bd2  is actually the best move, after which White should have a pleasant endgame, meeting  9...Nb4  with  10.Rc1  giving back the pawn. }
9... Nb4
{ 9...a6  should be preferred, avoiding Bb5. I do understand the appeal of 9... Nb4 however. }
10. Bb5+ Ke7 11. Ba4
{ White already makes a mistake.  11.Kf1!  was an improvement, found by Smyslov in 1951. After 11.Kf1 White is doing great as Black's initiative is not going anywhere. }
11... Bc4
{ With b5 coming, White has a hard time defending all the light squares. } 12.
Nge2 b5 13. Bd1 Nd3+ 14. Kf1 { White has managed to stay solid, but passive. }
14... b4 15. Ne4 f5
{ 15...Nf6  was an improvement, intending to activate the passive pieces quickly after  16.Nxf6  Kxf6  . }
16. N4g3 g6 17. Bc2
{ White needed to act quickly with  17.Bb3  . Now after  17...Bg7  White is even more passive than before. }
17... Bg7 18. Bxd3 Bxd3
{ 18...Rxd3  was even stronger, followed by Kf7-Ne7-Rhd8 after White has dealt with the Rd1# threat. }
19. f3 Rc8
{ Too slow. Black is fighting for the initiative and should try to develop the remaining pieces. White would have had a better position now after  20.Kf2  Rc2  21.Rd1  . }
20. Ke1
{ It is unclear to me why White did not grab this opportunity to activate pieces. }
20... Nf6 21. Nf4 Bc2 22. Bd2 a5
{ Now Black is dominating again, and White should collapse once the h8-rook starts to participate. }
23. Rc1 Nd7 { With Bb2/Bxb2 coming, White is going to lose material. } 24. Nd5+
Ke6 25. Nf4+ Kf7 26. b3 Bb2 27. Kf2 Bxc1 28. Rxc1 Ne5 29. h4 Rhd8 30. Be1 Nd3+
31. Nxd3 Bxd3 32. Ra1 Rc2+ 33. Kg1 Rdc8
{ Black is still dominating, is up in material and picking up even more very soon. After the joint efforts of Heinrich von Hennig and Anton Schara, the gambit was named after them: The Von Hennig-Schara Gambit. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pirc, Vasja vs. Alekhine, Alexander, Bled 1931"]
[Result "*"]

{ This was the first time the Schara Gambit was used by a World Champion, and it took 91  (!!)  years for it to happen for the second time. Now in 2022, it is clear that the Schara Gambit is fully playable and that it has a much better status than it had decades or even just years ago. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6
8. Bg5
{ White tries to get out the dark-squared bishop before playing e3, but that is usually a bad idea in such positions as it leaves the b2-pawn weak. White should instead focus on getting the king out of the center as soon as possible. }
8... Nf6 9. Qd2 h6
{ White would normally like to react to this move with Bh4, but  10.Bh4  is bad here due to  10...g5  11.Bg3  Qa5  with a strong initiative. }
10. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Black is now guaranteed some long-term compensation due to the bishop pair. }
11. e3
{ This is too slow. White should have used the d5-square instead with  11.Nd5  . }
11... O-O-O { Why not! } 12. O-O-O
{ The same cannot be said for White. Castling queenside is quite typical for Black in the Schara Gambit, but I have never really seen it be a good idea for White. Both kings are quite exposed on the queenside, but due to the lead in development that Black has, Black is the only one able to make use of it. }
12... Bg4 { The start of a powerful combination. } 13. Nd5 Rxd5
{ Sacrificing an exchange to gain time. } 14. Qxd5 Ba3
{ A beautiful combination that started with 12... Bg4. What a way to show the power of the Schara Gambit!  15.bxa3  now loses to  15...Qa1+  16.Kc2  Bxd1+  17.Qxd1  Qxa2+  followed by Rd8. }
15. Qb3 Bxd1 16. Qxa3 Qxf2
{ White was about to survive, but the attack keeps on going. } 17. Qd3
{ Intending to play Nh3 next. } 17... Bg4
{ Preventing  18.Nh3  as it loses to  18...Qe1+  19.Kc2  Nb4+  .  Alexander Alekhine did a great job of making Vasja Pirc's life miserable in this game. }
18. Nf3 Bxf3 19. Qf5+ Kb8 20. Qxf3 Qe1+
{ The attack is still going strong, and by moving the king to b8 Black is about to have the last piece join on c8. }
21. Kc2 Rc8 22. Qg3+ Ne5+ 23. Kb3 Qd1+ 24. Ka3 Rc5
{ And finally White resigned, not being able to put up any more resistance as Ra5 was coming. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Artemiev, Vladislav vs. Carlsen, Magnus, Chess24 Rapid 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game started out completely different from our repertoire, but eventually transposed back into it. }
1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 d5 5. d4 a6
{ Now we are back in our first chapter, normally reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c5  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  a6  . }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. g3 c4
{ I thought it should be useful to show a game with this pawn structure, as it can often be reached in the 5...  a6 lines. Black would like to finish development and consolidate, when the space advantage on the queenside should give Black an edge. }
8. Bg2 Bb4 9. Bd2 O-O 10. Ne5 Nc6 11. O-O Re8 12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Magnus Carlsen has actually played my recommendation line all the way up to this position. Black should now have a more pleasant position due to the space advantage on the queenside. It looks like White can do something about it by playing 13. b3, but Magnus reacts in a clever way. }
13. b3 a5
{ Intending to meet  14.bxc4  with  14...Ba6  to play Bxc4 and not ruin Black's pawn structure.   It was actually not bad at all to just play  13...cxb3  ,  and then soon play h5-h4 which is a typical plan in these positions. }
14. bxc4 Ba6 15. Qc2 Bxc4 16. Rfb1 Bxc3
{ Magnus makes the right call here, understanding that White's knight would have been quite powerful if White had the time to play Na4. White will get the bishop pair now, but it is not so great in this closed position. Especially White's light-squared bishop finds it hard to do much. }
17. Bxc3 Ne4
{ This knight will actually remain on e4 until the game ends. White never wants to play Bxe4 as it weakens the king too much. Playing f3 looks bad as well as it weakens the e-pawn and shuts out the light-squared bishop even more. }
18. Be1 h5
{ When Black finds the time for it, this is the correct plan. Now  19.h4  weakens White's kingside even more, but allowing Black to play h4 is not great either. }
19. Qd1 h4
{ Now Black can eventually go for a rook lift with Re6-Rh6 to attack on the h-file. }
20. g4
{ This closes things for now, but the pawn on h4 will be annoying White for the long term. }
20... a4
{ Magnus wants to create an outpost on b5 for the bishop to be able to close off the queenside. It is also quite annoying for White to allow Black to play a3. }
21. a3 Bb3 22. Qe2 Re6
{ From here on Magnus goes a bit astray. Up until here he has basically played perfectly, showing various nice strategical ideas. It makes sense also, because it was a rapid game so time must have gotten somewhat low around here.   He could have started to really punish Vladislav Artemiev here with  22...c5!  23.dxc5  Nxc5  ,  followed by 24... Bc4 and 25... Nb3. }
23. Rc1 Qg5 24. f4
{ Magnus is trying to get White to play f4, but that's actually a useful move for White. }
24... Qe7 25. Bb4
{ White is now back in the game, having gained space on the kingside and activating the bishop. }
25... Qc7 26. f5
{ White could have finally activated the light-squared bishop with  26.g5  followed by Bh3. }
26... Ree8 27. Qe1 Qd8 28. Rxc6 h3
{ The attack is finally starting. Magnus throws in this pawn sacrifice to uncoordinate White. }
29. Bxh3 Qg5 30. Qe2 Rac8
{ Setting up a sneaky trap. Now Rac1 makes a lot of sense for White, but it loses on the spot. }
31. Rac1 { White would have been fine after  31.Rxc8  instead. } 31... Bc4
{ Winning the game instantly. } 32. Rxc8 Bxe2 33. Rxe8+ Kh7
{ Black did not win material, but with the queen missing White is simply collapsing on e3 or g4. }
34. Bd2 Bxg4 35. Bg2 Bf3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Johansson, Linus vs. Hector, Jonny, Copenhagen 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. e3
{ White of course does not have to capture the d5-pawn, but this usually leads to a pleasant version of the typical isolated queen's pawn positions. It seemed like adding an IQP game would be a good thing to do, as they can arise via the 4. e3 line but also if White does not take our pawn in the Schara Gambit. }
7... Nf6 8. Nf3 Bc5
{ 8...Bd6  is the move I recommended in chapter 2 @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@, but  8...Bc5  and  8...Bb4  are also perfectly viable. The bishop on c5 will support the d4-break, instead of focusing on the kingside. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O a6
{ This is always a useful move in IQP positions, giving more room to our dark-squared bishop but also stopping the manoeuvre Nb5-Nfd4/Nbd4. }
11. a3 Re8 12. b4 Ba7
{ The bishop is quite nice on a7. It not only supports the d4-break, but once we get in Bg4, Qd6 and Rad8 it can also be brought to b8 to aid the attack. }
13. Qb3
{ An inaccurate move that could have been punished. It was better to start with the more logical  13.Bb2  . }
13... Bg4
{ 13...d4!  Would have been strong.  14.Rd1  could be met with  14...Be6  15.Qc2  Rc8  with a winning initiative, while  14.exd4  Nxd4  15.Nxd4  Bxd4  just wins the game, as Bxc3 is threatened and  16.Bf3  is met with  16...Bxf2+!  Things can get ugly very soon for White if White does not pay attention. }
14. Bb2 Qd6
{ Again  15...d4!  was strong. After  16.Rad1  Qc7  17.exd4  Rad8  White's position just collapses. }
15. Rad1 Rad8
{ I probably do not need to say it again, but  15...d4!  would have been strong. }
16. Rfe1 d4
{ Finally Jonny Hector saw the light, and now gets a winning initiative. White's setup has been too passive. }
17. Ng5 Qc7
{ Getting out of the pin and defending f7 with devastating effect.  18.exd4  Nxd4  just loses, so White is in a world of trouble. }
18. Na4 dxe3 19. f3 Bf5
{ Black is up a powerful pawn which will be dominating the position. From here on, play is rather natural for Black. }
20. Rxd8 Nxd8 21. Nc5 Bxc5 22. bxc5 Qf4 23. Nh3 Qh4 24. Rf1 Bxh3 25. gxh3 Nh5
26. Qc3 Re6 27. Bd3 Nc6 28. Qe1 Qxh3 29. f4 e2
{ And White resigned, as  30.Bxe2  Rg6+  leads to mate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Shevchenko, Kirill vs. Warmerdam, Max, Terme Catez 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ Although this game was not necessarily a model game, I do think that it showed a pretty high level. I thought that it was also a good idea to show a game of myself in the model game section, as I can better explain the thought process of one of the players in this way. }
1. c4
{ My opponent thought that this would be a clever move order, but having the Schara Gambit planned for this game I did not really care. }
1... e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 8.
Qb3 Na6 9. e3
{ Up until this moment everything was still quite normal for me, but I could not really recall this move order, trying to get the knight to e2. }
9... Nc5 10. Qd1 Nce4
{ 10...Nfe4  is an improvement, as mentioned in chapter 5 @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. The point is that the queen will be able to make threats by playing Qh4 or Qf6. }
11. Nge2
{ 11.Bd2  would have been better this time, not allowing Black to ruin White's pawn structure with  Nxc3  , but still allowing the light-squared bishop to develop. White had to go  g3  eventually in the game now, but that weakens the light-squares quite a bit as White has also played  e3  . In the game I managed to take advantage of these light-squared weaknesses later on. }
11... Rc8
{ Here it was not entirely easy for me to see whether  11...Bb4  or  11...Rc8  was more accurate.  11...Bb4  feels more natural as we want to develop the minor pieces first. However, I was not sure what to think of  12.a3  Bxc3+  13.Nxc3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  . My understanding of these positions was not as good back then as it is now, as it actually looks super fine for Black. Black has a lead in development and a better pawn structure. White has the bishop pair, but the bishops are not that strong actually.   Still,  11...Rc8  is a very fine move. }
12. g3 Bb4
{ Inaccurate, as it is more clever to start with  12...Nxc3  13.Nxc3  Bb4  . This is because after  14.Bg2  the move  14...Rxc3  is possible. I only realized this after we had played 12...Bb4 13. Bg2, when I tried to make things connected to Rxc3 work. I did not manage, however, as for example  12...Bb4  13.Bg2  Nxc3  14.bxc3!  Rxc3  15.O-O!  gives back the pawn, but I am badly coordinated and will soon have to give back material.  13...Rxc3  does not work either, as I am losing material after  14.bxc3  Nxc3  15.Qd4! }
13. Bg2 Bb5
{ This was, however, a pleasant move to make. I realised that due to the light-squared weaknesses and all the pressure on the knights, I should still have good compensation in the endgame. }
14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. a3
{ This move makes sense, as it gets rid of the tension.  15.f3  was an alternative to try to achieve the same. }
15... Bxc3+ 16. Nxc3 Nxc3 17. bxc3
{ I am still down a pawn, and also gave up the bishop pair. However, White is still not able to castle, and the light-squares are quite weak. The isolated c-pawn does not help either. I had to see my next move in advance when playing 13... Bb5. }
17... Nd7 { Going after White's king before White is able to coordinate. } 18.
Rb1 Bc4
{ The bishop is best on c4, as Ba6 would allow Bxb7 with a tempo on my bishop. The bishop is also more flexible on c4, as it can switch diagonals. For example  19.Bf1?  can now be met with  19...Bd5! }
19. Bf3 Ne5 20. Be2
{ White is trying to castle by playing like this, but it costs a lot of time. }
20... Bd5
{ Slightly more accurate than  20...Nd3+  , as I lose a pawn after  21.Bxd3  Bxd3  22.Rxb7  . It should still be a comfortable draw however after for example  22...h5  .  20...Bd5 does allow White to castle, but it protects b7 and I will be able to trade my knight for White's bishop after Nf3+. }
21. O-O Nf3+ 22. Bxf3 Bxf3
{ I am still down a pawn, but due to White's isolated pawns and my superior minor piece I am definitely not worse here. From here on the game becomes less interesting for us as we have left the middle game. }
23. e4 Rd7 24. Re1 O-O 25. Be3 Bxe4
{ This meant that I get my pawn back and a draw should be the likely outcome. }
26. Rb4 f5 27. Bxa7 Ra8 28. Bc5 Rc7 29. Bd4 Rxa3 30. Rb5 h6 31. g4 Rf7 32. h3
Ra6 33. Kh2 Rg6 34. Re5 h5
{ I thought that my opponent was pushing a bit too much for the win and wanted to try to punish him with this move. However, I should have probably just kept on waiting. }
35. g5 h4 36. Ra5 Rd7 37. f3 Bxf3 38. Rxf5 Bc6 39. Re8+ Kh7 40. Ree5 Rdd6 41.
Rf7 Rd5 42. Rxd5 Bxd5 43. Rf5 Rd6 44. Rf4 Kg6 45. Rxh4 Kxg5 46. Rg4+ Kf5 47.
Kg3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Braun, Arik vs. Nisipeanu, Liviu Dieter, Bundesliga 2014"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is probably not a very important model game, as Black followed the plan of castling queenside which is usually quite bad. I did include it however, as I thought it would be nice to show how it could work out. If you are having fun in a blitz game you may as well try it. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6
{ 7...Nf6  is our move order, not allowing the position after  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qb3  .  In the past it did not matter so much, however, as Black was anyway intending to castle queenside and use this setup. }
8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qd1 Bc5 10. e3 Qe7 11. a3 O-O-O
{ 11...O-O  would likely have tranposed back to our notes, but Liviu-Dieter Nisipeanu was probably never intending to castle kingside anyway. White will now have to move the queen to deal with the discovered attack on the d-file in a nice way. }
12. Qc2 g5
{ This is the typical attacking plan that was connected to castling queenside. It was probably stronger to move the king to b8 first. }
13. Be2 g4 14. Nd2
{ Usually the knight should move to h4, where it is actually quite safe and blocks Black's h-pawn. }
14... Kb8
{ This move should be played at some point, as otherwise b4-b5 may become an issue. }
15. b4 Bb6
{ This is the right square for the bishop, and not d6. Black is intending to play h5-h4-g3 and then the e3-pawn will become a target. }
16. Nc4 Bc7 17. Bb2 Ne5
{ At some point Nb5 will become an issue, as it would pick up the dark-squared bishop. By playing Ne5, Black creates space for the bishop, and also gets rid of what is probably Black's worst minor piece. }
18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. O-O Rc8 { Creating counterplay on the queenside as well. }
20. Rac1 h5
{ The march of the h-pawn is finally coming and starts to become threatening. }
21. Rfd1 g3
{ A typical way to break through, as this is faster than starting by 21... h4.  Black simply threatens gxf2+, so White needs to respond on the kingside. }
22. f3
{ White was actually still doing okay after capturing on g3, or just playing Bf3. This, however, allows a tactic. }
22... h4
{ This move still wins, but Black will need to be precise after 23. h3. Black could have immediately won the game with  22...Bxc3  23.Bxc3  Qxe3+  24.Kh1  Ng4!!  25.fxg4  hxg4  followed by Rxh2#. }
23. h3 Bxc3
{ This finally wins back the sacrificed pawn, but Black could have gotten much more than that. It was however already difficult at this point. Black could have won with  23...Bxh3!  24.gxh3  Bd4!  when Black checkmates after for example  25.exd4  Qe3+  26.Kh1  g2+  27.Kh2  Qf2  28.Rg1  Qg3#  . }
24. Bxc3 Ba4 25. Qxa4 Qxe3+ 26. Kh1 Rxc3 27. Rxc3 Qxc3
{ Black has won back the pawn after a long tactically struggle, but the attack is gone as well. }
28. b5
{ This does nothing to prevent Nd5. Starting with  28.Bf1  would have, and was better. The position would still have been equal. }
28... Nd5 29. Qe4 Ne3 30. Rg1 f5
{ Black is just dominating now. White's light-squared bishop will have very little to do. }
31. Qe7 f4 32. Bd3 Qc7 33. Qf6 Rd8 34. Be2 Nd5
{ The knight is going to c3-d1-f2 to deliver checkmate. } 35. Qxh4 Nc3 36. Bc4
Nd1 37. Re1 Qd6 { Preparing Nf2+ followed by Qd4. } 38. Bf7 Rc8 39. Bd5 Nf2+
40. Kg1 Nd3
{ Followed by Qb6+ with an eventual smothered mate, so White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Khalesi, Parsa vs. Mousavi, Seyed Khalil, Shiraz 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6
{ Basically all the model games have started with  7...Nc6  , while  7...Nf6  should be preferred. As long as the games transpose back to our repertoire it should not matter too much. }
8. Qd1 { 8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qb3!  is how White punishes Black's move order. } 8...
Nf6 9. Nf3 Bc5 10. e3 Qe7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Rfd8 13. Qc2 Rac8
{ This is an interesting alternative to my recommendation, which was  13...Nb4  to immediately harass White's queen.  13...Rac8  seems objectively sound, and play could continue with  14.Rd1  Nb4  15.Qb1  g6  @@StartBracket@@preparing  Bf5  @@EndBracket@@  16.e4  Ng4  with a big mess, or 14. a3 as played in the game. }
14. a3 Bg4
{ This is usually not a move that should be played so early on. Very often we start by playing Ne5, and very often we move the bishop to c6 instead of g4. Now after  14...Bg4?!  15.h3  Bh5  16.Rd1  , Black would have struggled to keep the initiative.   14...Bd6  is an improvement, after which  15.Rd1  Ne5  16.Nd4  Neg4  should lead to a strong initiative for Black. Kamil Plichta recommends  14...Bd6  15.Bd2  for White in his Go for The Throat : 1.d4! Chessable course. After  15...Ne5  16.Nd4  the typical reply  16...Nc6  should annoy White a bit. He recommends  17.Rfe1  , but after either  17...Qe5  18.g3  Bg4  or  17...h6  with Qe5 on the next move we should have good counterplay. }
15. Bd2 { As Ne5 is coming, the bishop is quite vulnerable on d2. } 15... Ne5
16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Rae1 h5
{ A typical move, but even stronger was  17...Bf5!  , forcing  18.Qc1  after which White is quite passive. For example just  18...Bb6  followed by Ne4 leads to a great position. }
18. Bxg4 hxg4
{ An interesting choice by Black.  18...Nxg4  would seem more typical to me, threatening checkmate. After  19.g3  the attack can be continued with  19...h4  .  The point of 18...hxg4 is that it really limits White's kingside. In the long run Black will try to get a rook to the h-file, or play Qh5-Bd6 to force g3 and then play Nd7-Ne5 to get to the f3-square. }
19. f4 gxf3
{ This looks logical, and leads to a pleasant position as well as White's pawn structure will be ruined. White will also have a tough task ahead of defending their king.   However, even stronger seems to be  19...Qh5  , after which White has a very passive position full of weaknesses. }
20. Rxf3 Ng4 21. Rh3 g6
{ Black will now play Kg7 and Rh8 to keep the attack going. } 22. Qd1 Qe6
{ It is important to keep the knight on g4, as it is attacking e3 and h2. } 23.
Qe2 Bd6
{ Threatening  24.--  Bxh2+  25.Rxh2  Nxh2  26.Kxh2  Qd6+  followed by Qxd2. }
24. Bc1 Kg7
{ White had to play a passive move like @@StartFEN@@2rr2k1/pp3p2/3bq1p1/8/6n1/P1N1P2R/1P1BQ1PP/4R1K1 w - - 4 24@@EndFEN@@  24.Nb1  to be able to play Bc3 next. Now with Rh8 coming, the attack is way too strong and Black is basically already winning. }
25. Rh4 f5 26. Rf1 Rh8 27. Rxh8 Rxh8 28. h3 Qe5
{ What is always difficult about such positions is that White cannot play h3 and g3 at the same time and also keep both pawns defended by each other. }
29. Rf4 g5 30. Rxg4 fxg4 31. Qxg4
{ White has survived so far, but a hopeless position is ahead. } 31... Rf8 32.
Qd4 Kg6 33. Qxe5 Bxe5
{ And White simply resigned, without even being down material. The position is just hopeless due to the passive pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kipper, Jens vs. Kuijf, Marinus, Bundesliga 1998"]
[Result "*"]

{ Marinus Kuijf, former Dutch Champion, was often pioneering the Schara Gambit. Back then Black almost exclusively castled queenside, but Marinus showed good understanding in this game, castling kingside and showing the typical plans afterwards. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6
{ This was the way they would normally always proceed back in the days. We adopt the  7...Nf6  move order, as  7...Nc6  is inaccurate due to  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qb3  . }
8. e3 Nf6 9. Qd1 Bc5
{ Now we are back into our repertoire after Black has castled kingside. } 10.
Nf3 Qe7 { Flirting with the idea of castling queenside. } 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O
Rfd8 { 12...Ne5  is the extra option that I also covered in chapter  8. } 13.
a3 Ne5 14. b4 Bd6
{ 14...Nxf3+  15.Bxf3  Bb5  would maybe be my choice and is covered as my recommendation in chapter 8. However, objectively this move is also quite fine and the position stays in the more typical situation that we have in the Schara Gambit. }
15. Qc2 Rac8 16. Bb2 Nfg4
{ So far Marinus Kuijf was making normal moves, but this was the first time a decision had to be made.  16...Bc6  17.Nd4  Neg4  was also a typical way to continue the attack, but I actually quite like the decision to play 16...Nfg4. The idea is to play Nxf3+ and then take on h2. }
17. g3
{ White was perhaps not happy with  17.h3  Nxf3+  18.Bxf3  Nh2  ,  but 17.g3 weakens the light-squares quite a bit. Actually, after  18...Nh2  19.Bxb7  Nxf1  20.Bxc8  Nxe3  21.Qe4  White ensures equality due to having an extra pawn in exchange for the bishop pair.  @@StartFEN@@2rr2k1/pp1bqppp/3b4/8/1P4n1/P1N1PB1P/1BQ2PP1/R4RK1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Qe5  or  18...Bh2+  19.Kh1  Bb8  would have also been quite dangerous for White. }
17... Qf6
{ Putting pressure on f3 and c3, while the queen may also be able to switch to h6 to put pressure on h2. }
18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Rac1
{ This obvious move is actually a big mistake already. White should have gone for counterplay with  19.Rad1!  instead. After  19...Bxc3  20.Rxd7!  works out, but it was not easy to see. Black could instead keep the initiative with @@StartFEN@@2rr2k1/pp1b1ppp/5q2/4b3/1P4n1/P1N1P1P1/1BQ1BP1P/3R1RK1 b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...h5  . }
19... Nxh2 20. Kxh2 Qh4+
{ This gives away the win.  20...Bf5  21.Qb3  Qh4+  would have been winning. For example  22.Kg1  Bxg3  23.fxg3  Qxg3+  24.Kh1  Rc6  followed by Rh6 with checkmate.   After  20...Bf5  , the try  21.e4  also ends badly after  21...Rxc3!  22.Bxc3  Qh4+  23.Kg1  Bxg3  24.fxg3  Qxg3+  25.Kh1  Qh4+!  26.Kg1  Bxe4  after which Black wins the queen or White gets mated. }
21. Kg1 Bxg3 22. fxg3 Qxg3+ 23. Kh1 Qh3+ 24. Kg1 Qg3+ 25. Kh1 Rc6
{ Continuing the game. White is still okay, but has a tough task ahead. } 26.
Bh5 { The only move. } 26... Rh6 27. Qh2
{ This was the idea behind 26. Bh5. White is happy to give back one piece, as Black has actually sacrificed two. }
27... Qg5
{ 27...Bc6+  28.e4  Qg5  would have been a bit more accurate, not allowing Ne4. However, as we will see in the game, Black still has the initiative, even in the endgame. }
28. Ne4 Qxh5 29. Qxh5 Rxh5+ 30. Kg1 Bc6
{ White still has a tough task ahead. Black has two pawns already, and White's king is still vulnerable. }
31. Rcd1 Re8 32. Rf4 f5 33. Nf2
{ 33.Ng3  would have led to an unclear position after  33...Rh3  34.Nf1  Be4  . Black is quite active, but White has a lead in material. }
33... Rg5+ 34. Kf1 Rxe3
{ Winning a third pawn, and now Bb5+ or Bg2+ will win the game. } 35. Nd3 Rh3
{ 35...Bb5  would have immediately won. } 36. Rf2 Bb5 37. Ke2 Rgg3 38. Rc1 Re3+
39. Kd2 Rxd3+ 40. Kc2 Rdf3 41. Rxf3 Rxf3
{ The three extra pawns win the game. Marinus Kuijf played this game quite well, especially up until move 20 everything was just perfect basically. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Admiraal, Miguoel vs. Warmerdam, Max, The Netherlands 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6
{ This game does not feature the Schara Gambit, but after a novelty on move 5 that I introduced in this game the positions will become very similar. This game was also included in my Janowski course, as it is from the Janowski opening @@StartBracket@@  3...a6  @@EndBracket@@. Some of my analysis from back then for this game will remain the same. This game shows that such positions can also be reached from different openings, and that it is good to get a feeling for long term pawn sacrifices. }
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Qb3 Bd6
{ I had found this novelty about half a year before this game was played, and I was really happy to have finally get it on the board. It really messes with your opponent's mind - as the d5-pawn has been attacked twice you would think that Black needs to protect it. Instead of defending the d5-pawn, we are 'unprotecting' it once more by cutting off our queen as well. After White has taken on d5 and we push for c5, we will get the same structure as we have in the Schara Gambit. }
6. Qxd5 Nf6 7. Qb3 c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Now you can see the similarities between the Schara Gambit and this position. Most of the pieces are on the same squares and the structure is the same. Concretely speaking, the difference is that we have played a6 and White played Qb3. The line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.cxd5  cxd4  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  Nf6  8.Qd1  Bc5  is what I am comparing it to. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/5n2/3Q4/8/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qb3  is quite different, as we play  8...Na6  and Nc5 there and have a completely different setup. }
9. Nf3 Nc6 10. a3 O-O 11. Qc2 Re8
{ What is very similar here to the Schara Gambit is that we want White to play e3 before developing the dark-squared bishop. With the queen on c2 protecting the b2-pawn,  12.Bg5  Qb6  does not do so much here as it typically does in the Schara Gambit. Usually, we put our rook on d8, but it is quite well placed on e8 as well in these positions.   Since White has not committed to playing e3 yet, I thought that  11...b5  for the moment was still too slow as it allows  12.Bg5  . }
12. e3
{ After  12.Bg5  we can put White under pressure with  12...Bg4  , after which it is difficult for our opponent to play either e3 or g3. }
12... Qe7
{ Before I made the move b5, I first wanted to play Qe7 to protect our bishop on c5.  12...b5  would be allowing  13.Nxb5!  Usually, White's queen does not go to c2 so early and we do not have to take this tactic into account, but our queen is quite well placed on e7 anyway. }
13. Be2 b5 14. b4
{ An interesting plan that I had not seen before. Usually, White does not play Qc2 so early on. Instead, White usually finishes development with O-O and Bd2. It does make sense for White, however, to take space on the queenside with a tempo. Now if we want to know where to put our bishop, we need to keep in mind that our target is the white king once it has castled kingside. }
14... Bd6
{ We want this bishop to point towards h2 because we will start attacking soon. Because White has grabbed space on the queenside it will be difficult for us to play on that flank as our usual plan with Na5 has been stopped. }
15. O-O Bb7
{ This is one of the big differences between this gambit and the Schara Gambit. Usually our bishop is already on d7 in such positions, and we cannot play Bb7. However, we often intend to get the bishop to that diagonal by playing Ne5 and Bc6. Sometimes we even drop back the bishop to b7 from c6, as it is more secure over there. }
16. Bb2 Ne5
{ Opening up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop, while we are also trying to get rid of White's best defender of the king. We are threatening to take on f3 which would ruin White's pawn structure. }
17. Nd4
{ A natural response to the pressure on the knight, but now there are very few pieces defending the king. White's idea was to play Nf5 soon, to trade off some pieces. This plan is not fast enough as I was ready to create threats.   A much better move would have been  17.Qf5  ,  a typical computer move that is often suggested in the Schara Gambit positions as well. We can make a draw here with  17...Bc8  18.Qc2  Bb7  . }
17... Neg4
{ Our obvious threat is to take on h2 right now, but our less obvious one is actually more devastating.  18.--  Nxe3  is also a sneaky trick, as after  19.fxe3  Qxe3+  the knight on d4 will be hanging. }
18. Nf5 Bxh2+
{ We have won back our sacrificed pawn and it is clear that Black must be better. Our pieces are still attacking White's king, which has very few defenders. }
19. Kh1 Qc7
{ Not only does this pin the c3-knight, but we also have a very strong idea in mind that my opponent probably missed. It is a known idea from the isolated queen's pawn positions. }
20. Rac1
{ This does unpin the knight as now the queen is protected, however, my opponent has clearly missed the following move. White had to play  20.Bxg4  , but giving up the bishop pair does seem a little bit sad. }
20... Bg1
{ Both my g4-knight and the bishop are protecting the h2-square for my queen to go to and White can not take either piece. White has to block the diagonal but, as  21.Ng3  will be answered by  21...Bxf2  ,  f4 has to be played. }
21. f4 Bxe3
{ Now we are threatening to play  22.--  Nf2+  followed by Qxf4, so White is forced to go for the following line. I calculated that it was winning for Black so I went for Bxe3, but  @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/1bq2ppp/p4n2/1p3N2/1P3Pn1/P1N1P3/1BQ1B1P1/2R2RbK b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Nxe3  was also winning. }
22. Nd5 { An interesting resource. } 22... Qxc2 23. Nde7+ Kf8 24. Rxc2
{ White has managed to escape into an endgame being only a pawn down, but it is clear that something is wrong with White's position. }
24... Be4
{ The rook turns out to not have many squares to go to, and we also want to play Rxe7 after which we are up too much material for White to stay in the game. }
25. Rc7 Nf2+
{ Cutting off the defense of the f4-pawn. Now it is an easy conversion. } 26.
Kh2 Bxf4+ 27. g3 Bxc7 28. Nxg7 N6g4+
{ And I was simply up a full rook at this point, without any hope left for my opponent to save the game. It was an interesting game, but in general, I was happy that I got to play the novelty and then show the ideas behind it. It would feel a bit stupid to play a strong novelty and then lose the game like the idea was thrown away for nothing. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "So, Wesley vs. Grischuk, Alexander, Crypto Cup 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This chapter is meant to illustrate new ideas that were featured in recent games, to show how the Schara Gambit has changed. All the games that I have selected were from the years 2021 and 2022. These games are not model games, but I think it is also good to learn from mistakes. If you only see how great the Schara Gambit can be, you will not know when certain moves are mistakes.These games were not selected on their quality, or the result. They were selected because the Black players played a novelty that is important for the opening. You can skip this chapter if you would like to, but I wanted to give this as an extra service because I think that the Schara Gambit deserves it. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 Bd6 8.
Bg5 Nge7
{ This line was also featured in a lot of correspondence games in the years 2017-2018 by Dietmar Goehring. }
9. Qd2 h6 10. Rd1 hxg5 11. Qxd6 Qb6 12. Qa3 O-O
{ This was an important novelty that was introduced by Alexander Grischuk in May 2020 during the FTX Crypto Cup. Up until then, the correspondence games only featured  12...Be6  ,  and that is also the move that David Martinez covered in his 1.d4 Chessable course. With 12...O-O Black remains flexible, as Black can now still choose between operating with Nb4 or Be6 next. }
13. e3 { 13.Nf3  seems to me to be the more critical approach. } 13... Nb4 14.
Qa4 Bf5 { This is why the bishop was left on c8 on move 12. } 15. e4 Be6
{ White would rather have the pawn on e3, but had no choice. With the pawn on e4 the dark-squares are typically weakened. }
16. a3 Na2 17. Nxa2 Bxa2 18. Qb5 Qe6 19. Bd3 Rfd8
{ Up until here everything was covered in chapter 2, where I propose the improvement  19...Ng6  - see the variation. Grischuk now finds it difficult to keep the initiative going and ends up in a worse endgame. }
20. Ne2 Nc6 21. O-O Ne5
{ So far Grischuk is playing well, making use of the akward bishop on d3. He is threatening to win the game with the surprising move  22.--  b6!  This move prepares to win material with a6, not allowing Qxb7. }
22. Nc1 Nxd3
{ This move was fine, but he could have opted for  22...a6  as well. This would either force White to allow a draw with  23.Qxb7  Rdb8  24.Qc7  Rc8  , or allow the knight to be dominated after  23.Qb4  Nxd3  24.Rxd3  Bc4  25.Rxd8+  Rxd8  . }
23. Nxa2 a6
{ It is difficult to say for me whether Alexander was ambitious at this point or not, but he probably was. Otherwise he could have gone for  23...Nxf2  , winning back the pawn and leading to a major piece position which should be rather safe. }
24. Qxb7 Nf4 { Black is now threatening to win the game with  25.--  Qg4  . }
25. Nc3
{ I have to say that Wesley So has been playing quite well so far, not giving in to the initiative. He would have been a bit worse after 19...Ng6, but except for that he has been playing quite accurately. Alexander should have opted to make a draw with either  25...Qg4  26.Rxd8+  Rxd8  27.g3  Nh3+  28.Kg2  Nf4+  now, or even  25...Nxg2  . }
25... Rdb8
{ From here on, the game starts to go badly for Alexander. He does win back the pawn, but the endgame is slightly nasty. }
26. Qd7 Rxb2 27. Qxe6 fxe6
{ 27...Nxe6  should have been preferred. Although it allows White to get the d5-square, it keeps the kingside structure together. }
28. g3 { White is definitely taking over from here on. } 28... Ng6 29. Rd6 Kf7
30. Rd7+ Kf6 31. Rc7 Rd8
{ Alexander is now back in the game. Wesley should have gone for @@StartFEN@@r7/5kp1/p2Rp1n1/6p1/4P3/P1N3P1/1r3P1P/5RK1 w - - 3 30@@EndFEN@@  30.Rc6  to keep control due to the pressure on a6. }
32. Rc6 Kf7
{ Too passive.  32...Ne5  33.Rxa6  Rdd2  should have been preferred, with counterplay due to the active rooks. }
33. Rc7+ Kf6 34. Rc6 Kf7 { Again,  34...Ne5! } 35. Na4
{ This is why Kf7 was wrong. White is now going to pick up all the pawns with Nc5. }
35... Re2 36. Nc5 Ne5 37. Rxa6 Nf3+ 38. Kg2 g4 39. Ra7+
{ As it was a rapid game, the quality of these top players was not as high as we would expect from them. They were probably quite low on time at this point.  39.h3  or  39.Nxe6  would have kept a winning advantage.  39...Rh8  was never a problem anyway as  40.h4  could always be played. }
39... Kf6 40. Ra6 Rdd2
{ 40...Ng5  keeping the e6-pawn would still have been within drawing margins. Now Black is just down too many pawns. }
41. Nxe6 Kf7 42. Nf4 Rxe4 43. h3 Ne1+ 44. Rxe1
{ 44.Kh1  would have been better objectively, but this decision forces a very difficult endgame. }
44... Rxe1 45. hxg4 Ra2
{ 45...g5  followed by Re5 would have been the right defensive setup. } 46. g5
Kf8 47. g6 Re8 48. Ne6+ Kg8 49. Ra7 Kh8 50. Nd4 Rf8 51. Nf5 Rb2 52. g4 Rg8 53.
Re7 Rb6 54. Re1 Rgb8 55. Rh1+ Kg8 56. Rd1
{ This actually gives away the win.  56.Ne7+  Kf8  57.Nd5  was an immediate game over. }
56... Kf8
{ Giving Wesley another chance to find Ne7+. A move like  56...Re8  would have been a draw. }
57. Rh1 Kg8 58. Ne7+ { And this time Wesley does manage to find it. } 58... Kf8
59. Nd5 { With either Nxb6 or Rh8 incoming. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Grischuk, Alexander, Zagreb 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ We are going to be following chapter 5 for quite a long time in this game. It is clear that Alexander Grischuk had done his homework in the Schara Gambit. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qb3 Na6 9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qd1
{ This is the solid alternative to the more critical  10.Qc2  .  It immediately allows 10... Nce4, but avoids any pin on the c-file. }
10... Nce4 11. e3 Bb4 12. Bd2 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Qa5 15. Qd4 Rc8 16.
Qb4 Qc5 17. Bd3
{ 17.Qxc5  seems more critical to me. This just allows Black to get back the pawn. }
17... Qxc3+ 18. Qxc3 Rxc3 19. Kd2 Ra3 20. Rhb1 b6 21. Rb3 Ra5 22. Nd4 Ke7
{ Up until this point it is all mentioned in the corresponding chapter - see the variation. Alexander played pretty much perfect up until this point, and the ensuing endgame is quite interesting. It is a question whether Black can start to push this. }
23. a4 Rc8 24. f3
{ Black has now developed all the pieces, and a decision has to be made. White is soon going to be playing e4, and the knight on f6 will become a slight issue. }
24... Ne8
{ Rerouting the knight to d6.  24...Rc7  would have been an interesting alternative, threatening 25...Rxa4 as a7 is now protected. White has to deal with this pawn, and  25.Rb4  would be met with  25...Nd5  . The alternative  25.Rba3  looks passive, and now Black can go for  25...Ne8  followed by Nd6. }
25. Rb4
{ Since Nd5 is no longer on the horizon, the rook is pretty safe on b4. } 25...
Nd6 26. e4 h5
{ Now  27.Nb3  Rg5  28.g3  would have been interesting, followed by f4-e5. }
27. h4 { 26...g5 would have also prevented this move. } 27... g5 28. hxg5 Rxg5
{ Black has achieved better control over the dark-squares now, but the structure has been damaged. }
29. Bf1 Rgc5 30. Ke3 f5
{ This is a way to try to kill the game, trading off even more pawns. A draw was soon made. }
31. exf5 Nxf5+ 32. Nxf5+ Rxf5 33. Bd3 Re5+ 34. Kf2 Rcc5 35. Be4 Bc6
{ Going for a rook endgame, in which for sure nothing will happen at this level. }
36. Bxc6 Rxc6 37. Ra2 Rcc5 38. Rd2 Rc6 39. Ra2 Rcc5 40. Rd2 Rc6 41. Ra2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Holm, Kristian Stuvik vs. Tari, Aryan, Warsaw Wch Rapid 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qb3 Na6 9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2 Rc8 11. e3 Bd6
{ This move was a novelty in over the board chess at this point, although it had been used online already. The main move is  11...Nce4  , but the alternative  11...Bd6  is also covered in chapter 6. }
12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Qe7 14. Rd1 a6
{ We were still following my recommendation, but here Aryan Tari follows the wrong path. After both 14.Rd1 and 14.Bd2,  14...g6  should be played to get in Bf5 as soon as possible. See the theory section for more details. }
15. Bd2 b5 16. a3
{ 16.Be1  was perhaps a slight improvement, trying to meet  16...b4  with  17.Nd5  . }
16... g6
{ Only now does Black play g6, but White is more comfortable playing Nd4 by now. That is because the bishop on d2 is already protecting c3, so Ne4 will not do as much. }
17. Nd4 Nfe4 18. Be1
{ White is now comfortably meeting Nfe4 with this move. Perhaps 17...Ne6 was a better plan, focusing more on the kingside instead of the queenside. }
18... Nxc3 19. Qxc3 { Not allowing  19.Bxc3  Ne4  . } 19... Be5
{ This is quite a slow move, and the bishop does not belong on this square. By putting the bishop on e5, Black does not have the possibility to play Qe5 anymore.   Something like  19...Rfd8  followed by h5 should have been preferred. }
20. Bf3
{ The bishop does not do so much on this square so much in general, and is actually quite exposed. Aryan Tari immediately starts to make use of this. }
20... Qh4 { Hoping for  21.g3  Qf6  . } 21. h3
{ Not weakening the light-squares. @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/3bqp1p/p5p1/1pn1b3/3N4/P1Q1PB2/1P3PPP/R2RB1K1 b - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qf6  should have been preferred, as the inclusion of h3 should help White. }
21... Qf6 22. b4
{ Black was intending to play Ne6 anyway, so this move does not really help White. Instead, getting out of the pin with something like  22.Qd2  should have been preferred. }
22... Ne6 23. Qd3 Rfd8 { The pressure starts to build up. } 24. Rac1
{ This loses material to a trick. } 24... Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Nxd4 26. exd4 Qf4
{ This is why 24.Rac1 was wrong. Black is now either going to mate White with Qh2+, or take the rook on c1. }
27. Bd2 Qh2+ 28. Kf1 Bf5 29. Qb3 Bxd4 30. Bd5 Rxd5
{ A nice finishing touch, intending to checkmate White with  31.Qxd5  Bd3+  32.Ke1  Qg1#  . }
31. Rc8+ Kg7 32. Bh6+ Kxh6 33. Qxd5 Bxc8 34. Qxd4
{ White is just down a piece here. } 34... Qh1+ 35. Ke2 Qxg2 36. Qh4+ Kg7 37.
Qd4+ f6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Shankland, Samuel L vs. Carlsen, Magnus, Wijk aan Zee 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is basically the main line of chapter 6. } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 8. Qb3 Na6
{ It is interesting to note that from this move on Magnus starts to take quite some time on each move. He must still have been in book at this point, but it is a habit of Magnus to operate like this. He did it in his match against Nepomniatchi quite often, even when he was clearly still able to recall what the best move was. He seems to like to think about the position once more over the board and not give his opponents a clue about when he is exactly out of book. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2 Rc8 11. e3 Nce4 12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd5 14. O-O Nxc3 15.
Bb2 Bb4 16. Bxc3
{ Sam Shankland was still going for the critical line up to this point, but kind of bails out at this moment. Both  16.Qb3  and  16.Ne5  seem more critical to me, which are both covered in the chapter - see here for 16. Qb3 and here for 16. Ne5. }
16... Bxc3 17. Rab1 { Other rook moves were also possible. } 17... Bf6
{ This is the moment we stopped analysing in chapter 6. Black has reached a fine position, and is soon able to finish development with O-O. The bishop pair can give Black some hope to play for an advantage in the future. }
18. Qe2 Rc7
{ Protecting b7 and d7. Shankland was clearly intending to play e4-e5-e6, so having the rook protect the 7th rank is quite useful, in comparison to  18...b6  . }
19. e4 O-O 20. e5 Be7 21. Nd4
{ Still pushing for e6. Sam wants to go for an opposite-coloured bishop position, where he should be comfortable. }
21... Bc5 22. e6 Bxe6 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. Qxe6+ Kh8
{ Due to the missing f-pawn it might seem like Black's king is a little bit unsafe, but it was different in the game. The f2-pawn is actually a nice target, and White needs to be somewhat accurate to keep the game equal. }
25. Qh3 h6 26. Qg3 Rd7
{ Magnus set a sneaky trap for Sam here to fall for, which Sam mentioned on his Twitter.  27.Rxb7  seems appealing, and maybe even leading to a good position for Black. The idea is to meet  27...Rxb7  with  28.Qg6  , and  27...Rxd3  with  28.Qxg7#  . Black can anyway make a draw with  27...Rxf2  , but has even better. After  27...Bxf2+!  28.Rxf2  Rxb7  29.Qg6  , there is  29...Rb1+!!  30.Bxb1  Qd1+  31.Rf1  Qxf1#  .  It was at this point that Sam was probably starting to feel slightly uncomfortable, as Magnus' pieces are starting to activate and go after f2. }
27. Rb3 Rf6 { Preventing any future Qg6. } 28. h3 b6 29. Be2 Rd2
{ Probably not the most ambitious, as it allows White to trade rooks with 30. Rd3. Something like  29...Qe7  would have kept more pressure, intending to meet  30.Rd3?!  with  30...Bd6  . }
30. Rd3 Rxd3 31. Bxd3
{ It is difficult to say why Sam did not just play  31.Qxd3  ,  offering a trade of queens. The f-file can soon be blocked with Bf3. }
31... Qd6
{ Magnus missed an opportunity to start pushing with  31...Qd5!  here. The queen simply attacks a2 and intends to meet  32.a3  or  32.a4  with  32...Qb3  winning the pawn. What was probably missed is that after  @@StartFEN@@7k/p5p1/1p3r1p/2bq4/8/3B2QP/P4PP1/5RK1 w - - 1 32@@EndFEN@@  32.Bb1  Black can play  32...Rxf2+!  33.Rxf2  Qd1+  34.Kh2  Qxb1!  White will have to give back the exchange and suffer in a queen endgame. }
32. Qxd6
{ This of course led to a quick draw due to the opposite-coloured bishops. }
32... Rxd6 33. Rd1 g5 34. Kf1 Kg7 35. Bc2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Berkes, Ferenc vs. Tabatabaei, Mohammad Amin, World Cup 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qd1 Bc5 9. Nf3 O-O 10. a3
{ One of the critical directions, as  10...Nc6  was supposed to be bad. } 10...
Nc6
{ The alternative  10...Qc7  is also playable, but it is nice to see that this move was played.  10...Nc6  was a novelty until this game, although it does transpose to a number of games from a different move order. }
11. Bf4 Qb6 12. e3 Rfd8
{ Although this move is quite interesting, Amin probably found it difficult to recall his notes here. My recommendation of the novelty  12...Nh5  seems to be completely fine. }
13. Nd2
{ 13.Be2!  was more critical, intending to meet  13...Bh3  with  14.Nd2!  Bxg2  15.Rg1  ,  after which Black is in a lot of trouble. This is quite difficult to realize I have to say, and it is odd to give up the g2 pawn like this. The problem is that the queen on b6 has very few squares, and b4 or Na4 is coming.Black should instead play  13...Bf5  14.Qc1  14...Be7  followed by Ne4 and Bf6 with decent compensation. }
13... Be6 14. Qc2 Bd6
{ This trade makes little sense, as we are fighting for the initiative. Amin probably did not see a good way how to deal with the threat of Na4. The engine spits out  14...Bd4!?  , but that is a bit inhuman. Instead, something like  14...Be7  followed by Nd5 and Bf6 would also give good compensation. The point is that  15.Na4?  is actually not an issue, as Black is just winning after  15...Qa5  16.b4?  Nxb4  17.axb4  Bxb4  . This is actually quite typical and something we have seen in the corresponding chapter as well. }
15. Bg5
{ Not going for the exchanges is rather odd for White as well. White would have had a great position after  15.Bxd6  Rxd6  16.Nc4  , forcing even more exchanges. Probably both players thought  16...Bxc4  17.Bxc4  Rad8  would give compensation, but after  18.Rd1!  trading one pair of rooks it is nowhere to be found. }
15... Be5 { Now Black has a pleasant position again. } 16. Rd1 h6
{ 16...Bg4  would have been quite annoying for White to meet. } 17. Bxf6 Bxf6
18. Be2 Rac8 19. O-O Na5
{ It was better to start with  19...Bxc3  , forcing  20.bxc3  anyway. } 20.
Nde4 Be7
{ Too passive. The bishop should have kept pressure with  20...Be5  . } 21.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1
{ Now Black will find it difficult to find compensation. The bishop pair gives some, but the bishops are not as active as they could be. The rest of the game is basically Amin fighting for the draw. }
22... Rxd1+ 23. Nxd1 Qd8 24. Ndc3 a6 25. Qd2 Nb3 26. Qxd8+ Bxd8 27. Kf1
{ 27.Bd1!  would have been nasty, intending  27...Na5  28.Nc5  . } 27... f5 28.
Ng3 g6 29. Ke1 Nc1 30. Bf1 Bf6
{ By now Amin is getting some pressure on the queenside, with Na2 incoming. }
31. Kd1 Na2 32. Nge2 Nxc3+ 33. Nxc3 Kf7 34. Be2 Ke7 35. Bf3 b6
{ White is still a bit better, but it is difficult for White to make progress due to the pressure of the bishop pair. Black should be comfortably making a draw in such situations typically, and Amin had no issues in the game as well. }
36. Kc2 Kd6 37. g3 a5 38. Ne2 Kc5 39. Nf4 Bf7 40. Nd3+ Kd6 41. b3 Be8 42. h3 g5
43. g4 Bg6 44. Be2 fxg4
{ This gives White a passed pawn, but it is rather difficult to advance. Black is also ready to trade on d3 and make a draw in the resulting opposite coloured bishop endgame. }
45. hxg4 Be7 46. Kc3 Bxd3
{ Usually only one pawn extra is not enough to put pressure in opposite-coloured bishop endgames, and a draw was soon agreed. }
47. Bxd3 Ke5 48. b4 axb4+ 49. axb4 Kd5 50. Bf1 Bf6+ 51. Kd3 Ke5 52. Kc4 Be7 53.
Bg2 Bf8 54. Bf3 Be7 55. Kb5 Bf8 56. Kc4 *

