[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Salem, Saleh vs. Tari, Aryan, Warsaw Wch Rapid 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qd1 Bc5 9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3 Qe7 11. Be2 Nc6 12. O-O Ne5
{ This was the first time this idea was introduced, with Magnus Carlsen following later on. }
13. Bd2 Rad8
{ Usually the setup of our rooks is either Rac8 and Rfd8 or Rac8 and Rfe8, but not Rad8 and Rfe8. White can now safely play  14.Qc2  ,  or 16. Qc2 as in the game. }
14. Nd4 Nc6 15. Nf3 Ne5
{ The typical repetition happened, but Salem intends to fight for a win in this game. }
16. Qc2 { Making use of the fact that Aryan Tari has gone Rad8. } 16... b5
{ This is not as threatening without a rook on c8. } 17. a3 Bd6
{ Too slow. Something like  17...Bc6  or  17...Rfe8  should have been played. White is now able to play Nd4 followed by Nf5 or Ne4. }
18. Nd4 a6 19. Nf5
{ 19.Ne4  was even better, but this also looks quite appealing for White as it wins the bishop pair. }
19... Bxf5 20. Qxf5 Bxa3
{ This temporarily wins a pawn, but a6 is about to drop as well. This move only activates the a1-rook and weakens the b-pawn. }
21. Bc1 Bd6 22. Rxa6
{ Due to the bishop pair, extra pawn and White's pieces becoming active, White is more or less winning already. }
22... b4 23. Nb5 Bb8
{ 23...Bc5  was better to at least control the d4-square. Black is not really having attacking chances anymore, so the bishop does not do that much on b8. }
24. Nd4 Rd5 25. Qh3 Ne4 26. f4
{ Kicking away the knight, but the solid move  26.g3  was even stronger, intending to play Qg2 next. }
26... Nd7
{ This just loses material,  26...Ng6  would have kept the game going. } 27.
Nf5
{ With Bc4 incoming this position is now just lost. For example  27...Qd8  28.Bc4  Rc5  29.Qg4  g6  30.Rxg6+!  +- }
27... Qc5 28. Rc6 { 28...Qxc6  loses to  29.Ne7+  . } 28... Qa5 29. Ne7+ Kh8
30. Ra6
{ Black could have also just taken the rook immediately, but this is slightly more accurate. }
30... Qc5 31. Nxd5 Qxd5 32. Rd1
{ A very good game by Saleh Salem, and things seem to have gone wrong for Aryan Tari when he started to put his pieces on the wrong squares early on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Le, Quang Liem vs. Carlsen, Magnus, Airthings Masters 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ The current match situation was such that Magnus would win it with a draw. It is interesting that he chose to play the Schara Gambit in order to get a draw. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qd1 Bc5 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. e3 O-O 11. Be2 Qe7 12. O-O Ne5
{ Magnus, who possibly spent time on the Schara Gambit in his World Championship Match preparation, was aware of this move. }
13. Nd4 Nc6
{ Magnus of course does not mind the draw, as it would guarantee match victory. }
14. a3 a5
{ This is not a very typical move in the Schara Gambit. The inclusion of a3-a5 should favour White as it weakens the b5 square. Le tries to make use of this later on.   In the chapter I am recommending  14...Rfd8  ,  which actually transposes to our notes of 12... Rfd8. }
15. b3 Rad8
{ This time Rad8 is a fine move, although Rfd8 was equally fine. Black is anyway not going to play on the c-file anymore especially as b5 is difficult to achieve as Magnus has played a5 already. }
16. Ncb5 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4
{ This either forces exd4 which gives White an isolated pawn, or Qxd4 after which Black has a nice initiative. }
18. Qxd4
{ 18.exd4  was objectively better, but after  18...Rfe8  19.Re1  Bb5  20.Be3  Bxe2  Black does not have much to worry about due to the good knight bad bishop situation after Black has installed the knight on d5. }
18... Bb5 { Getting back the bishop pair. } 19. Qb2 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 Ne4
{ This was the position that Magnus had in mind when playing 17... Bxd4. The point is that  21.Bb2?  is met with  21...Rd2  ,  winning a piece. Although a lot of minor pieces have been exchanged, the pieces that White is left with are all passive. }
21. a4
{ Trying to activate the bishop on a3, but it will not do very much over there. }
21... Rfe8 22. Ba3 Qe6
{ Magnus is still dominating the position, especially as  23.Rfd1  or  23.Rad1  is met by  23...Nc3  .  Otherwise Rd2 is coming. }
23. b4 Rd2 24. Qb5
{ White was already drifting, but Magnus now has a killing blow.  24.Qf3  should have been preferred, but Black has a pleasant position after  24...b6  . }
24... Nxf2
{ A typical sacrifice, and one that should immediately win the game. After  25.Rxf2  Rxf2  26.Kxf2  Qxe3+  27.Kf1  ,  27...Qf4+  28.Kg1  Qd4+  picks up the rook. }
25. Bc1 Nh3+
{ The winning move, although Magnus used it to make a draw to secure match victory.  26.gxh3  Qxe3+  27.Kh1  Qe4+  28.Kg1  Qg2#  is just mate. }
26. Kh1 { The only move to stay alive, for now. } 26... Nf2+
{ Now  26...Rxg2!  27.Kxg2  Qg4+  28.Kh1  Qe4+  or  27.Qxe8+  Qxe8  28.Kxg2  Ng5  would have won, and even  26...Rc2  would be winning. However, with the match situation it is understandable that Magnus settled for a draw. I am sure that he normally would have finished off the game here. }
27. Kg1 Nh3+ 28. Kh1 Nf2+ 29. Kg1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Recent Games"]
[Black "Anton Guijarro, David vs. Van Foreest, Jorden, Carlsen Invitational 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This was the first time that Jorden played the Schara Gambit in tournament practice, and it must have attracted attention as other strong players followed soon. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qd1 Bc5 9. e3 O-O 10. Nf3 Qe7 11. Be2 Rd8 12. Qc2 Nc6 13. a3 Rac8
{ My recommendation would be  13...Ne5  here, transposing to our notes after  14.O-O  .  However, as mentioned in the Khalesi-Mousavi game from the model games chapter, this is quite playable as well. }
14. O-O Bd6 15. Bd2 Ne5 16. Rad1
{ Up until here Jorden was making the right moves, but he found it difficult to continue the initiative in the right way. }
16... Bc7
{ This prematurely gets the bishop out of the way, intending to meet  17.Nd4  with  17...Nc6  to avoid a fork with 18. Nf5. However, the bishop is usually not going to this square.   Instead,  16...Nfg4  should have been played, an idea we also saw in the Kipper-Kuijf game. The engine however, comes up with an even stronger idea of  16...Nxf3+  17.Bxf3  Bb5!  making use of the pin. After  18.Rfe1  Bd3  it is Black for choice due to the dominant position. }
17. Bc1 h5
{ This move is quite typical, but should probably be played once there is no knight on f3 anymore. White can now get a great position by playing  18.Ng5!  followed by f4, making use of the hole on g5 that Black just created. }
18. Nd4 Nc6 19. h3
{ This slow move allows Black to obtain a fine position. David probably did not see a good way to meet Nxd4 followed by Qe5. The best move was actually to return with  19.Nf3  and go for the Ng5 idea. }
19... Nxd4 20. Rxd4 Qe5
{ Now White has to weaken the kingside quite a lot with f4. } 21. f4 Qe7
{ The pawn on f4 will ensure Black long term compensation due to the weakened king. The bishop is about to come to b6 to put pressure on e3. }
22. Bf3 Bb6 23. Rb4
{ An odd square for the rook. David was intending to meet  23...Bxe3+  with  24.Bxe3  Qxe3+  25.Qf2  ,  trying to trade off the queens after which the rook on b4 does make sense. Jorden had a better idea however. }
23... Bc6
{ Understanding that Black does not immediately need to win back the pawn. }
24. Bxc6 Rxc6
{ The light squares have now been weakened, and the rook on b4 looks odd. } 25.
Kh1
{ Now Black is able to grab the initiative and get a pleasant position. In general the king would have been better on h2, as now  25...h4!  followed by Nh5-Ng3 would have been pretty strong. }
25... Ba5 { This also leads to a pleasant position. } 26. Ra4 Bxc3 27. bxc3
{ Black should be a bit better due to White's poor pawn structure and passive bishop on c1. }
27... b5 28. Rb4 Qc5
{ Although b5 and Qc5 were not necessarily the best moves, they did set up a nice trick that David fell for. He would have been okay now after  29.Qe2!  a6  30.e4!  finally activating the bishop. }
29. a4
{ Sometimes these things happen in rapid and blitz, but you would not expect this to happen to a strong player such as David. }
29... Qxb4 { Wins the rook and the game. } *

